WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.480
[Amit Varma]: During this episode, I was moved by something that my guest said. He spoke about how awkward

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:14.880
[Amit Varma]: he felt when his father tried to hug him. And that reminded me of my own father. In

00:00:14.880 --> 00:00:18.920
[Amit Varma]: his last years before he died, I felt that he was opening up in ways that neither of

00:00:18.920 --> 00:00:23.640
[Amit Varma]: us were used to. Once when I visited him in Chandigarh, as I was leaving, about to get

00:00:23.640 --> 00:00:28.880
[Amit Varma]: into my taxi outside the house, he opened his arms for a hug. It was an awkward moment.

00:00:28.880 --> 00:00:33.400
[Amit Varma]: I was both happy and moved, but I hid the emotion. On one trip home, he even thanked

00:00:33.400 --> 00:00:38.320
[Amit Varma]: me for coming, which was also out of character because he was always so blase about it. When

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:43.440
[Amit Varma]: episode 200 of the show came out, which is basically a long interview of me by my guest,

00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:47.880
[Amit Varma]: he actually said he was proud of me, which was stunningly expressive, given his past

00:00:47.880 --> 00:00:53.120
[Amit Varma]: record of reticence of being a hard man. It's a regret I have that I didn't peel back past

00:00:53.120 --> 00:00:57.800
[Amit Varma]: all those layers, both his layers and mine, while he was still here. Maybe if I had heard

00:00:57.800 --> 00:01:02.600
[Amit Varma]: this episode, I would have. Here's the thing. I have done many episodes where I have discussed

00:01:02.600 --> 00:01:06.940
[Amit Varma]: feminism and the lives that women lead. Indeed, the title of this episode follows on from

00:01:06.940 --> 00:01:13.280
[Amit Varma]: episode 259, The Loneliness of the Indian Women. At this point in time, in 2022, anyone

00:01:13.280 --> 00:01:17.720
[Amit Varma]: listening to this show understands the many layers of oppression that women live with

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:22.760
[Amit Varma]: and normalize and that we must fight against. We have language for what happens to them,

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:27.840
[Amit Varma]: phrases like mansplaining and gaslighting and so on and on. We have frames to explain it.

00:01:27.840 --> 00:01:33.600
[Amit Varma]: But the thing is, it isn't just women who are victims of patriarchy. Men are also diminished

00:01:33.600 --> 00:01:38.120
[Amit Varma]: by it. They are trapped in roles, in grooves laid out for them. Here's what it means to

00:01:38.120 --> 00:01:43.600
[Amit Varma]: be a man, to be a provider, to be a father, to be a son. You play that role, you get the

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:49.600
[Amit Varma]: job done, you don't cry at movies, don't show emotion, don't be a wuss. And many of us often

00:01:49.600 --> 00:01:55.060
[Amit Varma]: get with the program and don't question what being male does to us. We have no language

00:01:55.060 --> 00:02:00.760
[Amit Varma]: to describe this. We keep our emotions bottled up inside us, not expressing them to others,

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:05.420
[Amit Varma]: not even expressing them to ourselves. So what my guest speaks at length about in this

00:02:05.420 --> 00:02:10.600
[Amit Varma]: episode should not be a surprise. The loneliness of the Indian man, the mental health problems

00:02:10.600 --> 00:02:15.480
[Amit Varma]: that young people throughout this country are having to confront, and what this does

00:02:15.480 --> 00:02:20.900
[Amit Varma]: to our society. This is all unseen. And there's a big lesson here. Men who call themselves

00:02:20.900 --> 00:02:25.600
[Amit Varma]: feminists like me, need to not only think about how they look at women, but also how

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:31.160
[Amit Varma]: they look at themselves. Their kindness has to go in that direction as well. Only kindness

00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:35.520
[Unknown]: can save us.

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:40.720
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:48.080
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:02:48.080 --> 00:02:51.840
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guest today is Nikhil Taneja, who trained as an

00:02:51.840 --> 00:02:56.200
[Amit Varma]: engineer, began working life as a journalist at Hindustan Times, went on to MTV and to

00:02:56.200 --> 00:03:00.860
[Amit Varma]: Yash Raj Films, where he was a general manager at the age of 30. Then he was crippled by

00:03:00.860 --> 00:03:05.840
[Amit Varma]: anxiety and decided to confront his mental health issues. And he realized that many of

00:03:05.840 --> 00:03:11.560
[Amit Varma]: the problems he faced came straight out of his being a man. He quit his job, did therapy,

00:03:11.560 --> 00:03:16.680
[Amit Varma]: and later started Yuva, an organization that makes content, builds communities, and carries

00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:22.120
[Amit Varma]: out research that's meant to understand and empower young Indians everywhere. Now, I think

00:03:22.120 --> 00:03:28.000
[Amit Varma]: of my episodes as being stimulating conversations, deep dives akin to oral histories. And this

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:33.600
[Amit Varma]: episode is all of them. But it's also an episode that can change lives. Something I felt about

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:38.560
[Amit Varma]: my episode with Shrayana as well. We discuss a growing loneliness in our connected world.

00:03:38.560 --> 00:03:43.800
[Amit Varma]: We discuss anxiety and mental health. We discuss the immense power of storytelling. What Nikhil

00:03:43.800 --> 00:03:48.280
[Amit Varma]: has done with it is so unique and inspiring. We talk about the kindness project and initiative

00:03:48.280 --> 00:03:53.520
[Amit Varma]: of Nikhil's and why most of all, we need to be kind to ourselves. So do listen and do

00:03:53.520 --> 00:03:59.160
[Amit Varma]: share it with anyone you think may be interested. I know it's a long episode, but it contains

00:03:59.160 --> 00:04:02.960
[Amit Varma]: multitudes. Before we get there, though, let's take a quick commercial break even though

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:07.800
[Amit Varma]: what the commercials are me only. That's how it is.

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:11.360
[Amit Varma]: Have you always wanted to be a writer but never quite gotten down to it? Well, I'd love

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:16.040
[Amit Varma]: to help you. Since April 2020, I've taught 20 cohorts of my online course, The Art of

00:04:16.040 --> 00:04:20.480
[Amit Varma]: Clear Writing. An online community has now sprung up of all my past students. We have

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:25.400
[Amit Varma]: workshops, a newsletter to showcase the work of students, and vibrant community interaction.

00:04:25.400 --> 00:04:29.720
[Amit Varma]: In the course itself, through four webinars spread over four weekends, I share all I know

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:33.920
[Amit Varma]: about the craft and practice of clear writing. There are many exercises, much interaction,

00:04:33.920 --> 00:04:38.360
[Amit Varma]: a lovely and lively community at the end of it. The course costs rupees 10,000 per GST

00:04:38.360 --> 00:04:43.160
[Amit Varma]: or about $150 and is a monthly thing. So if you're interested, head on over to register

00:04:43.160 --> 00:04:48.720
[Amit Varma]: at indiancut.com slash clear writing. That's indiancut.com slash clear writing. Being a

00:04:48.720 --> 00:04:53.920
[Amit Varma]: good writer doesn't require God given talent, just the willingness to work hard and a clear

00:04:53.920 --> 00:04:59.920
[Amit Varma]: idea of what you need to do to refine your skills. I can help you.

00:04:59.920 --> 00:05:06.720
[Amit Varma]: Nikhil, welcome to the scene in the unseen. Thank you for having me Amit. Yeah, I've been

00:05:06.720 --> 00:05:12.800
[Amit Varma]: thinking of inviting you for a long time though, got down to it fairly recently, but I'm actually

00:05:12.800 --> 00:05:17.720
[Amit Varma]: glad that I didn't invite you say two years ago, because the show was much shorter than

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:22.480
[Amit Varma]: and I just feel that you're a guest who's tailor made for this longer format where one

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:27.320
[Amit Varma]: can kind of go deep into oneself and introspect about the world. And that's that's one thing

00:05:27.320 --> 00:05:33.720
[Amit Varma]: I've also really enjoyed about the talks you've given in your columns with HT, where, you

00:05:33.720 --> 00:05:37.560
[Amit Varma]: know, there are various places where it feels like you're almost thinking aloud in the same

00:05:37.560 --> 00:05:42.280
[Amit Varma]: way that I do about the same things I care about. So I really enjoyed that. One of the

00:05:42.280 --> 00:05:47.600
[Amit Varma]: interesting things you mentioned in your column is that you are the last generation to grow

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:52.320
[Amit Varma]: up before the internet and also the the first generation to actually grow up with the internet

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:57.360
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that a transitional point and this is actually a question I've asked guests

00:05:57.360 --> 00:06:05.040
[Amit Varma]: of my own age. I'm 48 now at the time of recording. And what I have noticed in my life is that

00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:09.880
[Amit Varma]: I became an adult before the internet was there. So I was well into my 20s before the

00:06:09.880 --> 00:06:16.280
[Amit Varma]: internet came. And it was interesting because I had to kind of learn about the world again,

00:06:16.280 --> 00:06:21.720
[Amit Varma]: learn about myself again, you know, you just do that whole process from scratch, even something

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:26.440
[Amit Varma]: and it's a very clear demarcation and in my generation and also, you know, just in terms

00:06:26.440 --> 00:06:33.040
[Amit Varma]: of earlier before the internet, you are restricted by communities of circumstance, whereas now

00:06:33.040 --> 00:06:38.720
[Amit Varma]: we can form communities of choice. And in just so many ways, life is completely different.

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:44.440
[Amit Varma]: I want to hear from you what it was like, you know, growing up before the internet,

00:06:44.440 --> 00:06:50.320
[Amit Varma]: because you can contrast it in a much better with in a sense growing up with it because

00:06:50.320 --> 00:06:54.800
[Amit Varma]: it came when you were young enough. And, you know, earlier, when we were having lunch before

00:06:54.800 --> 00:06:59.520
[Amit Varma]: this, we were speaking about the importance of finding that quiet it you don't have where

00:06:59.520 --> 00:07:05.560
[Amit Varma]: you can just sit and, you know, not let sensations knock you from thing to thing. Tell me a bit

00:07:05.560 --> 00:07:08.840
[Amit Varma]: about your growing up years before the internet, like, where were you born? Where did you grow

00:07:08.840 --> 00:07:09.840
[Guest]: up?

00:07:09.840 --> 00:07:13.480
[Guest]: First, I want to again, and I know I've said this to you outside of the podcast, but I

00:07:13.480 --> 00:07:24.160
[Guest]: think like this is a milestone. I was as I think one of the markers of, you know, making

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:27.000
[Guest]: it for me was when I get called to the to this podcast.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:31.360
[Amit Varma]: You're too kind. You've been on very good podcasts like Varun Duggirala, Karthik Narkarachan.

00:07:31.360 --> 00:07:35.360
[Guest]: Amazing. No, but thank you for having me. Honestly, I'm really look, as I said, I think

00:07:35.360 --> 00:07:40.640
[Guest]: another thing that I'm really looking forward to over here is, you know, learning something

00:07:40.640 --> 00:07:44.640
[Guest]: about myself also, which I think like that's the every time I hear your podcast, as you

00:07:44.640 --> 00:07:48.480
[Guest]: yourself said, I think you learn not just about the person, but something about yourself.

00:07:48.480 --> 00:07:58.440
[Guest]: So where do I begin? So I was born in Karnal in Haryana. And my family, we were living

00:07:58.440 --> 00:08:03.520
[Guest]: in Lucknow at that time. My father was a banker. My mother tells me about the time when we

00:08:03.520 --> 00:08:09.720
[Guest]: were, you know, in Lucknow, we were not very well off. So she would always she has these,

00:08:09.720 --> 00:08:14.320
[Guest]: you know, when you see three idiots and you have that scene of black and white scene where

00:08:14.320 --> 00:08:20.520
[Guest]: you show people being, you know, not very well off. She kind of always talks about it

00:08:20.520 --> 00:08:25.420
[Guest]: in that way that, you know, papa ke ka coat phat jata tha. So then there was a choice.

00:08:25.420 --> 00:08:31.400
[Guest]: Should we get you an ice cream or should we get you should we get his coat repaired? So

00:08:31.400 --> 00:08:37.080
[Guest]: that's that's the context that I have, you know, of of growing up at that time where

00:08:37.080 --> 00:08:44.120
[Guest]: we were. There was a lot my father was doing to try and break out of his circumstance.

00:08:44.120 --> 00:08:49.360
[Guest]: And that was visible to everybody in the family. But he was constantly I don't think I spent

00:08:49.360 --> 00:08:53.240
[Guest]: time with my father, you know, growing up at all, you know, because he was constantly

00:08:53.240 --> 00:08:59.960
[Guest]: just trying to make it. He was just constantly trying to get more money, get a better house,

00:08:59.960 --> 00:09:06.380
[Guest]: get to a better life. And so, yeah, I don't, unfortunately, have too many memories of spending

00:09:06.380 --> 00:09:11.720
[Guest]: any time with my father. So I was very much raised by my mother in that sense. And two

00:09:11.720 --> 00:09:16.200
[Guest]: things started happening. Of course, I started, you know, finding a lot of love and empathy

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:22.500
[Guest]: for my mother for the sacrifices that she's done and kind of always wanting to grow up

00:09:22.500 --> 00:09:28.520
[Guest]: to be the kind of the opposite kind of a man as my father because as like I would see my

00:09:28.520 --> 00:09:37.680
[Guest]: mother doing it all alone, right? And my father just so much, you know, I just wish I knew

00:09:37.680 --> 00:09:42.900
[Guest]: him more, which I still do right now. But yeah, that there was a lot of my early years,

00:09:42.900 --> 00:09:48.020
[Guest]: you know, we from Lucknow, we went to Delhi, my father moved out, he was in Bangalore.

00:09:48.020 --> 00:09:52.000
[Guest]: From there, we were there for about a year and a half. And then we went to the Middle

00:09:52.000 --> 00:10:01.320
[Guest]: East, Dubai, in Delhi. You know, my memories of, I feel Amit, I've always somewhere been

00:10:01.320 --> 00:10:06.600
[Guest]: like this outsider looking in. I was talking to Hitesh Kevalia, who's, you know, is a writer

00:10:06.600 --> 00:10:11.520
[Guest]: and director, he's done Shubh Mangal Saavdhan, Zyada Saavdhan. He used this fantastic term

00:10:11.520 --> 00:10:15.760
[Guest]: called border wale log. He said that, you know, kuch log hote hain, border wale log

00:10:15.760 --> 00:10:21.800
[Guest]: hote hain, jo, jo, they're always on the borders, they're never like inside or outside. I feel

00:10:21.800 --> 00:10:27.440
[Guest]: like as someone who, you know, grew up in a manner where I was definitely not, I won't

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:32.840
[Guest]: say I was, you know, quote unquote poor, but we're definitely not very well off. And, and

00:10:32.840 --> 00:10:37.120
[Guest]: suddenly in Delhi, when lifestyle started improving, I was put into, for example, Rhein

00:10:37.120 --> 00:10:41.520
[Guest]: International. And I remember my memories of that time has been just me feeling really

00:10:41.520 --> 00:10:48.040
[Guest]: like, where am I fitting in here, you know, as somebody who was not, you know, as as rich

00:10:48.040 --> 00:10:51.720
[Guest]: as any of the other people over there, the way they spoke the English that they had,

00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:56.320
[Guest]: the clothes that they wore, the chocolates they would bring every day. And those are

00:10:56.320 --> 00:11:02.840
[Guest]: my early memories of like growing up. And then we went to Dubai, where, you know, my,

00:11:02.840 --> 00:11:08.640
[Guest]: again, upwardly mobile. So, you know, got a slightly better lifestyle. Again, I felt

00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:13.680
[Guest]: at home when I was in a school over there called our own English high school, where

00:11:13.680 --> 00:11:18.080
[Guest]: which was basically the one place where I think every middle class Indian kid over there

00:11:18.080 --> 00:11:24.600
[Guest]: was put in. But there was a better school there, which called modern high school, where,

00:11:24.600 --> 00:11:29.680
[Guest]: which was for the upper class, so to speak, where my parents ultimately put me. So my

00:11:29.680 --> 00:11:32.920
[Guest]: parents had made this choice when I was in when I was in Delhi, my younger brother was

00:11:32.920 --> 00:11:37.600
[Guest]: put in a place, put in not a very good school or a very rich school in that sense. And he

00:11:37.600 --> 00:11:41.920
[Guest]: was put in a government school and I was put in Rhein International. And so when we went

00:11:41.920 --> 00:11:46.200
[Guest]: to Dubai, they switched it and said, you know what, and now our younger son gets to go to

00:11:46.200 --> 00:11:50.960
[Guest]: a better school and you know, Nikhil gets to go to our own. No offense to anybody from

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:55.840
[Guest]: our own. But eventually when I went into modern high, again, the same, I feel like so much

00:11:55.840 --> 00:12:02.480
[Guest]: of my life was just trying to kind of figure out how, who, what are these people? And you

00:12:02.480 --> 00:12:10.160
[Guest]: know, what is this? Where am I stand? Where do I stand with these people? Right? And for

00:12:10.160 --> 00:12:15.160
[Guest]: me, again, I think I just took it in with my mother also constantly telling me as his

00:12:15.160 --> 00:12:19.760
[Guest]: mother was raising me pretty much on our own, constantly telling me things like, you know,

00:12:19.760 --> 00:12:24.080
[Guest]: you need to obviously do better. You need to get a certain amount of marks and you need

00:12:24.080 --> 00:12:28.360
[Guest]: to make me proud. You need to go with every young boy is told, you know, you have to be

00:12:28.360 --> 00:12:32.400
[Guest]: an engineer and do an MBA. All of those things were always there, you know, I was constantly

00:12:32.400 --> 00:12:36.720
[Guest]: being told. So my ambition initially just became that I have to make my mother proud.

00:12:36.720 --> 00:12:41.560
[Guest]: That is all I want to do in my life. And no matter what place I was in, no matter what

00:12:41.560 --> 00:12:48.680
[Guest]: role I was in, I was always just overworking, you know, putting my everything into it just

00:12:48.680 --> 00:12:52.560
[Guest]: to make sure that when I go back, my mother is just like seeing all the work that she's

00:12:52.560 --> 00:12:58.000
[Guest]: done in raising me and my brother. She's proud of us. And in that, I think I just imbibed

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:04.580
[Guest]: a mindset of like, you know, work is everything, you know, making it is everything. Aspiration

00:13:04.580 --> 00:13:10.120
[Guest]: is everything, which somehow started conflicting with I think who I was as a person, which

00:13:10.120 --> 00:13:14.440
[Guest]: I've now realized many, many, many years later, which was a person who used to really like

00:13:14.440 --> 00:13:18.600
[Guest]: writing, who used to really like art, who used to really like watching movies growing

00:13:18.600 --> 00:13:22.520
[Guest]: up. And, you know, stories were my comfort zone as someone again, as I said, someone

00:13:22.520 --> 00:13:27.640
[Guest]: who didn't really fit in or did not know where to fit in. I would always watch movies as

00:13:27.640 --> 00:13:33.080
[Guest]: you know, in a way for me to feel less alone. I remember one of the, you know, many years

00:13:33.080 --> 00:13:37.840
[Guest]: ago, I was just trying to teach and I'm sure we'll come to that. When I was teaching my

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:41.240
[Guest]: students, I used to always ask them, you know, tell me your story. And then one day when

00:13:41.240 --> 00:13:45.720
[Guest]: they asked me, what's my story, and I'd always tell them to go deeper, deeper, deeper. And

00:13:45.720 --> 00:13:49.560
[Guest]: then I said something very superficial. And then I started thinking like, you know, everyone

00:13:49.560 --> 00:13:54.800
[Guest]: I asked them to go deep, but what is my and then one of the and why do I do what I do?

00:13:54.800 --> 00:13:59.000
[Guest]: And I was in Yash Raj films at that time, I was, you know, filmmaker. And the deeper

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:03.000
[Guest]: that I went, I kind of recognized this one thing, which came to me as an epiphany that,

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:07.280
[Guest]: you know, one of the reasons why I even interested in stories was because so my father was a

00:14:07.280 --> 00:14:13.400
[Guest]: big Dev Anand fan. And the only time that my father would ever call me was when he put

00:14:13.400 --> 00:14:16.360
[Guest]: on would come home and put on a Dev Anand movie. And then he'd be like, do you want

00:14:16.360 --> 00:14:20.120
[Guest]: to watch it? And then I would sit with him and I would watch these movies. That's what

00:14:20.120 --> 00:14:27.640
[Guest]: I remember growing up. And I suppose, in that moment with my father, I started recognizing

00:14:27.640 --> 00:14:32.440
[Guest]: the power of stories and storytelling and the fact that, you know, they actually bring

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:37.840
[Guest]: you together in some way or the other. And that's my connection that I made with stories.

00:14:37.840 --> 00:14:43.000
[Guest]: You know, the only time I would ever have with my father was because of movies, because,

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:47.520
[Guest]: you know, we got to sit together and spend three hours while we didn't may not have spoken.

00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:51.440
[Guest]: My father would be very excited about the facts of that film. And that's all I know,

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:55.140
[Guest]: but he would never talk about me about feelings and emotions. But like, well, Dev Anand has

00:14:55.140 --> 00:14:58.640
[Guest]: done these many films and Adi Varman has done this and Kishore Kumar has done this and you

00:14:58.640 --> 00:15:03.000
[Guest]: know, but I was getting to spend time with my father, which meant a lot to me. But and

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:07.960
[Guest]: that was my life. And I started really falling in love with the written word with stories

00:15:07.960 --> 00:15:12.320
[Guest]: started writing when I was very young, when I was about 14. And, and that's where the

00:15:12.320 --> 00:15:17.640
[Guest]: internet came into my life. So from Dubai, we went to Bahrain. And there was a magazine

00:15:17.640 --> 00:15:21.200
[Guest]: in the Middle East called Young Times, which was a part of the Khaleesh Times group over

00:15:21.200 --> 00:15:27.640
[Guest]: there. And Young Times was for young writers. And they used to have an arts column in it

00:15:27.640 --> 00:15:32.240
[Guest]: where people used to make paintings and drawings and send them. So my brother was a natural

00:15:32.240 --> 00:15:36.920
[Guest]: artist, you know, so he would draw these beautiful, you know, drawings and whatnot and send them

00:15:36.920 --> 00:15:41.880
[Guest]: and they'd get published. And I would constantly also try to do the same, but they would never

00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:45.880
[Guest]: publish my story. And I mean, my drawings are used to get so irritated, you know, like,

00:15:45.880 --> 00:15:49.680
[Guest]: and I was very bad at it. And I would also then, you know, use like a transparent paper

00:15:49.680 --> 00:15:55.160
[Guest]: and copy, you know, a drawing and I clearly they found out that I'm actually it's a plagiarism,

00:15:55.160 --> 00:16:00.120
[Guest]: which I now understand. But, but you know, I was just getting so frustrated that my brother

00:16:00.120 --> 00:16:03.160
[Guest]: keeps getting published. I don't keep getting published. I've sent far more entries than

00:16:03.160 --> 00:16:06.960
[Guest]: my brother. So one day I wrote a letter to them, you know, saying that, you know, like,

00:16:06.960 --> 00:16:13.480
[Guest]: I have a grievance with you all, you know, as a 12, 13, 14 year old, you, you know, I've

00:16:13.480 --> 00:16:18.400
[Guest]: sent so many different, you know, entries and you never publish it. And they publish

00:16:18.400 --> 00:16:24.040
[Guest]: that letter. And then I was like, well, clearly there's something in my writing that they

00:16:24.040 --> 00:16:28.480
[Guest]: wanted to publish. So, so I started writing more letters to them and they started publishing

00:16:28.480 --> 00:16:34.040
[Guest]: those letters. And eventually, because it was a youth magazine, I kind of, and because

00:16:34.040 --> 00:16:38.040
[Guest]: we had access to the internet, they just had like this email ID. We had got our first computer

00:16:38.040 --> 00:16:42.960
[Guest]: at that time. This is when I was 13. And, and we just got an internet dial up internet

00:16:42.960 --> 00:16:48.040
[Guest]: connection. So I just, I don't know why, but again, sense of ambition, constantly wanting

00:16:48.040 --> 00:16:54.720
[Guest]: to do better. I was like, what if I asked these folks that, uh, what if I could do something

00:16:54.720 --> 00:16:59.600
[Guest]: in Bahrain as a young writer? Can I be their correspondent? Can I, you know, because there's

00:16:59.600 --> 00:17:04.080
[Guest]: a lot of Indian celebrities to come to Bahrain. I was like, what if I interview them? And

00:17:04.080 --> 00:17:07.920
[Guest]: I don't even know where these ideas are. I didn't even know where these ideas came from,

00:17:07.920 --> 00:17:12.800
[Guest]: but I was just, I gave it a shot because of the internet and the road back saying, yes,

00:17:12.800 --> 00:17:18.200
[Guest]: go for it. And I said, what? And, and that's where my writing career pretty much began

00:17:18.200 --> 00:17:25.720
[Guest]: at, at 13, 14, you know, I got published. I've, I interviewed like from Junoon to, you

00:17:25.720 --> 00:17:31.420
[Guest]: know, Shankar Mahadevan to, you know, to Michael Schumacher. I have interviewed all of them

00:17:31.420 --> 00:17:37.280
[Guest]: before I was 18 during school years. And actually like spending time with those folks, Mohan

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:42.760
[Guest]: Lal, I've sat with him. And the internet was the way for me to get to know these people.

00:17:42.760 --> 00:17:46.720
[Guest]: To know them as well. I just do intense research on everybody. So when I'd go there, you know,

00:17:46.720 --> 00:17:50.440
[Guest]: because I was like, age is against me in that sense, they'd be like, Oh, who's this 13,

00:17:50.440 --> 00:17:55.480
[Guest]: 14 year old coming? But like my, I need to make sure that when I ask questions, nobody,

00:17:55.480 --> 00:17:59.400
[Guest]: you know, looks down on me. So I just research the hell out of everybody and then go into

00:17:59.400 --> 00:18:05.160
[Guest]: that and, and start asking these questions. So before the internet, I feel like I kind

00:18:05.160 --> 00:18:08.920
[Guest]: of did not, as I think, did not know where to fit in. And when the internet happened,

00:18:08.920 --> 00:18:16.960
[Guest]: I suddenly kind of found my voice, you know, as somebody who just in the offline world,

00:18:16.960 --> 00:18:22.720
[Guest]: because of a certain, I don't know, class hierarchy, a social hierarchy, I was just

00:18:22.720 --> 00:18:31.400
[Guest]: always lost, always trying to find, you know, companionship, or true friendship, or authentic

00:18:31.400 --> 00:18:37.480
[Guest]: relationships, which I was just not able to as a young boy. And, and which is where movies

00:18:37.480 --> 00:18:41.600
[Guest]: became important to me. I think because of the internet, then I started finding like,

00:18:41.600 --> 00:18:48.160
[Guest]: a reason or an entire world on the internet. That was meant for me that was like, this

00:18:48.160 --> 00:18:52.160
[Guest]: is my community, this is going to be my world. This is where I fit in.

00:18:52.160 --> 00:18:56.800
[Amit Varma]: Wow, that's very resonant and many things I want to double click on. But first I was

00:18:56.800 --> 00:18:59.960
[Amit Varma]: you just before you told me that you were born in Karnal, I thought of Karnal during

00:18:59.960 --> 00:19:04.360
[Amit Varma]: lunch. And the reason is that I was born in Chandigarh. But so I kind of know Karnal from

00:19:04.360 --> 00:19:10.840
[Amit Varma]: a distance. But the reason is that you were talking about the film you're kind of working

00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:14.840
[Amit Varma]: on, you're talking about one of your projects. And a project that I once abandoned came to

00:19:14.840 --> 00:19:21.640
[Amit Varma]: mind, which was about 12-13 years ago, I decided that I'm going to write the series of three

00:19:21.640 --> 00:19:26.680
[Amit Varma]: really bad pulpy novels, much like Roger Corman films, you know, that kind of feel. And I'm

00:19:26.680 --> 00:19:31.200
[Amit Varma]: going to write each of them in one week. So it's going to be really hurried and bad. And

00:19:31.200 --> 00:19:36.400
[Amit Varma]: one of those was called Karnal in Karnal. And it was about this bunch of boys, bunch

00:19:36.400 --> 00:19:41.360
[Amit Varma]: of guys who want to have a party in this farmhouse in Karnal. And they get a bunch of sex workers

00:19:41.360 --> 00:19:46.120
[Amit Varma]: or a bunch of girls to have it with. And then it quickly becomes a horror film, as these

00:19:46.120 --> 00:19:50.840
[Amit Varma]: women turn on them and eventually murder all of them. And, you know, so it was very gory

00:19:50.840 --> 00:19:55.400
[Amit Varma]: and very whatever I never ended up doing this, because, you know, one thinks of a million

00:19:55.400 --> 00:20:00.080
[Amit Varma]: projects and all that. But, you know, now when you mentioned Karnal, for some reason,

00:20:00.080 --> 00:20:04.640
[Amit Varma]: I thought of that. And it's again, women striking back against a patriarchy, right? There's

00:20:04.640 --> 00:20:09.840
[Amit Varma]: a certain kind of oppression you're hitting at, which is also the theme of so much of

00:20:09.840 --> 00:20:16.800
[Amit Varma]: your work. The first of the things I want to double click on is your what you told me

00:20:16.800 --> 00:20:21.440
[Amit Varma]: the memories you shared with your mother, and even your father, like I did this recent

00:20:21.440 --> 00:20:26.480
[Amit Varma]: episode with Samarth Bansal, you know, very beautiful, deep conversation and where he

00:20:26.480 --> 00:20:32.680
[Amit Varma]: spoke about the expectations he had from his mother. And, you know, he spoke about how

00:20:32.680 --> 00:20:38.480
[Amit Varma]: the day he got his first job, she said that I feel like I have become independent. Because,

00:20:38.480 --> 00:20:45.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, and, and it was very interesting. And I'm interested in not just that aspect

00:20:45.760 --> 00:20:52.480
[Amit Varma]: of it, but that aspect that in the sense, when we grow up, we often don't think of our

00:20:52.480 --> 00:20:58.640
[Amit Varma]: parents a way we would do later, right? They are playing roles, we are also playing a role,

00:20:58.640 --> 00:21:02.720
[Amit Varma]: they are playing roles, they are stuck in that role. We take them for granted. For us,

00:21:02.720 --> 00:21:06.720
[Amit Varma]: a mother is a particular role that is being played by someone, a father is a particular

00:21:06.720 --> 00:21:12.760
[Amit Varma]: role. We don't even think of them as real people. You know, recently, my father passed

00:21:12.760 --> 00:21:18.800
[Amit Varma]: last year. So I was looking through old photographs. And I came across a photograph of my parents

00:21:18.800 --> 00:21:25.800
[Amit Varma]: when they were in their early 40s. Right? And it's, it's like, a huge sort of mental

00:21:25.800 --> 00:21:31.960
[Amit Varma]: shift you have to make. Because in that photograph, they're younger than I am now. And they're

00:21:31.960 --> 00:21:37.520
[Amit Varma]: actual, they look like actual real people. And at the same time, I have a memory of them

00:21:37.520 --> 00:21:42.200
[Amit Varma]: as that little boy in the picture, you know, looking at them as people who are in these

00:21:42.200 --> 00:21:46.880
[Amit Varma]: roles, you never really see them as people. And later on, when you you know, you go through

00:21:46.880 --> 00:21:51.440
[Amit Varma]: life, you look back, you kind of understand a little bit more, I think some people may

00:21:51.440 --> 00:21:56.680
[Amit Varma]: go through their whole lives, just playing out roles, never seeing never understanding

00:21:56.680 --> 00:22:02.080
[Amit Varma]: that my mother is someone who might have felt restrained by her circumstances that God knows

00:22:02.080 --> 00:22:08.080
[Amit Varma]: what kind of quiet grief she hid within her as she did as she played her roles, you know,

00:22:08.080 --> 00:22:12.200
[Amit Varma]: and ditto for fathers, as you've pointed out, you know, both men and women in different

00:22:12.200 --> 00:22:19.480
[Amit Varma]: ways are victims of patriarchy. But I want to ask about sort of this memory aspect that,

00:22:19.480 --> 00:22:23.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, were you clear as a kid at what was happening? Or is this stuff you're beginning

00:22:23.720 --> 00:22:29.440
[Amit Varma]: to figure out in hindsight? And how do you look back on them and post all of that? You

00:22:29.440 --> 00:22:33.560
[Amit Varma]: know, how did your how did your relationship with them evolve? Like, is this stuff that

00:22:33.560 --> 00:22:35.640
[Guest]: you can talk about now at a distance?

00:22:35.640 --> 00:22:41.440
[Guest]: Absolutely. When I was much younger, I obviously did not have an understanding or perspective

00:22:41.440 --> 00:22:48.320
[Guest]: of the roles my parents were playing. I just had a lot of love for my mother, because I

00:22:48.320 --> 00:22:54.400
[Guest]: would see how hard she tries. And not just because of me, and I don't want to I don't

00:22:54.400 --> 00:23:00.240
[Guest]: want to dive too deeply into this part of my life, because it's about my brother. And

00:23:00.240 --> 00:23:04.880
[Guest]: I don't think I'm the right person to talk about his life. But my brother went through

00:23:04.880 --> 00:23:11.680
[Guest]: a really long phase of mental health issues, and younger brother, so just really like a

00:23:11.680 --> 00:23:20.360
[Guest]: 10 year period where he was depressed. And my mother's worked day and night to, you know,

00:23:20.360 --> 00:23:25.280
[Guest]: help him. You know, even even when you were in Dubai Bahrain, you know, again, we were

00:23:25.280 --> 00:23:32.200
[Guest]: not now I think we're in a place where we can easily say that we have privilege. But,

00:23:32.200 --> 00:23:37.160
[Guest]: you know, we were, we didn't have enough money to travel through taxi. So my mother would

00:23:37.160 --> 00:23:44.000
[Guest]: enroll us in every, you know, extracurricular activity possible. And then just walk us there,

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:50.680
[Guest]: you know, like, so we like 40-45 minutes in the 45-50 degree heat, we would be walking

00:23:50.680 --> 00:23:56.240
[Guest]: from after school from our home to like, you know, tuition that she wanted us to be at

00:23:56.240 --> 00:24:00.920
[Guest]: a karate class, a tennis class, a swimming lesson, which most of which we gave up on

00:24:00.920 --> 00:24:06.160
[Guest]: you're like terrible kids in that sense, you know, but I was very aware that there is an

00:24:06.160 --> 00:24:10.960
[Guest]: effort going into, you know, raising us and, and, and that became even more apparent when

00:24:10.960 --> 00:24:17.440
[Guest]: my brother started going through his issues. And my mother really like just her entire

00:24:17.440 --> 00:24:23.600
[Guest]: life became about making sure my brother is, you know, able to get out of it. We did not

00:24:23.600 --> 00:24:27.960
[Guest]: know at that time it was depression. You know, at that time, we thought that there was, it

00:24:27.960 --> 00:24:34.240
[Guest]: was just, I mean, he's some problem as a child, he's not a problematic child in some way.

00:24:34.240 --> 00:24:37.680
[Guest]: And much later, we found out that this is mental health related, because those terms

00:24:37.680 --> 00:24:43.080
[Guest]: did not exist then, you know, so, so, so yeah, I think growing up and then my I was also

00:24:43.080 --> 00:24:47.200
[Guest]: very close to my Maasi, you know, who was like this ray of light who would come like

00:24:47.200 --> 00:24:52.040
[Guest]: again, she's a teacher, she has had a very hard life, she lost her husband, lost her

00:24:52.040 --> 00:24:55.160
[Guest]: parents, single handedly, like took care of her parents after losing her husband very

00:24:55.160 --> 00:25:01.480
[Guest]: early, lost her brother, both my mother, they've lost his elder brother. And she would just

00:25:01.480 --> 00:25:06.600
[Guest]: come in and you know, give us like this. So these gifts she'll bring in, you know, just

00:25:06.600 --> 00:25:12.800
[Guest]: a lot of love, a lot of, you know, care every time she'd come in to meet us. And these two

00:25:12.800 --> 00:25:17.880
[Guest]: women I would, and my Maasi was someone who would, you know, teach at a school. So she

00:25:17.880 --> 00:25:22.800
[Guest]: was a teacher, English teacher at a convent school in Karnal. And one of the most respected

00:25:22.800 --> 00:25:26.560
[Guest]: women in Karnal, even today, like sometimes you go for holidays, and you meet a student

00:25:26.560 --> 00:25:30.640
[Guest]: of hers who comes in, ma'am, you've, you've changed my life and whatnot. It's so beautiful

00:25:30.640 --> 00:25:34.480
[Guest]: to see. So these two strong women, you know, who are doing everything that was that was

00:25:34.480 --> 00:25:41.320
[Guest]: my understanding, like, you know, of of my parents in that sense, or my elders. On the

00:25:41.320 --> 00:25:46.120
[Guest]: other hand, with my father, it was mostly resentment. I was just really angry with him

00:25:46.120 --> 00:25:50.720
[Guest]: that he was not there for me. I'd see some of my other friends, you know, playing cricket

00:25:50.720 --> 00:25:55.400
[Guest]: with their fathers, etc, etc, or hanging out with them, you know, my father had no time

00:25:55.400 --> 00:26:02.800
[Guest]: for us. And, and my father also went through his own issues, used to be very angry, which

00:26:02.800 --> 00:26:06.960
[Guest]: I feel like most fathers are, I suppose, now that I've found or now that I've spoken to

00:26:06.960 --> 00:26:14.080
[Guest]: hundreds of 1000s of kids in India, I think that's the pattern, father is equal to angry.

00:26:14.080 --> 00:26:20.000
[Guest]: But what he would also go through something which I much later realized was anxiety. So

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:29.520
[Guest]: he was his he would his again, I feel he would there's a sense of violence, but that was

00:26:29.520 --> 00:26:36.520
[Guest]: to himself versus that anger was taken out on us as well. But never as much as on himself,

00:26:36.520 --> 00:26:43.920
[Guest]: you know, if I can put it as nicely as possible. So I just did not really like I was just angry

00:26:43.920 --> 00:26:50.360
[Guest]: with my father, you know, like I think all young men in our country are. And I wanted to be

00:26:50.360 --> 00:26:56.080
[Guest]: the kind of husband. I mean, everything my father's like, I was always like, here's my

00:26:56.080 --> 00:27:00.720
[Guest]: profile of my father, I'm going to be absolute opposite of him in every possible way. I'm

00:27:00.720 --> 00:27:04.360
[Guest]: going to be the best husband, I'm going to be the best son, I'm going to be the best,

00:27:04.360 --> 00:27:09.680
[Guest]: you know, brother, I'm going to be the best, you know, caretaker of a home, I'm going to,

00:27:09.680 --> 00:27:14.120
[Unknown]: you know, I mean, I'm never going to go into banking, which he was the absolute opposite

00:27:14.120 --> 00:27:21.840
[Guest]: of banking. I was like, I'm not going to be a banker. So if he's outside of India, I'll

00:27:21.840 --> 00:27:25.800
[Guest]: go back to India. You know, I'm everything for me was just like, I'm not going to be

00:27:25.800 --> 00:27:32.800
[Guest]: him. And, and, and again, let me let me point out this that he was never in fact, he was

00:27:32.800 --> 00:27:40.400
[Guest]: never unkind to me. You know, in that sense, like he was, he was not again, with my mother,

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:45.560
[Guest]: he was I think he was just as patriarchal as every Indian man is, let me put it that

00:27:45.560 --> 00:27:51.240
[Guest]: way, you know, which used to get me even angrier, because I'd be like, why are you, you raise

00:27:51.240 --> 00:27:56.600
[Guest]: us, you do all this work in home, why do you still have to like, work for him? You're not

00:27:56.600 --> 00:28:01.400
[Guest]: you don't have to work for him. You can you work for the you're working for your home.

00:28:01.400 --> 00:28:08.440
[Guest]: I get it, but you have to work for him as well. But, but he was, you know, while and

00:28:08.440 --> 00:28:12.600
[Guest]: and for for whatever it's worth, he's never like, while he's been angry at us, and he's

00:28:12.600 --> 00:28:16.960
[Guest]: might have raised his hands at me and my brother, but he's never like, you know, with my mother,

00:28:16.960 --> 00:28:22.960
[Guest]: he's never really been violent in a domestic violence way, you know, and, but he as I said,

00:28:22.960 --> 00:28:27.720
[Guest]: he just had a lot of, you know, anxiety issues, which I much later found out and and seeing

00:28:27.720 --> 00:28:32.560
[Guest]: him, I had a sense of, you know, and I feel very now that I look back, I feel really bad

00:28:32.560 --> 00:28:37.280
[Guest]: about that I used to have a sense of a weak man. It's not a very strong man, you know,

00:28:37.280 --> 00:28:41.180
[Guest]: whereas I feel like it does take a lot of strength for him to break out of the family

00:28:41.180 --> 00:28:46.640
[Guest]: that he came from, you know, and go on to his whole family, you know, nobody else has

00:28:46.640 --> 00:28:51.080
[Guest]: been, so to speak successful in his family, you know, he was from Panipat and his parents

00:28:51.080 --> 00:28:56.280
[Guest]: and I mean, both our parents are from, you know, what is now Pakistan, Punjab in Pakistan,

00:28:56.280 --> 00:29:00.720
[Guest]: you know, crossed over, grandparents crossed over, one settled in, you know, Karnal eventually

00:29:00.720 --> 00:29:07.320
[Guest]: and one settled in Panipat eventually. And, but he broke out of his, you know, he and

00:29:07.320 --> 00:29:14.160
[Guest]: he did it on his own. There was no support system. He did like the, you know, the clerk

00:29:14.160 --> 00:29:19.720
[Guest]: exam or, you know, whichever the banking exam is, and then rose his ranks. And now he is,

00:29:19.720 --> 00:29:25.440
[Guest]: you know, chairman at ICC in Bahrain. And, you know, he's spoken at United Nations on

00:29:25.440 --> 00:29:29.320
[Guest]: him. He's one of the biggest names in trade finance, even though he's still like thinks

00:29:29.320 --> 00:29:36.560
[Guest]: he's nothing, you know, but it has, it's been very, I mean, much later, I've looked back

00:29:36.560 --> 00:29:41.040
[Guest]: and thought that, you know, I mean, he was much stronger man without the support system.

00:29:41.040 --> 00:29:45.240
[Guest]: You know, my, my mother was the biggest support system, but he'd grown up without a system

00:29:45.240 --> 00:29:51.200
[Guest]: which, which then made him so angry at his own life, that all the things that he would

00:29:51.200 --> 00:29:57.520
[Guest]: do or, you know, he just didn't have the emotional quotient that my mother had. And I, earlier

00:29:57.520 --> 00:30:01.160
[Guest]: I used to blame him for him for it. And then after a lot of therapy, I realized that, you

00:30:01.160 --> 00:30:06.520
[Guest]: know, it's not his fault either, is it? So growing up, I had very, you know, clear rules

00:30:06.520 --> 00:30:11.520
[Guest]: of, you know, what my mother's supposed to, my mother is what my father is. But much later

00:30:11.520 --> 00:30:17.840
[Guest]: in life, I have, I was very angry with my father for many, many, many, many years. Now

00:30:17.840 --> 00:30:23.840
[Guest]: I'm not, now I empathize, now I understand, now I feel bad for the way that I've treated

00:30:23.840 --> 00:30:29.520
[Guest]: him as a son, even though, you know, I'm still angry at the way he treated my mother. But

00:30:29.520 --> 00:30:34.480
[Guest]: at the same time, I recognize it's not, it's, it's conditioning. And it's, you know, he

00:30:34.480 --> 00:30:39.480
[Guest]: had anxiety, he had conditioning, he tried so hard to, he's the reason why I have whatever

00:30:39.480 --> 00:30:43.080
[Guest]: privilege I have today. He's the reason why our family has whatever privilege we have

00:30:43.080 --> 00:30:48.200
[Guest]: today. That, you know, and we were good children. And that's a, let me be honest, like my brother

00:30:48.200 --> 00:30:52.520
[Guest]: and I, we never, you know, we recognize that our parents have worked hard to get their

00:30:52.520 --> 00:30:57.960
[Guest]: money. We've never spent up like, never, we didn't even ask for a gift on our birthdays.

00:30:57.960 --> 00:31:05.520
[Guest]: We were just happy, like being with each other, you know, and, and it's only like in my 30s,

00:31:05.520 --> 00:31:10.120
[Guest]: my father has started gifting me things, which has been like a, like, okay, what do I do

00:31:10.120 --> 00:31:17.840
[Guest]: with this now? I have an iPad. Thank you. But, but, you know, so yeah, I just, I just,

00:31:17.840 --> 00:31:23.040
[Guest]: and on the other hand, when I, my anger with my father also translated to anger with my

00:31:23.040 --> 00:31:29.840
[Guest]: mother during my 20s, because, because she wanted me to again, break out of our circumstances

00:31:29.840 --> 00:31:34.200
[Guest]: in some way, she just put a lot of pressure on me, which again, I don't begrudge her for

00:31:34.200 --> 00:31:40.280
[Guest]: anymore. But at that time, it just, it drove me into a certain kind of, again, depression,

00:31:40.280 --> 00:31:45.960
[Guest]: if I can say so, where I was trying after my, I mean, I'm sure we'll get into that.

00:31:45.960 --> 00:31:51.560
[Guest]: But I did after, even though I was someone who was writing such, such an early age, you

00:31:51.560 --> 00:31:56.840
[Guest]: know, I remember this very distinct conversation, which is not even a conversation that my parents

00:31:56.840 --> 00:32:01.840
[Guest]: would remember. But we were at our first ever family holiday in life, you know, so after

00:32:01.840 --> 00:32:09.200
[Guest]: I finished 12th, my father took us for this SOTC Europe tour, you know, and there was,

00:32:09.200 --> 00:32:12.800
[Guest]: and my father is always this person, which I'm saying he's always also been like, anytime

00:32:12.800 --> 00:32:17.040
[Guest]: I had interviews, he'd drive me to those interviews. So he's also been like, I always looked at

00:32:17.040 --> 00:32:20.960
[Guest]: him in such such a sharply negative point of view that I could never see the efforts

00:32:20.960 --> 00:32:24.840
[Guest]: he made in different ways. But I remember like, again, my father showing off to everyone

00:32:24.840 --> 00:32:28.000
[Guest]: saying my son has written in these magazines, he's interviewed these people, look at this,

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:31.880
[Guest]: look at that, he was 17 at that time. And there's this old couple that he was talking

00:32:31.880 --> 00:32:36.120
[Guest]: to, and the couple said, that sounds so fantastic. So is he going to now, I was in 12th, right?

00:32:36.120 --> 00:32:39.480
[Guest]: Is he going to an arts college? Is he, are you putting him in like Delhi in like something

00:32:39.480 --> 00:32:45.960
[Guest]: interesting? And my mother immediately said, no, no, that's a hobby. You know, that's not

00:32:45.960 --> 00:32:51.720
[Guest]: what he will do. He will, you know, be an engineer. And, and he's going to, you know,

00:32:51.720 --> 00:32:58.440
[Guest]: and do MBA. And, you know, and I was, it wasn't like, it's such a distinct memory for me.

00:32:58.440 --> 00:33:03.200
[Guest]: And much later, I remember that it's still something that hits me that I just never had

00:33:03.200 --> 00:33:09.840
[Guest]: an opinion or a decision in what I was ever going to do. It was just decided for me, right?

00:33:09.840 --> 00:33:13.640
[Guest]: Ki yehi karega. Aur maine bhi uss time socha nahi, main ka, main bhi maan gaya tha, yehi

00:33:13.640 --> 00:33:20.560
[Guest]: karna hai. I am going to be an engineer, you know. But I mean, I was this, whatever, bright

00:33:20.560 --> 00:33:25.160
[Guest]: kid who used to love writing. And I wish somebody had pointed me in the direction and said,

00:33:25.160 --> 00:33:28.760
[Guest]: you know what, do this. But I had to find a different path. I had to finish engineering.

00:33:28.760 --> 00:33:33.320
[Guest]: Then I had to leave. I mean, like after that, I got jobs. Told my parents, dekho main, I'm

00:33:33.320 --> 00:33:37.920
[Guest]: capable of getting jobs. After that, I came to Bombay and then started working with Hindustan

00:33:37.920 --> 00:33:43.440
[Guest]: Times at a very, you know, like a terrible, terrible salary for like two, two and a half

00:33:43.440 --> 00:33:48.520
[Guest]: years. Even during that time, my mother would keep telling me and she would say it in the,

00:33:48.520 --> 00:33:52.520
[Guest]: again, from a place of, you know, you're not earning money, you should really like do something

00:33:52.520 --> 00:33:57.560
[Guest]: where you're going to be comfortable. But for me, it was always like, you know, have

00:33:57.560 --> 00:34:01.920
[Guest]: some faith in me. I know there's no money right now, but I'm trying to do something

00:34:01.920 --> 00:34:06.720
[Guest]: of my own. You're the one person who's always given me love. Why can't you today show me

00:34:06.720 --> 00:34:12.960
[Guest]: that love and that trust and that support and, and, and just let me be. And that just

00:34:12.960 --> 00:34:17.800
[Guest]: drove like a wedge into our relationship. So for a very long time, you know, I kind

00:34:17.800 --> 00:34:25.160
[Guest]: of have this thing where I feel like when you are younger, your parents are always forgiving

00:34:25.160 --> 00:34:30.240
[Guest]: you for like being an idiot. You know, in the middle, there's a time when you grew up

00:34:30.240 --> 00:34:32.680
[Guest]: and your parents stop forgiving you because you're like, now you can't be needed because

00:34:32.680 --> 00:34:37.080
[Guest]: you are, you know, not young anymore. But because your parents have always had a certain

00:34:37.080 --> 00:34:42.240
[Guest]: way of behaving with you, you start, you know, also getting angry. You've always like, why

00:34:42.240 --> 00:34:45.880
[Guest]: not now? I'm so what I'm still your child or whatever. You still say I'm a child, but

00:34:45.880 --> 00:34:49.720
[Guest]: why are you getting angry? So you also get angry back, right? And then you kind of get

00:34:49.720 --> 00:34:53.280
[Guest]: older and then you become the opposite. You become a parent in that sense to your parents

00:34:53.280 --> 00:34:57.440
[Guest]: where you're just like, yeah, they're old and they don't get it as much as we do now.

00:34:57.440 --> 00:35:02.120
[Guest]: We need to start forgiving, right? And that's what I think happened after in my thirties

00:35:02.120 --> 00:35:08.760
[Guest]: where I've just like, let it all go. And I've really, you know, try to listen to my parents,

00:35:08.760 --> 00:35:13.720
[Guest]: try to understand them. As you very nicely said, I've tried to look at them not as parents,

00:35:13.720 --> 00:35:19.760
[Guest]: but as human beings and just really felt bad for the way that I was just so angry in my

00:35:19.760 --> 00:35:24.880
[Guest]: twenties with them. I mean, we still, my mother is still very hurt about the way that I talk

00:35:24.880 --> 00:35:31.320
[Guest]: about these years because she obviously has done her best to be a fantastic mother, even

00:35:31.320 --> 00:35:37.080
[Guest]: though it ended up pressurizing me and driving me into a sense of like real despair that

00:35:37.080 --> 00:35:43.000
[Guest]: my mother doesn't believe in me, you know, but I can now keep telling her that it's okay,

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:45.960
[Guest]: you know, it's not your fault as well. And you need to be comfortable with that, you

00:35:45.960 --> 00:35:50.080
[Guest]: know, that there was a period that maybe both of us, I mean, all of us are victims of patriarchy

00:35:50.080 --> 00:35:53.560
[Guest]: and none of us knows any better. You know, you can get angry with your parents as much

00:35:53.560 --> 00:35:57.080
[Guest]: as you want, but they've been conditioned to behave in the same way from their parents

00:35:57.080 --> 00:36:01.720
[Guest]: and so on and so forth. You know, everybody has come from the societal conditioning. And

00:36:01.720 --> 00:36:08.040
[Guest]: if you are aware today, you need to have the empathy and it's empathy is not easy. It is

00:36:08.040 --> 00:36:13.120
[Guest]: a responsibility. It is, it's tough. It's a burden sometimes, but if you don't have

00:36:13.120 --> 00:36:18.840
[Guest]: it, then you know, you're never going to have, you're never going to go beyond anger into

00:36:18.840 --> 00:36:25.680
[Guest]: love, into compassion, into togetherness, you know. So I'm just, I'm really glad that

00:36:25.680 --> 00:36:30.440
[Guest]: now I see my parents differently. And I'm just a lot more grateful for what they've

00:36:30.440 --> 00:36:35.840
[Guest]: given me. My father for the long hours, you know, where he just, when I think about it

00:36:35.840 --> 00:36:39.640
[Guest]: right now, I mean, he never got to hang with his son. I, I've always felt like he didn't,

00:36:39.640 --> 00:36:46.840
[Guest]: my father didn't hang with me. But now I also feel like, well, he as a person, as a human

00:36:46.840 --> 00:36:50.720
[Guest]: being, as a man did not get to hang out with his son. You know, my mother, I would always

00:36:50.720 --> 00:36:55.480
[Guest]: be like, she always wanted me to be this way. And now I'm, I'm looking at it in a different

00:36:55.480 --> 00:36:59.920
[Guest]: way that she wanted some, she expected something from her son, which her son was pushing back

00:36:59.920 --> 00:37:05.760
[Guest]: on. So, so even their anger was valid or, you know, their efforts were valid, you know,

00:37:05.760 --> 00:37:09.920
[Guest]: in whatever they were doing. So, yeah, I feel a little, I feel like a tinge of regret in

00:37:09.920 --> 00:37:14.080
[Guest]: the way that I was in my 20s. But I recognize that, you know, obviously, this is just the

00:37:14.080 --> 00:37:17.120
[Guest]: way life is. And we got to do better now.

00:37:17.120 --> 00:37:20.200
[Amit Varma]: There's a lovely anecdote in one of your columns about when you're getting married and you're

00:37:20.200 --> 00:37:25.280
[Amit Varma]: having this destination wedding in Simla, and your mother is, you know, arguing with

00:37:25.280 --> 00:37:29.440
[Amit Varma]: you about some little thing. And you're like, come on, it's my marriage. Why are you arguing

00:37:29.440 --> 00:37:37.880
[Amit Varma]: now? And tell me about that. And what I'm also interested in is that you were able to

00:37:37.880 --> 00:37:43.200
[Amit Varma]: after a period of time, shrug off that layer where, you know, they're human beings for

00:37:43.200 --> 00:37:46.400
[Amit Varma]: you, they're not playing a role anymore. So you can see them in that new light and can

00:37:46.400 --> 00:37:51.160
[Amit Varma]: evaluate them in that new light. Were they able to shrug off those layers, not just with

00:37:51.160 --> 00:37:57.040
[Amit Varma]: regard to you, but perhaps with regard to yourself? Like, are these conversations, like,

00:37:57.040 --> 00:38:00.240
[Amit Varma]: everything that we've been talking about, is this a conversation you could have with

00:38:00.240 --> 00:38:02.640
[Amit Varma]: both of them sitting there sitting across somewhere?

00:38:02.640 --> 00:38:09.520
[Guest]: Great question. With my father, not so much. Because my father, he's still like, you know,

00:38:09.520 --> 00:38:13.640
[Guest]: I don't know if he'll ever hear this. He totally hears most of the things I do. So I'm also

00:38:13.640 --> 00:38:18.800
[Guest]: now a little worried that he's going to hear this. But, you know, I'd love to have a conversation

00:38:18.800 --> 00:38:24.600
[Guest]: with my father someday, you know, and I want to, I want to just have an honest conversation

00:38:24.600 --> 00:38:30.280
[Guest]: with him, just get to know him better. Now, the thing about him, he also talks a lot.

00:38:30.280 --> 00:38:34.520
[Guest]: OK, so he's also someone who's very absent minded in how much he speaks. So he speaks

00:38:34.520 --> 00:38:39.560
[Guest]: a lot about his life anyway, but not in a meaningful way. Right. So I may know, I know

00:38:39.560 --> 00:38:43.920
[Guest]: every story of his life a hundred times over, because that's anytime he meets anybody at

00:38:43.920 --> 00:38:48.200
[Guest]: any party, he will repeat those stories. At the same time, I just feel like there's nothing

00:38:48.200 --> 00:38:53.760
[Guest]: I know beyond the surface of these stories. So I'd love to have like a meaningful conversation

00:38:53.760 --> 00:38:57.240
[Guest]: with my father someday where, you know, we can be friends and we can talk about each

00:38:57.240 --> 00:39:07.400
[Guest]: other. But, you know, I just feel like he never matured into the EQ that you should

00:39:07.400 --> 00:39:14.920
[Guest]: have to be able to have a compassionate conversation with someone you love, someone who loves you.

00:39:14.920 --> 00:39:20.680
[Guest]: So he just has just been, distance has been his, and I feel like that's true for all fathers,

00:39:20.680 --> 00:39:29.320
[Guest]: right? Distance becomes their thing. I don't know what to say, but that's what they're,

00:39:29.320 --> 00:39:33.160
[Guest]: that's the way of life, you know, being distant from each other. You work, I have to work

00:39:33.160 --> 00:39:37.480
[Guest]: on my thing, you work on your thing. And every once in a while we will call each other and

00:39:37.480 --> 00:39:41.680
[Guest]: then I will hand the phone to your mother, which is, you know, like every time my father

00:39:41.680 --> 00:39:46.200
[Guest]: calls me, the first reaction is I get scared. Like, why is my father calling me? Kuch ho

00:39:46.200 --> 00:39:50.720
[Guest]: toh nahi hain, you know, dar la jata hai mujhe. And if he calls me and he's just like, how

00:39:50.720 --> 00:39:54.800
[Guest]: are you? I'm like, why? Like, what happened? That's my question. I don't like, I'm fine.

00:39:54.800 --> 00:39:59.280
[Guest]: What? I'm like, what happened? You know, that thing he might sometimes just, so I, I've

00:39:59.280 --> 00:40:04.560
[Guest]: still had that place with my father now after retirement has also wanted to like, give me

00:40:04.560 --> 00:40:12.400
[Guest]: a hug. And I'm just like, what? When do you want hugs? When he gives me a hug, when I

00:40:12.400 --> 00:40:17.080
[Guest]: give him a hug, even with somebody who kind of now talks a lot about things like empathy,

00:40:17.080 --> 00:40:20.920
[Guest]: I get so uncomfortable. I don't know, you know, when my father gives me a hug, I'm still

00:40:20.920 --> 00:40:25.400
[Guest]: like, I don't know what to do about it. I'm just like closed. I'm like, this is weird.

00:40:25.400 --> 00:40:29.120
[Guest]: This is not natural. Even though it should be the most natural thing ever, right? For

00:40:29.120 --> 00:40:33.040
[Guest]: a child to be hugged by their parent. So I feel bad about that. I want, I would love

00:40:33.040 --> 00:40:37.040
[Guest]: to change that. I don't know how to, I'm still struggling with it. On the other hand, with

00:40:37.040 --> 00:40:41.560
[Guest]: my mother, I'm really fortunate that, you know, we have gone through every cycle of

00:40:41.560 --> 00:40:47.000
[Guest]: our relationship where we've gotten really angry with each other. I stopped talking to

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:52.200
[Guest]: her almost for a year in between. And I was so angry with her not supporting me and not

00:40:52.200 --> 00:40:57.120
[Guest]: seeing me go down a path where I was very, and despaired that she wanted me to do an

00:40:57.120 --> 00:41:05.360
[Guest]: MBA. I remember like, this one time when I was at MTV, I had, my show was announced at

00:41:05.360 --> 00:41:10.720
[Guest]: 25. I had become the creator and producer, the youngest creator and producer at MTV to

00:41:10.720 --> 00:41:15.440
[Guest]: create a fiction show. I was going to be given that those credits, you know, and for anybody

00:41:15.440 --> 00:41:19.920
[Guest]: who's 25 to get that was just an insane thing in India, you know, and I called my mother

00:41:19.920 --> 00:41:22.800
[Guest]: and I said, you know what, they've announced my show. I'm only producing it. I'm also going

00:41:22.800 --> 00:41:27.760
[Guest]: to be credited as created by, you know, and she heard me out and she's just like, I can't

00:41:27.760 --> 00:41:32.360
[Guest]: forget that. She's just like, that's so good to hear. That's so great to hear. Does that,

00:41:32.360 --> 00:41:38.920
[Guest]: but does that mean you will not do an MBA? And I'm like, I just told you that at 25,

00:41:38.920 --> 00:41:46.280
[Guest]: I am going to be making a show of my own on national television. And your thing is still

00:41:46.280 --> 00:41:50.920
[Guest]: stuck on. But I mean, that's parents, right? Like, and because that's the only way that

00:41:50.920 --> 00:41:57.720
[Guest]: she knows that people become successful, because that's the only she's, she just didn't have,

00:41:57.720 --> 00:42:02.520
[Guest]: you know, she didn't have the internet to begin with. And she did not have, you know,

00:42:02.520 --> 00:42:07.040
[Guest]: enough resources would tell her that, you know, there are possibilities outside of engineering

00:42:07.040 --> 00:42:13.880
[Guest]: and MBA for a young man to be able to still find his voice and his career and make it.

00:42:13.880 --> 00:42:21.280
[Guest]: And until I joined Yashraj, I remember like the, for me, the, my greatest moment in life

00:42:21.280 --> 00:42:26.560
[Guest]: so to speak is when my mother came to Bombay and I started working in Yashraj and I had

00:42:26.560 --> 00:42:31.480
[Guest]: done pretty well over there. So I'd gotten a cabin and I'd been promoted to GM. So I'd

00:42:31.480 --> 00:42:35.960
[Guest]: got a double promotion, got, became GM at YRF and my mother had come down to Bombay.

00:42:35.960 --> 00:42:40.560
[Guest]: So I just asked her to come to the Yashraj office. I took her through, I showed her around

00:42:40.560 --> 00:42:46.240
[Guest]: the whole Yashraj campus, took her then to my floor, you know, got her to come to my

00:42:46.240 --> 00:42:49.920
[Guest]: cabin and said, this is my cabin. And then she entered and I got her to sit down to a

00:42:49.920 --> 00:42:53.480
[Guest]: picture with it. I'm like, are you feeling happy now? And she said, yes, I'm feeling

00:42:53.480 --> 00:42:58.040
[Guest]: very happy. And then I was like, okay, now it's like achieved, tick mark, you know, just

00:42:58.040 --> 00:43:02.520
[Guest]: the fact that my mother is now finally like happy with where I am in life. But at that

00:43:02.520 --> 00:43:07.880
[Guest]: time it was tough, you know, but we went through a lot, you know, we, we, you know, and, and

00:43:07.880 --> 00:43:10.440
[Guest]: I mean, that was how that happened in the marriage, which is a whole other thing that

00:43:10.440 --> 00:43:14.920
[Guest]: has happened, you know, we, there was a lot of misunderstanding between me and my mother

00:43:14.920 --> 00:43:23.240
[Guest]: and I, you know, and, but eventually I just started. And again, I think anxiety and therapy

00:43:23.240 --> 00:43:32.960
[Guest]: have been like God given gifts to me where I could tap into, you know, a lot more of

00:43:32.960 --> 00:43:39.640
[Guest]: my, you know, empathy or my emotions to be able to look at my family in different lights,

00:43:39.640 --> 00:43:43.920
[Guest]: you know, and go beyond the anger, you know, and over the last six, seven years, I have

00:43:43.920 --> 00:43:48.400
[Guest]: had such a beautiful, friendly relation with my mother. She's my closest, one of my closest

00:43:48.400 --> 00:43:53.400
[Guest]: friends, I would say, if not my closest friend, my wife is my closest friend. If she hears

00:43:53.400 --> 00:43:55.760
[Guest]: that I said something, otherwise she'll get angry.

00:43:55.760 --> 00:43:58.720
[Amit Varma]: You're getting into trouble with both people.

00:43:58.720 --> 00:44:06.040
[Guest]: Tough, tough line, but, but she's, you know, and to her credit, she has tried so hard to

00:44:06.040 --> 00:44:12.960
[Guest]: kind of be a friend to us. And I've not seen other people of her age or of her generation

00:44:12.960 --> 00:44:19.760
[Guest]: try that hard. She has tried so hard. I am so inspired. And I, I look up to her so much.

00:44:19.760 --> 00:44:24.840
[Guest]: She has done everything. She realized that her relationship with both her children was

00:44:24.840 --> 00:44:30.080
[Guest]: getting stuck at a place. We were not, wasn't going beyond that. And she did everything.

00:44:30.080 --> 00:44:36.000
[Guest]: She said, tell me what I have to do. And she did it. She's like, you know, I mean, all,

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:40.760
[Guest]: all parents, I feel after a certain point, you know, because of the patriarchal conditioning

00:44:40.760 --> 00:44:45.080
[Guest]: and everything, they have these certain, you know, whether they're homophobic, Islamophobic,

00:44:45.080 --> 00:44:49.880
[Guest]: all of these, you know, issues, just conditioned into them. She's gone beyond them. She's like

00:44:49.880 --> 00:44:53.960
[Guest]: tried when you would tell her that this is wrong, she would hear it. We'll say that,

00:44:53.960 --> 00:44:59.360
[Guest]: you know, this is misogynist. She will fight back a little bit, but then she would be like,

00:44:59.360 --> 00:45:05.640
[Guest]: okay, explain why. And she's heard it. And she's been, she's, I mean, it's incredible

00:45:05.640 --> 00:45:10.800
[Guest]: the way she has carried herself, the grace, the, she's the light of my life. I'll be very

00:45:10.800 --> 00:45:15.760
[Guest]: honest. She's like, you know, I'm my biggest fear in life, honestly, is that I don't know

00:45:15.760 --> 00:45:22.520
[Guest]: who I'll be when she's gone. I just don't know. I don't know. Like she's, she's really

00:45:22.520 --> 00:45:27.600
[Guest]: carried the family. She's carried, you know, yeah, she's even with all the pressure she

00:45:27.600 --> 00:45:32.400
[Guest]: put on me, I can't, you know, I can't, I'm just far more grateful about the kind of values

00:45:32.400 --> 00:45:37.640
[Guest]: she's inculcated in me. There are still a lot of things in me that I, I do get angry

00:45:37.640 --> 00:45:44.400
[Guest]: that, you know, it came from mother, but like, it's, you know, she's done everything to,

00:45:44.400 --> 00:45:50.440
[Guest]: you know, compensate for any time she has not been, you know, kind to us or not been

00:45:50.440 --> 00:45:56.760
[Guest]: like understanding or a good friend and just a parent in that sense. So, yeah, I'm, you

00:45:56.760 --> 00:46:02.640
[Guest]: know, as I said, in that, during my wedding, like, it was one of those things where, you

00:46:02.640 --> 00:46:06.960
[Guest]: know, we had many things happen, but like, long story short, we had reached that place

00:46:06.960 --> 00:46:15.000
[Guest]: where my parents and my wife's parents were just at loggerhead, so to speak, because they're

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:20.160
[Guest]: from Assam, we're from the Punjabis, just ridiculous things started coming up, you know,

00:46:20.160 --> 00:46:24.080
[Guest]: like, why are we having this in the, they wanted to do it in the daytime, because that's

00:46:24.080 --> 00:46:27.440
[Guest]: how they do it, and we want to do it in the night time, because that's how we do it, you

00:46:27.440 --> 00:46:31.160
[Guest]: know, they wanted non-veg, my parents were like, suddenly, my mother, who's been, while

00:46:31.160 --> 00:46:35.200
[Guest]: my family is now vegetarian and whatnot, but my mother, who would encourage my younger

00:46:35.200 --> 00:46:39.320
[Guest]: brother to eat chicken, because it gives strength, even though I'm not going to eat it, suddenly

00:46:39.320 --> 00:46:45.360
[Guest]: I was like, no, we will never have non-veg on our wedding, like, what is this, like ridiculous

00:46:45.360 --> 00:46:51.000
[Guest]: things, so, you know, and I remember, like, things came to such a head that I was just

00:46:51.000 --> 00:46:55.840
[Guest]: again getting really, like, I was very frustrated in my wedding, because I feel like I was,

00:46:55.840 --> 00:47:01.280
[Guest]: I was getting myself married, like, because my parents anyway live, they don't live in

00:47:01.280 --> 00:47:06.160
[Guest]: the country, so I was just very, again, just my father is just, doesn't know what to do,

00:47:06.160 --> 00:47:10.680
[Guest]: he's just like a tourist to my marriage, he's come as a guest, no idea, what's happening,

00:47:10.680 --> 00:47:13.840
[Guest]: what's not happening, the whole wedding, the whole location, I got everything done, my

00:47:13.840 --> 00:47:16.480
[Guest]: mother's tried her best, but she also doesn't live in India, beyond a point, what can she

00:47:16.480 --> 00:47:21.160
[Guest]: do, so I was also very, I was like, I'm getting married now, you need to just, you know, I

00:47:21.160 --> 00:47:26.560
[Guest]: know that you have more sense and more love than this, you've been a good mother to me,

00:47:26.560 --> 00:47:30.280
[Guest]: why are you making such a big thing out of such a small stupid thing, and then she said

00:47:30.280 --> 00:47:34.600
[Guest]: during that time, the first time I think we've had an honest conversation, where she told

00:47:34.600 --> 00:47:41.400
[Guest]: me that, you know, you've always done what you wanted, you've always, and I didn't say

00:47:41.400 --> 00:47:46.200
[Guest]: anything, which is lies, she told me lots of things, but she's like, you finish engineering

00:47:46.200 --> 00:47:51.240
[Guest]: and then you decide to go to Hindustan Times, you've said that you're gonna marry a Punjabi

00:47:51.240 --> 00:47:54.680
[Guest]: girl and then you went and married an Aziz girl, you said you'll not do media, you did

00:47:54.680 --> 00:48:00.080
[Guest]: that, everything has been like against what we wanted, but we didn't say anything, but

00:48:00.080 --> 00:48:05.200
[Guest]: like this is the, and then she said this thing that, you know, again, just has remained in

00:48:05.200 --> 00:48:09.800
[Guest]: my head where she said that, you know, but when it comes to the marriage, right, that's

00:48:09.800 --> 00:48:14.600
[Guest]: the last time your parents get to have a say in your life, after that it's your life, after

00:48:14.600 --> 00:48:19.400
[Guest]: that where will we come, you know, but this is the thing that we get to do, and this is

00:48:19.400 --> 00:48:26.280
[Guest]: the last thing we get to do, so, you know, if you're not letting us do this, then like,

00:48:26.280 --> 00:48:31.680
[Guest]: you know, I just feel like I don't have a stake in your life, and I don't know what

00:48:31.680 --> 00:48:36.200
[Guest]: to do as a mother, and I just, that honest thing that happened, and I was just like,

00:48:36.200 --> 00:48:39.640
[Guest]: man, if you had said this earlier, all this wouldn't have happened, so I just said, we

00:48:39.640 --> 00:48:43.280
[Guest]: will do what you want, and then we did everything, I mean, we did everything, we said like what

00:48:43.280 --> 00:48:48.880
[Guest]: functions do you want, I convinced her parents, I just made sure, we did like three versions

00:48:48.880 --> 00:48:53.400
[Guest]: of the marriage, we went to Assam to kind of, you know, to be with Daisy's parents and appease

00:48:53.400 --> 00:48:57.840
[Guest]: her family, went to Bahrain again, did a whole function for my family, in the wedding, we

00:48:57.840 --> 00:49:01.760
[Guest]: said what all we have to do, we will do everything, you just, you know, you want to do this, we

00:49:01.760 --> 00:49:06.080
[Guest]: will do it your way, you know, don't feel like, it means so much to me, everything that

00:49:06.080 --> 00:49:09.640
[Guest]: you have done for me, so, that is the moment I think where I started looking at her not

00:49:09.640 --> 00:49:14.840
[Guest]: as my mother, but like as a human being, and I feel like that's one of the first times

00:49:14.840 --> 00:49:21.360
[Guest]: that I realized that, you know, where I have been, you know, I just realized that, you

00:49:21.360 --> 00:49:27.840
[Guest]: know, this person's son is getting married, you know, my mother's son is getting married,

00:49:27.840 --> 00:49:30.000
[Guest]: and she should also have a stake in that, right?

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:32.360
[Guest]: Why am I making such a big deal out of it?

00:49:32.360 --> 00:49:38.920
[Guest]: So yeah, I think it's been a journey to understanding my parents, but I'm, yeah, I'm more grateful

00:49:38.920 --> 00:49:43.120
[Guest]: than, you know, regretful of the things that have happened so far.

00:49:43.120 --> 00:49:48.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I was very struck by that, that beautiful story of that conversation and similar because

00:49:48.520 --> 00:49:53.520
[Amit Varma]: it is a rare moment of honesty that, you know, people can't often see themselves so well

00:49:53.520 --> 00:49:58.240
[Amit Varma]: as she saw herself in that moment and was able to express, you know, one of my favorite

00:49:58.240 --> 00:50:04.280
[Amit Varma]: phrases in literature, which I think expresses a human condition so well is Thoreau's phrase,

00:50:04.280 --> 00:50:09.800
[Amit Varma]: lives of quiet desperation, right, and I think most people definitely so in all the generations

00:50:09.800 --> 00:50:12.760
[Amit Varma]: before us, live lives of quiet desperation.

00:50:12.760 --> 00:50:18.560
[Amit Varma]: And I think part of that desperation doesn't necessarily come from things like monetary

00:50:18.560 --> 00:50:21.360
[Amit Varma]: circumstances or all those other things.

00:50:21.360 --> 00:50:25.160
[Amit Varma]: It comes from just being trapped in a groove that this is a groove that has been laid out

00:50:25.160 --> 00:50:26.160
[Unknown]: for you.

00:50:26.160 --> 00:50:33.320
[Amit Varma]: You know, the man has to be the owner, he has to be the stern man, he cannot show emotion,

00:50:33.320 --> 00:50:39.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, all of that and the mother's got a different role and everything you said about

00:50:39.240 --> 00:50:45.720
[Amit Varma]: your parents was so resonant with me, I can, you know, recognize all of that.

00:50:45.720 --> 00:50:52.240
[Amit Varma]: And in general, the great human tragedy has been that the illusion never lifts, the layers

00:50:52.240 --> 00:50:56.320
[Amit Varma]: never go, which is why I was interested if you, you know, managed to speak about them

00:50:56.320 --> 00:51:02.480
[Amit Varma]: later about all of this, because I think most of us who get on these grooves and live out

00:51:02.480 --> 00:51:07.200
[Amit Varma]: that quiet desperation, we can't express it, we can't acknowledge it even to ourselves.

00:51:07.200 --> 00:51:08.440
[Amit Varma]: And we are passing it on.

00:51:08.440 --> 00:51:15.240
[Amit Varma]: Like one of my favorite poems by Philip Larkin has these great lines, man hands on misery

00:51:15.240 --> 00:51:18.440
[Amit Varma]: to man, it deepens like a coastal shelf.

00:51:18.440 --> 00:51:22.140
[Amit Varma]: And that's such a lovely poetic image, it deepens like a coastal shelf, right.

00:51:22.140 --> 00:51:26.440
[Amit Varma]: And of course, the poem is trying to convince people not to have children.

00:51:26.440 --> 00:51:31.200
[Amit Varma]: For just this reason, man hands on misery to man, it deepens like a coastal shelf.

00:51:31.200 --> 00:51:37.240
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that you've written eloquently about is firstly, these traps of

00:51:37.240 --> 00:51:39.080
[Amit Varma]: getting trapped in these roles.

00:51:39.080 --> 00:51:45.880
[Amit Varma]: And also the fact that this might be the one generation, you know, especially Gen Z digital

00:51:45.880 --> 00:51:52.680
[Amit Varma]: natives exposed to the world growing up on the internet, who have access to other truths,

00:51:52.680 --> 00:51:58.600
[Amit Varma]: who don't have to, you know, follow these lanes that are laid out for them by patriarchy

00:51:58.600 --> 00:52:02.520
[Amit Varma]: or by conservative Indian society or any of that.

00:52:02.520 --> 00:52:06.800
[Amit Varma]: And you've spoken about this a lot, and I'll put all those links in the show notes also.

00:52:06.800 --> 00:52:13.760
[Amit Varma]: But I'd also like you to talk about how your realization of this evolved about these strict

00:52:13.760 --> 00:52:20.600
[Amit Varma]: roles, these lanes that are laid out, tell me a little bit about how your realization

00:52:20.600 --> 00:52:26.560
[Amit Varma]: of this evolved and then going through time, you know, like, because once you realize it,

00:52:26.560 --> 00:52:31.440
[Amit Varma]: you can't unsee it, you know, it's absolutely, it's never unseen again.

00:52:31.440 --> 00:52:35.440
[Amit Varma]: And you will see it in every face that you look into, you will see it, right, you will,

00:52:35.440 --> 00:52:37.000
[Amit Varma]: you will hear it in their stories.

00:52:37.000 --> 00:52:44.880
[Guest]: Tell me a little bit about that journey for you and what Yeah, you know, so I think, again,

00:52:44.880 --> 00:52:50.800
[Guest]: you know, I saw all of it at home without registering, you know, that this is, I just

00:52:50.800 --> 00:52:56.160
[Guest]: knew that this is wrong, my mother shouldn't be constantly, you know, in the service of

00:52:56.160 --> 00:52:57.920
[Guest]: my father.

00:52:57.920 --> 00:52:58.920
[Guest]: She should.

00:52:58.920 --> 00:53:07.920
[Guest]: My mother used to be a professor of economics, even she had an MA in economics at Kurukshetra

00:53:07.920 --> 00:53:15.960
[Guest]: University, and then she had taught it to students over there when she was 23, 24.

00:53:15.960 --> 00:53:17.880
[Guest]: She's a wonderful painter.

00:53:17.880 --> 00:53:21.800
[Guest]: She's I mean, she's one of the smartest I'm telling you, she's like, it's insane how multifaceted

00:53:21.800 --> 00:53:22.800
[Guest]: she is.

00:53:22.800 --> 00:53:28.200
[Guest]: You know, tell her anything and she'll do it, you know, I remember this one moment,

00:53:28.200 --> 00:53:33.480
[Guest]: you know, where we were at this really random place called workshop called born to excel,

00:53:33.480 --> 00:53:38.440
[Guest]: where these folks had come to kind of give young people how to the methods of excelling

00:53:38.440 --> 00:53:41.640
[Guest]: or whatever is a summer course that you are getting enrolled in.

00:53:41.640 --> 00:53:46.200
[Guest]: And you know, the first time he asked the question, the man over the workshop, and he

00:53:46.200 --> 00:53:50.600
[Guest]: was like, Well, I have a question that if there is a let's see which young person answers,

00:53:50.600 --> 00:53:56.360
[Guest]: you know, and there is a bucket, and in that bucket, there is, you know, a ball, how do

00:53:56.360 --> 00:54:03.760
[Guest]: you take it out without your hand, you know, and, and, and then everybody was like, giving

00:54:03.760 --> 00:54:04.760
[Guest]: all kinds of answers.

00:54:04.760 --> 00:54:08.360
[Guest]: Nobody's like, you know, you can't turn it over, or you have to keep it in etc.

00:54:08.360 --> 00:54:11.360
[Guest]: And then a mother was the one who's like, when you put water into it, and then it'll

00:54:11.360 --> 00:54:12.360
[Guest]: come up on its own.

00:54:12.360 --> 00:54:15.640
[Guest]: And, you know, in this case, like, yes, that's the right answer.

00:54:15.640 --> 00:54:16.640
[Guest]: Never got this answer.

00:54:16.640 --> 00:54:21.240
[Guest]: My mother is so sharp, you know, so she's, she's very creative.

00:54:21.240 --> 00:54:25.000
[Guest]: She writes poems at now also, she's like at 66 now.

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:28.440
[Guest]: And she has these wonderful poems for my birthday, she will write a poem and narrate it by my

00:54:28.440 --> 00:54:30.200
[Guest]: wife's birthday.

00:54:30.200 --> 00:54:36.360
[Guest]: So beautiful, you know, and so yeah, I kind of knew always that, you know, there is, it's

00:54:36.360 --> 00:54:37.360
[Guest]: not right.

00:54:37.360 --> 00:54:42.240
[Guest]: But, you know, and I just wanted to be the opposite of that didn't realize that genders.

00:54:42.240 --> 00:54:44.480
[Guest]: If anybody would ask me, what is identity?

00:54:44.480 --> 00:54:49.360
[Guest]: You know, it's a question that now, I think a lot about, especially in the world we live

00:54:49.360 --> 00:54:56.040
[Guest]: in right now, how identity has become so, you know, become such a big issue.

00:54:56.040 --> 00:55:02.640
[Guest]: And how we have now reframed every, you know, our identities into nationalism, right?

00:55:02.640 --> 00:55:07.360
[Guest]: But when you ask, you know, when we were growing up and you ask, what's your identity?

00:55:07.360 --> 00:55:10.960
[Guest]: You wouldn't I mean, I don't know, Indian was maybe one thing you would say, you know,

00:55:10.960 --> 00:55:16.600
[Guest]: I would say engineer, because all the boys are engineers, you know, be taken in computer

00:55:16.600 --> 00:55:17.600
[Guest]: engineering.

00:55:17.600 --> 00:55:18.600
[Guest]: That's my identity.

00:55:18.600 --> 00:55:21.800
[Guest]: You know, somebody would say a writer, somebody say artist, you know, those were the ways

00:55:21.800 --> 00:55:23.920
[Guest]: that you would define yourself, right?

00:55:23.920 --> 00:55:27.640
[Guest]: I would never think of gender as an identity that like, like when you ask a woman this,

00:55:27.640 --> 00:55:32.840
[Guest]: what's your identity, she will say woman, because every day of her life, she's reminded

00:55:32.840 --> 00:55:37.560
[Guest]: that you're a woman through the way our systems are structured, but men are not, would never

00:55:37.560 --> 00:55:41.800
[Guest]: say, although now they are saying because of I think, in a post-media world, every man

00:55:41.800 --> 00:55:47.160
[Guest]: suddenly has become more aware of their identity, which is a whole thing, but, but before that,

00:55:47.160 --> 00:55:51.040
[Guest]: it was never the thing that, you know, I'm a man that was never it, it was always designation

00:55:51.040 --> 00:55:57.840
[Guest]: when I'm a CEO, or I'm a, you know, again, engineer, I'm the owner of these houses, or

00:55:57.840 --> 00:56:03.000
[Guest]: you know, I have this much property, your numbers would define your identity, as a young

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:06.960
[Guest]: as a man, and you think about it, it all comes down to your reduced your worth is reduced

00:56:06.960 --> 00:56:07.960
[Guest]: to numbers.

00:56:07.960 --> 00:56:13.720
[Guest]: It's, it's about how many marks you got, how many trophies you won, how many extracurriculars

00:56:13.720 --> 00:56:19.680
[Guest]: you participated in, you know, everything, everything is monetizable, everything is,

00:56:19.680 --> 00:56:22.520
[Guest]: you know, has to have a worth attached to it.

00:56:22.520 --> 00:56:27.200
[Guest]: You can't even have as a hobby, I remember like when you're going up, and I'd read like

00:56:27.200 --> 00:56:30.680
[Guest]: a lot and you know, and then sometimes we like instead of reading this, why don't you

00:56:30.680 --> 00:56:34.600
[Guest]: read your school textbooks, because that's the way you will get more marks, you know,

00:56:34.600 --> 00:56:37.760
[Guest]: you'd play something, you know, if you're, if instead of doing this, why don't you do

00:56:37.760 --> 00:56:39.980
[Guest]: this thing and take part in this competition.

00:56:39.980 --> 00:56:46.840
[Guest]: So even a hobby needed to be something that is a is in service of a victory or an achievement

00:56:46.840 --> 00:56:50.900
[Guest]: you needed to have, you know, and then how many of these achievements did you have was

00:56:50.900 --> 00:56:56.880
[Guest]: what would define you as a man, then salaries became a thing, then you know, then packages,

00:56:56.880 --> 00:57:02.560
[Guest]: CTCs, then the number of houses that you have the number of cars, you have everything, everything.

00:57:02.560 --> 00:57:08.440
[Guest]: It's all been like a, you know, we've just been reduced to numbers as identities, right?

00:57:08.440 --> 00:57:09.440
[Guest]: And we don't think about that.

00:57:09.440 --> 00:57:10.440
[Guest]: That's just how it is.

00:57:10.440 --> 00:57:13.160
[Guest]: That's just normalized.

00:57:13.160 --> 00:57:20.400
[Guest]: And and but somewhere I kind of subconsciously or unconsciously started recognizing or started

00:57:20.400 --> 00:57:24.800
[Guest]: feeling that, you know, everything that I'm going through, as somebody who was fighting

00:57:24.800 --> 00:57:28.480
[Guest]: this idea that after engineering, I don't want to do this.

00:57:28.480 --> 00:57:35.120
[Guest]: I'd gotten jobs in, you know, I was in NID Gurukshetra, like Mahima, and, you know, I

00:57:35.120 --> 00:57:37.640
[Guest]: was also taking part in all that.

00:57:37.640 --> 00:57:42.160
[Guest]: So I realized in the first six months that I can't do this.

00:57:42.160 --> 00:57:47.160
[Guest]: And that's a very big thing for someone who used to be a really like, I was a good student

00:57:47.160 --> 00:57:52.760
[Guest]: in school, like I cared about computing, computer science, I used to code, I used to enjoy coding.

00:57:52.760 --> 00:57:56.880
[Guest]: And then six months of NID Gurukshetra and while it is somewhat also a reflection of

00:57:56.880 --> 00:58:00.720
[Guest]: the college, while I don't think it's entirely that, I just feel it's just engineering as

00:58:00.720 --> 00:58:03.360
[Guest]: a setup, you know, and you go in there and six months, you're just like, what the hell

00:58:03.360 --> 00:58:04.520
[Guest]: is going on.

00:58:04.520 --> 00:58:07.560
[Guest]: And when you realize that you can't do this, then you have three and a half years to figure

00:58:07.560 --> 00:58:08.560
[Guest]: out what to do.

00:58:08.560 --> 00:58:14.720
[Guest]: You know, I feel like that's like a, I always joke and say this that, you know, in the US,

00:58:14.720 --> 00:58:20.280
[Guest]: you'd have people would give after 12th standard, you know, to their children, a gap year.

00:58:20.280 --> 00:58:23.480
[Guest]: You go and have a gap year, travel the world, find out who you are.

00:58:23.480 --> 00:58:28.480
[Guest]: In India, there is a gap year for boys, engineering college, go for engineering, then you do what

00:58:28.480 --> 00:58:29.960
[Guest]: you want to do in life, right?

00:58:29.960 --> 00:58:34.040
[Guest]: So I was, it was that on me, I went there and then I was like, okay, now I have this

00:58:34.040 --> 00:58:37.760
[Guest]: time and I don't want to quit because again, I'm a man, so I can't just quit.

00:58:37.760 --> 00:58:39.040
[Guest]: So I will go through this.

00:58:39.040 --> 00:58:42.560
[Guest]: I will somehow, I'll do what it needs to pass and I'll do what it needs to get exams.

00:58:42.560 --> 00:58:45.960
[Guest]: I know that I'm not interested in this anymore, but what can I do with my time over here?

00:58:45.960 --> 00:58:49.880
[Guest]: So I started, you know, again, doing more writing work, I start, you know, there's a

00:58:49.880 --> 00:58:55.800
[Guest]: magazine that I got to be a part of that I created a magazine, a college magazine out

00:58:55.800 --> 00:58:59.560
[Guest]: of the last entity and last version of what it was.

00:58:59.560 --> 00:59:05.800
[Guest]: It used to be a paper, you know, like two papers on a wall stuck as that was the college

00:59:05.800 --> 00:59:06.800
[Guest]: magazine culture.

00:59:06.800 --> 00:59:12.520
[Guest]: I created a whole, you know, 30-40 pager proper magazine.

00:59:12.520 --> 00:59:16.880
[Guest]: I got into Vishwanathan Anand with Ranbir Kapoor and said like, this is your magazine

00:59:16.880 --> 00:59:20.120
[Guest]: now, like, here's what it can be.

00:59:20.120 --> 00:59:24.200
[Guest]: I used to, I mean, again, with the official college magazine, became the editor like Mahima

00:59:24.200 --> 00:59:32.080
[Guest]: as the one after so, you know, and all of and at college, I kind of just did everything

00:59:32.080 --> 00:59:33.080
[Guest]: I could.

00:59:33.080 --> 00:59:35.280
[Guest]: I took part in every extracurricular thing.

00:59:35.280 --> 00:59:39.100
[Guest]: Now it's reverse because I talk about identity also, as I said earlier, you know, I used

00:59:39.100 --> 00:59:41.560
[Guest]: to be someone who is to always be the outside looking in.

00:59:41.560 --> 00:59:47.680
[Guest]: Suddenly, as somebody who had a little bit of, I mean, I became aware of my privilege

00:59:47.680 --> 00:59:48.680
[Guest]: at that time.

00:59:48.680 --> 00:59:49.680
[Guest]: So it is a digression.

00:59:49.680 --> 00:59:51.160
[Guest]: I'll go back into your question.

00:59:51.160 --> 00:59:58.440
[Guest]: But NIT Gurushetra is when I immediately, instantly became aware of my privilege.

00:59:58.440 --> 01:00:04.200
[Guest]: It is a and anybody who knows the way NITs function, you have 50% quota from the same

01:00:04.200 --> 01:00:05.760
[Guest]: state and 50% of the rest of the country.

01:00:05.760 --> 01:00:08.080
[Guest]: So there was everybody from every place.

01:00:08.080 --> 01:00:14.880
[Guest]: And most people were, you know, were not, so to speak, that privileged or, you know,

01:00:14.880 --> 01:00:19.000
[Guest]: that came, came from a certain kind of, and I recognize this on the very first conversation

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:25.200
[Guest]: I had in a mess, which, you know, I had no idea what is caste, you know, and as they

01:00:25.200 --> 01:00:27.600
[Guest]: say that, you know, if you're upper caste, you don't know what it is, right.

01:00:27.600 --> 01:00:33.680
[Guest]: But I never knew and, and I remember the first conversation I had with, you know, someone

01:00:33.680 --> 01:00:39.120
[Guest]: in the mess and the boy said, I asked him, like, what do you do, I mean, which, which,

01:00:39.120 --> 01:00:42.520
[Guest]: you know, where are you from, he said, Panipat, oh great, I'm from Karnal, great, something

01:00:42.520 --> 01:00:43.520
[Guest]: in common.

01:00:43.520 --> 01:00:45.280
[Guest]: Then like, what are you doing over here?

01:00:45.280 --> 01:00:48.720
[Guest]: I'm doing engineering, computers, he's doing whatever electric, electronics, mechanical,

01:00:48.720 --> 01:00:55.160
[Guest]: okay, fine, you know, we'll not the same thing, not the same course, but whatever.

01:00:55.160 --> 01:00:59.600
[Guest]: And then I'd asked him, and this is my always my regular normal follow up question, what

01:00:59.600 --> 01:01:01.280
[Guest]: does your father do?

01:01:01.280 --> 01:01:05.840
[Guest]: That's just the question that everybody asks, you know, or at least I assumed that, because

01:01:05.840 --> 01:01:07.520
[Guest]: I was always asked to me.

01:01:07.520 --> 01:01:10.560
[Guest]: And you know, when I was in Dubai and Bahrain, and that's how we kind of like, what does

01:01:10.560 --> 01:01:11.560
[Guest]: your father do?

01:01:11.560 --> 01:01:15.000
[Guest]: You buy my father is working here, my father's working there, whatever it is.

01:01:15.000 --> 01:01:19.560
[Guest]: And here the answer was that, well, he's works, he works in a garage.

01:01:19.560 --> 01:01:24.240
[Guest]: In my, you know, my upper caste mind, I was just like, oh, he owns the garage.

01:01:24.240 --> 01:01:26.200
[Guest]: He's like, no, no works in it.

01:01:26.200 --> 01:01:31.160
[Guest]: And then I was like, in my again, I can't fathom I'm just like, so, like, does he

01:01:31.160 --> 01:01:35.960
[Guest]: have like this car, big cars, and he works with big cars and because he's like, no, he

01:01:35.960 --> 01:01:37.760
[Guest]: repairs bicycles.

01:01:37.760 --> 01:01:41.280
[Guest]: And I was suddenly I was like, wait, what?

01:01:41.280 --> 01:01:49.080
[Guest]: Like, you know, I mean, it was such a big that everything I used to feel about class,

01:01:49.080 --> 01:01:53.640
[Guest]: you know, before I came, because I was the one outsider looking in into these rich folks

01:01:53.640 --> 01:01:57.400
[Guest]: in these schools, where everybody where they would talk about like, what do you do after

01:01:57.400 --> 01:01:58.400
[Guest]: class?

01:01:58.400 --> 01:02:04.280
[Guest]: So I have like a, you know, I have an instructor who comes in to play the, you know, piano

