[Guest]: They've been lonely.

01:41:01.920 --> 01:41:06.720
[Guest]: And now that loneliness has turned into anger and resentment because nobody is trying to

01:41:06.720 --> 01:41:11.560
[Guest]: have sensitive conversations about gender with them, saying that now we live in a world

01:41:11.560 --> 01:41:18.040
[Guest]: where it's also okay for you not to be the version of a boy or a man that Petra K tells

01:41:18.040 --> 01:41:19.120
[Guest]: you to be.

01:41:19.120 --> 01:41:20.760
[Guest]: It is okay to not hustle as hard.

01:41:20.760 --> 01:41:22.440
[Guest]: It is okay not to work as hard.

01:41:22.440 --> 01:41:23.520
[Guest]: It is okay to have hobbies.

01:41:23.520 --> 01:41:24.800
[Guest]: It is okay to have work-life balance.

01:41:24.800 --> 01:41:25.800
[Guest]: It is okay to cry.

01:41:25.800 --> 01:41:30.800
[Guest]: It is okay to, you know, just spend time, you know, without being productive.

01:41:30.800 --> 01:41:38.400
[Guest]: It is okay to, you know, not want to, you know, harm yourself because you're failing

01:41:38.400 --> 01:41:39.760
[Guest]: in an exam.

01:41:39.760 --> 01:41:45.800
[Guest]: It is okay to fail in exams and do something else apart from engineering and MBA.

01:41:45.800 --> 01:41:47.280
[Guest]: Every one of these things is okay.

01:41:47.280 --> 01:41:49.000
[Guest]: It is absolutely okay.

01:41:49.000 --> 01:41:51.120
[Guest]: You don't have to try so hard.

01:41:51.120 --> 01:41:53.960
[Guest]: You don't have to be so hard on yourself.

01:41:53.960 --> 01:41:59.080
[Guest]: And that anger is also the anger historically we see with all our parents.

01:41:59.080 --> 01:42:05.600
[Guest]: Why are most of our fathers angry or violent or alcoholic?

01:42:05.600 --> 01:42:13.600
[Guest]: Because for the same reason, they've just buried it all inside without having any avenues

01:42:13.600 --> 01:42:14.840
[Guest]: to express.

01:42:14.840 --> 01:42:19.520
[Guest]: Anytime they were expressed, anytime they would express, they would be looked down upon.

01:42:19.520 --> 01:42:23.520
[Guest]: I told you that I thought my father was weak because he used to, you know, I thought he

01:42:23.520 --> 01:42:25.960
[Guest]: was weak because he was going through anxiety.

01:42:25.960 --> 01:42:29.480
[Guest]: And I used to look at it as, you know, whenever he would talk about it, complain about it

01:42:29.480 --> 01:42:34.400
[Guest]: or go through something, I would just, I would look, you know, what kind of a man is he?

01:42:34.400 --> 01:42:37.040
[Guest]: Because that was what was conditioned into me that boys can't, every time I would have

01:42:37.040 --> 01:42:40.480
[Guest]: a scrape, you know, somebody would come and tell me, you're crying like a girl.

01:42:40.480 --> 01:42:45.880
[Guest]: You know, now if girls cry and boys don't cry, and now I can't cry and I can't have

01:42:45.880 --> 01:42:50.240
[Guest]: an healthy outburst of emotion, and I'm always going to be looked down upon as a sensitive

01:42:50.240 --> 01:42:53.720
[Guest]: boy just because I'm crying, then I'd much rather not cry.

01:42:53.720 --> 01:42:54.720
[Guest]: And that becomes toxic.

01:42:54.720 --> 01:42:56.400
[Guest]: And that becomes, that turns into anger.

01:42:56.400 --> 01:43:00.880
[Guest]: And that turns into, you know, whatever you see in the world right now.

01:43:00.880 --> 01:43:03.480
[Guest]: So it is, we need to have these conversations.

01:43:03.480 --> 01:43:06.360
[Guest]: I'm so grateful to therapy.

01:43:06.360 --> 01:43:08.960
[Guest]: I'm so grateful to anxiety.

01:43:08.960 --> 01:43:15.280
[Guest]: I'm so grateful to my own mental health issues for leading me to a place where today I can

01:43:15.280 --> 01:43:18.960
[Guest]: I recognize these patterns in my own life.

01:43:18.960 --> 01:43:25.280
[Guest]: I'm trying as hard as possible to overcome any of the toxicity inside of me that still

01:43:25.280 --> 01:43:27.920
[Guest]: remains as a product of patriarchy.

01:43:27.920 --> 01:43:34.080
[Guest]: And I am dedicating a lot of my life to having these conversations about gender with all

01:43:34.080 --> 01:43:41.560
[Guest]: genders, you know, with women, men, and other genders to kind of tell them that you don't

01:43:41.560 --> 01:43:45.560
[Guest]: have to be defined by a single story that patriarchy gives you.

01:43:45.560 --> 01:43:47.840
[Guest]: You can have any story you want.

01:43:47.840 --> 01:43:51.800
[Guest]: You know, you need to fight back against patriarchy, you need to fight back against it.

01:43:51.800 --> 01:43:55.840
[Amit Varma]: These are such incredibly insightful and inspiring points.

01:43:55.840 --> 01:43:59.960
[Amit Varma]: And I want to read out this lovely para from one of your pieces, where you wrote, quote,

01:43:59.960 --> 01:44:04.320
[Amit Varma]: it is tragic that we live in a world where even as patriarchy benefits men, it first

01:44:04.320 --> 01:44:08.320
[Amit Varma]: oppresses the boys they once were, the boys who could have grown up not necessarily to

01:44:08.320 --> 01:44:12.720
[Amit Varma]: be engineers or doctors or MBAs, but perhaps poets and artists and dancers if they were

01:44:12.720 --> 01:44:17.560
[Amit Varma]: allowed to be the boys who could have grown up, not necessarily to constantly and continually

01:44:17.560 --> 01:44:22.480
[Amit Varma]: work for money, but perhaps be present fathers and husbands, the boys who could have grown

01:44:22.480 --> 01:44:28.280
[Amit Varma]: up without a stigma against feeling vulnerable, punishing any perceived weakness through violence,

01:44:28.280 --> 01:44:33.600
[Amit Varma]: but perhaps be kinder and gentler to the world around and to themselves, stop quote, and

01:44:33.600 --> 01:44:36.920
[Amit Varma]: the story from your engineering college about you know, you asking for that girl's number

01:44:36.920 --> 01:44:41.920
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, that reminded me of a story, a friend of mine told me in Hyderabad recently,

01:44:41.920 --> 01:44:43.440
[Amit Varma]: which ends in a great line.

01:44:43.440 --> 01:44:47.480
[Amit Varma]: So I've always remembered it, which is that basically, he was in an athletic delegation,

01:44:47.480 --> 01:44:52.480
[Amit Varma]: so he had gone for some sports event to Haryana, one of these Haryana towns, perhaps even Karnal.

01:44:52.480 --> 01:44:57.360
[Amit Varma]: So there, there was also a local girls team or whatever, he got talking to one of the

01:44:57.360 --> 01:45:00.080
[Amit Varma]: girls and they were friendly and they hung out and all.

01:45:00.080 --> 01:45:04.080
[Amit Varma]: And that evening in the place where they were staying, a bunch of Haryanvi boys came and

01:45:04.080 --> 01:45:08.040
[Amit Varma]: they beat him up, because one of those guys had been trying to put out the girl and the

01:45:08.040 --> 01:45:09.760
[Amit Varma]: girl wasn't giving him line of day.

01:45:09.760 --> 01:45:11.200
[Amit Varma]: So they beat him up.

01:45:11.200 --> 01:45:12.800
[Amit Varma]: And they beat him up and they go.

01:45:12.800 --> 01:45:16.640
[Amit Varma]: And then like in your case, that boy comes back.

01:45:16.640 --> 01:45:19.920
[Amit Varma]: And this guy is like, what you've already beaten me up.

01:45:19.920 --> 01:45:24.520
[Amit Varma]: And the guy just looks very sad and you know, and then he looks at him.

01:45:24.520 --> 01:45:30.200
[Amit Varma]: And he brings his face close to him and whispers, daagi toh laal hai, right?

01:45:30.200 --> 01:45:34.760
[Amit Varma]: And just the way it was said, daagi toh laal hai, I remember it for that reason.

01:45:34.760 --> 01:45:40.080
[Amit Varma]: But it's also very poignant, because the boys who beat up this boy, like you pointed out,

01:45:40.080 --> 01:45:41.080
[Amit Varma]: they are also trapped.

01:45:41.080 --> 01:45:42.560
[Amit Varma]: They're also victims.

01:45:42.560 --> 01:45:48.680
[Amit Varma]: But the thing is, that like you so wisely said, women now have the tools and the language

01:45:48.680 --> 01:45:51.000
[Amit Varma]: and the frames to understand this.

01:45:51.000 --> 01:45:56.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, they may not always have the privilege or the circumstances to act upon it.

01:45:56.240 --> 01:46:00.440
[Amit Varma]: But the language is there, the frames are there, they can understand it, they can understand

01:46:00.440 --> 01:46:01.440
[Amit Varma]: what's happening to them.

01:46:01.440 --> 01:46:06.080
[Amit Varma]: And they can, you know, even if they can't always fight it effectively.

01:46:06.080 --> 01:46:07.820
[Amit Varma]: It's there out there.

01:46:07.820 --> 01:46:10.760
[Amit Varma]: But for men, it is not there.

01:46:10.760 --> 01:46:11.760
[Amit Varma]: Men have no clue.

01:46:11.760 --> 01:46:15.440
[Amit Varma]: I did an episode with Sringda Poonam many years back when this was a shorter show on

01:46:15.440 --> 01:46:18.440
[Guest]: her lovely book, Dreamers.

01:46:18.440 --> 01:46:24.240
[Amit Varma]: And there she spoke about how while girls throughout small town India are asserting

01:46:24.240 --> 01:46:27.600
[Amit Varma]: themselves, the boys are just confused, boss.

01:46:27.600 --> 01:46:28.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:46:28.600 --> 01:46:29.600
[Unknown]: Kuch samajh mein nahi aa raha hai.

01:46:29.600 --> 01:46:30.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:46:30.600 --> 01:46:31.600
[Amit Varma]: Kuch samajh mein nahi aa raha hai.

01:46:31.600 --> 01:46:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, what role, you know, when we look at why society is the way it is, you

01:46:39.000 --> 01:46:43.320
[Amit Varma]: know, one of the really interesting points you made, which I want to ask you about, is

01:46:43.320 --> 01:46:44.600
[Amit Varma]: the role of popular culture.

01:46:44.600 --> 01:46:49.080
[Amit Varma]: Because typically, one looks at popular culture as a reflection of society.

01:46:49.080 --> 01:46:53.080
[Amit Varma]: And the point you made, boss, here it works as much the other way.

01:46:53.080 --> 01:46:55.920
[Amit Varma]: That popular culture can actually shape society.

01:46:55.920 --> 01:47:02.240
[Amit Varma]: And our popular culture is really all about toxic masculinity, like Bollywood kya hai

01:47:02.240 --> 01:47:03.240
[Unknown]: yaar.

01:47:03.240 --> 01:47:07.800
[Amit Varma]: Bollywood is basically about, you know, to romance a girl there is basically to stalk

01:47:07.800 --> 01:47:10.360
[Amit Varma]: her and harass her and so on and so forth.

01:47:10.360 --> 01:47:13.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, the men are entitled and the women eventually give in.

01:47:13.240 --> 01:47:17.000
[Amit Varma]: So, is there kind of change happening?

01:47:17.000 --> 01:47:20.720
[Amit Varma]: Because very clearly, in terms of women, in terms of the material available to them, the

01:47:20.720 --> 01:47:25.880
[Amit Varma]: frames available to them, the language available to them, at least the change is out there.

01:47:25.880 --> 01:47:29.640
[Amit Varma]: But in terms of men, it's still the great unseen.

01:47:29.640 --> 01:47:35.600
[Amit Varma]: Most men can live their entire lives without thinking of themselves in any way, as victims

01:47:35.600 --> 01:47:36.600
[Amit Varma]: of this.

01:47:36.600 --> 01:47:40.760
[Amit Varma]: Like earlier, you mentioned about how on day one, you know, when you had that conversation

01:47:40.760 --> 01:47:44.520
[Amit Varma]: with that friend of yours whose father or dad worked in a garage, that a layer fell

01:47:44.520 --> 01:47:48.080
[Unknown]: from your eyes that you see your privilege, class ka.

01:47:48.080 --> 01:47:54.000
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, you spoke about how women always have the awareness that they are women, right?

01:47:54.000 --> 01:47:55.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's true.

01:47:55.000 --> 01:47:59.720
[Amit Varma]: Most men don't realize that women are walking around with an extra layer of awareness ki

01:47:59.720 --> 01:48:03.720
[Amit Varma]: raat ko walk ke liye jaana hai, so you have to think, you enter a lift, you're looking

01:48:03.720 --> 01:48:05.080
[Amit Varma]: at everybody else.

01:48:05.080 --> 01:48:10.360
[Amit Varma]: You always have that extra layer of awareness in your head, which men don't, right?

01:48:10.360 --> 01:48:15.920
[Amit Varma]: And one conclusion from that, which is true, is that it's a better world for men, obviously,

01:48:15.920 --> 01:48:18.440
[Unknown]: but you don't need that layer, right?

01:48:18.440 --> 01:48:22.540
[Amit Varma]: But the other conclusion is that there is another layer about what being a man is doing

01:48:22.540 --> 01:48:25.120
[Amit Varma]: to us, and we don't see that.

01:48:25.120 --> 01:48:29.640
[Amit Varma]: So you know, do you feel that through all your traveling and your work, and we'll talk

01:48:29.640 --> 01:48:32.140
[Amit Varma]: about all of that in detail, of course, later.

01:48:32.140 --> 01:48:37.840
[Amit Varma]: But just as a broader question, do you feel that this is changing in any way?

01:48:37.840 --> 01:48:39.700
[Amit Varma]: What is the role popular culture is playing?

01:48:39.700 --> 01:48:43.160
[Amit Varma]: Is popular culture letting our society down?

01:48:43.160 --> 01:48:45.040
[Guest]: What is your sense of this?

01:48:45.040 --> 01:48:51.400
[Guest]: So I again talk a lot about this in my talks, you know, I have for a very long time, I wondered

01:48:51.400 --> 01:48:54.960
[Guest]: why does India not have like superhero universes, right?

01:48:54.960 --> 01:49:00.200
[Guest]: Superhero kyu nahi hai India gandhar, mallabh you had one Krrish and you had like one, you

01:49:00.200 --> 01:49:04.600
[Guest]: know, Drona and you know, you had two three like Ravan, but like you've never had that

01:49:04.600 --> 01:49:08.480
[Guest]: culture which is so prevalent in Hollywood, right?

01:49:08.480 --> 01:49:09.720
[Guest]: Why is that the case?

01:49:09.720 --> 01:49:13.520
[Guest]: And I've been, you know, kyu nahi banti itni, kyu nahi banti itni?

01:49:13.520 --> 01:49:20.280
[Guest]: And then at some point it struck me that the reason we don't have superheroes in India

01:49:20.280 --> 01:49:27.640
[Guest]: is because every man in every film plays a superhero because he's an Indian man.

01:49:27.640 --> 01:49:31.080
[Guest]: You don't need superheroes in India, you have Salman Khan, you don't need superheroes in

01:49:31.080 --> 01:49:35.640
[Guest]: India, you have Rajinikanth, you don't need superheroes in India, you have Tiger Shroff.

01:49:35.640 --> 01:49:36.640
[Guest]: What do you need?

01:49:36.640 --> 01:49:44.680
[Guest]: They are what super, what RRR, why is the world flipping over it because you know where

01:49:44.680 --> 01:49:52.200
[Guest]: you have to put a, you know, X amount of VFX logic into why Captain America can take a,

01:49:52.200 --> 01:49:57.560
[Guest]: you know, has a super strength and has a backstory where he's become so strong that he can now,

01:49:57.560 --> 01:50:02.960
[Guest]: you know, hold a, you know, or Spiderman has to go through a spider like a whole thing

01:50:02.960 --> 01:50:06.240
[Guest]: of becoming strong and then can stop a train.

01:50:06.240 --> 01:50:10.440
[Guest]: Here, you know, in RRR, you just have to be an Indian man and you can take a tank and

01:50:10.440 --> 01:50:11.440
[Guest]: throw it to somebody.

01:50:11.440 --> 01:50:13.440
[Guest]: You can take a motorcycle and throw it in someone's head.

01:50:13.440 --> 01:50:15.920
[Guest]: And that's just something that people are flipping out, but that's been the narrative

01:50:15.920 --> 01:50:21.000
[Guest]: always that Indian men don't need to be, you know, you don't need to have a spider biting

01:50:21.000 --> 01:50:25.880
[Guest]: you or a secret serum that turns you into a super soldier or like having gadgets like

01:50:25.880 --> 01:50:30.920
[Guest]: Iron Man to become, you know, strong and, you know, inhumanly powerful.

01:50:30.920 --> 01:50:34.080
[Guest]: You are inhumanly powerful anyway because you have an Indian man.

01:50:34.080 --> 01:50:37.680
[Guest]: And the problem in front of you is that somebody has taken the girl that you like away, you

01:50:37.680 --> 01:50:40.040
[Guest]: know, and that's what an Indian woman is supposed to do.

01:50:40.040 --> 01:50:45.800
[Guest]: She's the damsel in distress where an Indian man has to, Indian man has to save the girl,

01:50:45.800 --> 01:50:48.120
[Guest]: save the day, save the world.

01:50:48.120 --> 01:50:50.720
[Guest]: The Indian woman has to be saved.

01:50:50.720 --> 01:50:58.280
[Guest]: And during this entire time, you know, her trajectory is just waiting to be saved.

01:50:58.280 --> 01:51:03.560
[Guest]: And then in the middle, for some reason, dancing like that's the ways that, you know, Hindi

01:51:03.560 --> 01:51:06.040
[Guest]: films have been constructed for the longest time.

01:51:06.040 --> 01:51:12.960
[Guest]: So, you know, and we are the only society, again, can you imagine, like we call hero,

01:51:12.960 --> 01:51:17.280
[Guest]: like the lead actor in a movie, a hero, right?

01:51:17.280 --> 01:51:22.680
[Guest]: It's nowhere in the world do you call the lead actor, the hero of the film, he's a hero

01:51:22.680 --> 01:51:26.520
[Guest]: of the film because he's a hero and, and, and he's a superhero.

01:51:26.520 --> 01:51:28.280
[Guest]: That is why you're calling him a hero.

01:51:28.280 --> 01:51:34.160
[Guest]: And then, and you know, why do you have, you know, films which are called as female led

01:51:34.160 --> 01:51:39.400
[Guest]: films in our country now, that this film is a female led film, Tapsee leads this film,

01:51:39.400 --> 01:51:44.600
[Guest]: Bhoomi Pednekar leads this film, Anushka Sharma leads the film, it's a female led film.

01:51:44.600 --> 01:51:49.280
[Guest]: Because the premise of Indian films is that there will be a hero.

01:51:49.280 --> 01:51:54.040
[Guest]: And the moment you don't have a hero, you have to warn the audience that there is no

01:51:54.040 --> 01:51:55.040
[Guest]: hero in this film.

01:51:55.040 --> 01:51:59.960
[Guest]: In this film, women are leading it and women are not heroes in the minds of like filmmakers

01:51:59.960 --> 01:52:02.360
[Guest]: or the Bollywood or the industry at large, right?

01:52:02.360 --> 01:52:06.120
[Guest]: A woman who is fighting a circumstance, but a man is a hero.

01:52:06.120 --> 01:52:11.960
[Guest]: So heroine means someone who's going to dance and be saved, but otherwise you are a women

01:52:11.960 --> 01:52:12.960
[Guest]: led film.

01:52:12.960 --> 01:52:18.560
[Guest]: So can you imagine like the even the nomenclature of how we talk about, you know, the vocabulary

01:52:18.560 --> 01:52:23.680
[Guest]: we use when we talk about, you know, cinema and we talk about are the people who act in

01:52:23.680 --> 01:52:27.040
[Guest]: films, item numbers as an example.

01:52:27.040 --> 01:52:34.360
[Guest]: Even now, man, can you imagine that you have, you call it that, you call a dance number

01:52:34.360 --> 01:52:40.000
[Guest]: with a girl in a skimpy dress as first of all, that is the number one way to promote

01:52:40.000 --> 01:52:41.560
[Guest]: any film.

01:52:41.560 --> 01:52:45.720
[Guest]: Just now another film has come out Bhediya, which is about, you know, a man turning into

01:52:45.720 --> 01:52:46.720
[Guest]: a wolf.

01:52:46.720 --> 01:52:52.600
[Guest]: What does that have to do with an actress, you know, dressing in, you know, and again,

01:52:52.600 --> 01:52:55.360
[Guest]: nothing, but that's the way to promote that.

01:52:55.360 --> 01:53:01.600
[Guest]: You need to have quote-unquote as, you know, item number where a girl is quote-unquote

01:53:01.600 --> 01:53:03.360
[Guest]: an item.

01:53:03.360 --> 01:53:06.840
[Guest]: Imagine the derogatory language you're using to even refer to a woman over here and she's

01:53:06.840 --> 01:53:09.160
[Guest]: performing a number.

01:53:09.160 --> 01:53:14.080
[Guest]: And while of course some people, you know, actresses were smart and, you know, filmmakers

01:53:14.080 --> 01:53:16.520
[Guest]: were smart, turn it into an art form.

01:53:16.520 --> 01:53:23.080
[Guest]: As an example, BD Jalaila in, you know, in Omkara, which is Vishal Bhardwaj's way of

01:53:23.080 --> 01:53:24.080
[Guest]: like.

01:53:24.080 --> 01:53:28.680
[Guest]: So there are actresses and there are filmmakers who try to reclaim that idea, that if we have

01:53:28.680 --> 01:53:30.680
[Guest]: to do it, we will do it smartly.

01:53:30.680 --> 01:53:34.560
[Guest]: If the producer or the studio says that we have to put it, this is the only way to promote,

01:53:34.560 --> 01:53:37.360
[Guest]: we will do our own thing from it, etc.

01:53:37.360 --> 01:53:42.520
[Guest]: But at the same time, you can think whatever you want for the most widest audiences in

01:53:42.520 --> 01:53:49.360
[Guest]: our country, it is still like a provocative number for men to lust after, right?

01:53:49.360 --> 01:53:51.400
[Guest]: And you know, to see women in less clothing.

01:53:51.400 --> 01:53:54.920
[Guest]: So that's been historically the way we look at it.

01:53:54.920 --> 01:53:58.920
[Guest]: Now when you, and again, this was something else that I speak in my talks also with young

01:53:58.920 --> 01:54:04.600
[Guest]: people like when you look at the history of the way Bollywood has, you know, gone in terms

01:54:04.600 --> 01:54:06.800
[Guest]: of heroes.

01:54:06.800 --> 01:54:11.400
[Guest]: And if I just go back, not, you know, there's a Dilip Uma Dev Anand, but if I start from

01:54:11.400 --> 01:54:18.880
[Guest]: Amitabh Bachchan for as an example, in the 70s, there was one character that everybody

01:54:18.880 --> 01:54:19.880
[Guest]: knew of.

01:54:19.880 --> 01:54:20.880
[Guest]: What is the name of the character?

01:54:20.880 --> 01:54:23.480
[Guest]: Amitabh Bachchan used to play it, Vijay.

01:54:23.480 --> 01:54:24.480
[Guest]: Everyone knows that, right?

01:54:24.480 --> 01:54:27.280
[Guest]: Vijay is the angry young man.

01:54:27.280 --> 01:54:28.280
[Guest]: Why is he angry?

01:54:28.280 --> 01:54:31.320
[Guest]: Because society is not fair.

01:54:31.320 --> 01:54:39.200
