[Guest]: Kantara, but this scene, I couldn't, the movie for me after that, just after I saw that scene,

02:07:21.320 --> 02:07:25.760
[Guest]: I was just like, you know, how can I be comfortable with anything that happens in the movie that

02:07:25.760 --> 02:07:32.360
[Guest]: if there's such a rampant, misogynistic, you know, idea over here, right then and there

02:07:32.360 --> 02:07:34.920
[Guest]: and the way the woman's character has been treated in the whole film, again, it's just

02:07:34.920 --> 02:07:37.160
[Guest]: like a woman who's in service of a man.

02:07:37.160 --> 02:07:44.960
[Guest]: So gender is a, I don't think enough people recognize it, you know, if filmmakers in our

02:07:44.960 --> 02:07:49.840
[Guest]: country are now making films about which show gender in a new light or show for that matter

02:07:49.840 --> 02:07:54.000
[Guest]: sexuality in a new light or anything, I think they're also coming from a sense of business

02:07:54.000 --> 02:07:57.920
[Guest]: now that a story like this, because nothing else is working, this might work, so let's

02:07:57.920 --> 02:07:58.920
[Guest]: give it a shot.

02:07:58.920 --> 02:08:03.160
[Guest]: I don't think there's enough people who are passionate about it, or who care about it

02:08:03.160 --> 02:08:09.600
[Guest]: or who and anytime, you know, like as somebody who's also tried very hard to have these conversations,

02:08:09.600 --> 02:08:14.520
[Guest]: you if you pitch it that this is about gender, people are just going to be like, I don't

02:08:14.520 --> 02:08:15.520
[Guest]: care.

02:08:15.520 --> 02:08:19.160
[Guest]: But if you pitch it as entertainment, and then they're like, Oh, but I like what you've

02:08:19.160 --> 02:08:21.280
[Guest]: done in gender, they themselves will say interesting.

02:08:21.280 --> 02:08:26.360
[Guest]: But if I say that I'll tell you a story, but I'll tell you a story that it's a great story,

02:08:26.360 --> 02:08:27.920
[Guest]: then you might be interested in it.

02:08:27.920 --> 02:08:31.800
[Guest]: But the moment I start by saying, you know, I think we're trying to reverse, we're looking

02:08:31.800 --> 02:08:34.760
[Guest]: at misogyny in this way, I don't want to care, I don't care about message or whatever it

02:08:34.760 --> 02:08:39.920
[Guest]: is, because they think that there is a stench that comes with social issues, that the moment

02:08:39.920 --> 02:08:45.600
[Guest]: you talk about social issues, you know, there is your your film and your idea and your thought

02:08:45.600 --> 02:08:51.840
[Guest]: and your story has a stink to it, that that people try to rub off like it cannot be seen.

02:08:51.840 --> 02:08:55.760
[Guest]: As an example, Aamir Khan, again, no disrespect to anybody over here.

02:08:55.760 --> 02:09:00.640
[Guest]: I'm just trying to like, when when thugs of Hindustan came, and this is just something

02:09:00.640 --> 02:09:04.320
[Guest]: I noticed, right, again, I really respect him, I just talked about how Dangal was, you

02:09:04.320 --> 02:09:05.320
[Guest]: know, whatever.

02:09:05.320 --> 02:09:08.240
[Guest]: But when thugs of Hindustan came, he went on coffee with Karan.

02:09:08.240 --> 02:09:11.400
[Guest]: And Karan Johar said that, you know, you've been, you know, you have been such an impactful

02:09:11.400 --> 02:09:16.200
[Guest]: person, you know, you've done, what do you say, Satyamev Jayate, all your films have

02:09:16.200 --> 02:09:19.240
[Guest]: social issues at the core of it, it's so incredible, etc.

02:09:19.240 --> 02:09:24.960
[Guest]: And Aamir Khan said, no, no, no, I don't make films for social issues, I make good films,

02:09:24.960 --> 02:09:30.800
[Guest]: it's a good thing that I got a social message, but my social issue, he was so terrified,

02:09:30.800 --> 02:09:36.560
[Guest]: as one of India's biggest actors, to be seen as somebody who's supporting a film with a

02:09:36.560 --> 02:09:37.560
[Guest]: social cause.

02:09:37.560 --> 02:09:42.560
[Guest]: He's just like, no, no, no, no, no, please don't, you have to look at the like, immediate

02:09:42.560 --> 02:09:48.360
[Guest]: fear on his face, that please don't bracket me as a socially responsible actor, I'm not

02:09:48.360 --> 02:09:49.360
[Guest]: one, sorry.

02:09:49.360 --> 02:09:54.360
[Guest]: I am a hero and I'm an actor, I'm waiting for a thug, I'm killing people there, I'm

02:09:54.360 --> 02:09:57.120
[Guest]: doing violence, I've done Ghazni also, look, I do everything.

02:09:57.120 --> 02:09:58.920
[Guest]: So don't bracket me in that.

02:09:58.920 --> 02:10:03.880
[Guest]: I'm just doing good, good cinema, if they resonate and great, if not, they don't.

02:10:03.880 --> 02:10:07.280
[Guest]: And anybody who tries to do talk about social issue, Enraak Kashyap, you will have a separate

02:10:07.280 --> 02:10:11.040
[Guest]: fan base, but no one go for his films beyond a point of time, you know, you will have people

02:10:11.040 --> 02:10:13.140
[Guest]: just it's, it's sad.

02:10:13.140 --> 02:10:16.720
[Guest]: And I just I don't think that you know, when you look at international cinema, and you

02:10:16.720 --> 02:10:21.920
[Guest]: look at foreign cinema, you know, you know, as a foreign cinema, non English cinema, you

02:10:21.920 --> 02:10:25.920
[Guest]: have something like Parasite, which is about class.

02:10:25.920 --> 02:10:28.200
[Guest]: And that's why it won the Oscar.

02:10:28.200 --> 02:10:34.220
[Guest]: And they're the people they're aware, they're all coming together to make that commentary.

02:10:34.220 --> 02:10:39.360
[Guest]: You have most of the incredible films that are made internationally, have that team,

02:10:39.360 --> 02:10:44.280
[Guest]: you know, Asghar Farhadi, any of these people that you have internationally, and they're

02:10:44.280 --> 02:10:51.960
[Guest]: proud of the fact that they're exploring an insight or a theme into a social, social and

02:10:51.960 --> 02:10:56.640
[Guest]: all art is political, all art is about social issues only.

02:10:56.640 --> 02:10:59.000
[Guest]: You may realize it or you may not realize it.

02:10:59.000 --> 02:11:02.320
[Guest]: If you realize it, then you are then you're making it consciously if you don't realize

02:11:02.320 --> 02:11:08.320
[Guest]: it, you're just, you know, perpetuating stereotypes of a certain social understanding of the world

02:11:08.320 --> 02:11:12.120
[Guest]: you have and a certain political understanding of the world, you may not know that you have

02:11:12.120 --> 02:11:15.240
[Guest]: done misogyny, but you have done misogyny, and that is your point of view.

02:11:15.240 --> 02:11:16.800
[Guest]: I'm not even talking about Kabir Singh right now.

02:11:16.800 --> 02:11:22.080
[Guest]: I'm talking about like most of Indian Bollywood like history, which is had casual misogyny

02:11:22.080 --> 02:11:26.480
[Guest]: as you very well said, most Akshay Kumar films have had like, you know, just the hero like

02:11:26.480 --> 02:11:31.680
[Guest]: a girl by constantly stalking her by constantly like, you know, and that is the way that most

02:11:31.680 --> 02:11:32.800
[Guest]: men think.

02:11:32.800 --> 02:11:38.880
[Guest]: I know friends of mine, you know, who are women who have gotten into relationships after

02:11:38.880 --> 02:11:43.240
[Guest]: men followed them, because they were just like, okay, and this is I'm talking about

02:11:43.240 --> 02:11:46.760
[Guest]: maybe 10-15 years ago, because Imran Hashmi made it cool.

02:11:46.760 --> 02:11:50.840
[Guest]: And they thought that this is romantic, that if he saw me on this place, and then he followed

02:11:50.840 --> 02:11:54.920
[Guest]: me to somewhere, you know, maybe he really likes me.

02:11:54.920 --> 02:11:59.360
[Guest]: And because again, and there is a class element to that also, he seems like a person in a

02:11:59.360 --> 02:12:02.560
[Guest]: caste element to this also, it seems like he's from upper class, upper caste, so I don't

02:12:02.560 --> 02:12:04.320
[Guest]: mind like going out on a date for them.

02:12:04.320 --> 02:12:05.680
[Guest]: I don't feel unsafe.

02:12:05.680 --> 02:12:14.520
[Guest]: So there is, I mean, so many, so many issues that have been perpetuated consciously, unconsciously,

02:12:14.520 --> 02:12:17.440
[Guest]: subconsciously by Bollywood, will it change?

02:12:17.440 --> 02:12:18.440
[Guest]: I don't know.

02:12:18.440 --> 02:12:21.840
[Guest]: I think the web world is trying some very interesting things.

02:12:21.840 --> 02:12:27.400
[Guest]: You have a Delhi, you're seeing folks like Shefali Shah, who was an iconic actor, you

02:12:27.400 --> 02:12:32.360
[Guest]: know, being able to now have, you know, lead her own shows like a Delhi crime and, you

02:12:32.360 --> 02:12:34.760
[Guest]: know, and kick ass at it.

02:12:34.760 --> 02:12:39.040
[Guest]: You know, you have like now, now, a little bit of the internet, fortunately, is giving

02:12:39.040 --> 02:12:46.160
[Guest]: the web space is giving a little bit more respect to actors beyond age, beyond genders,

02:12:46.160 --> 02:12:50.640
[Guest]: you know, and just good storytelling, you know, but again, I mean, it's a clutter after

02:12:50.640 --> 02:12:55.440
[Guest]: a point of time, you know, this when there's too much, ultimately, when everybody wants

02:12:55.440 --> 02:12:58.560
[Guest]: to make 20,000 of one thing, then you look at the formula.

02:12:58.560 --> 02:13:02.840
[Guest]: And then you don't look at what is the out, you don't look at what is that biggest success,

02:13:02.840 --> 02:13:05.640
[Guest]: because that's always going to be difficult to make.

02:13:05.640 --> 02:13:09.000
[Guest]: Not everybody can make a family man, not everybody can make a Delhi crime, but everybody can

02:13:09.000 --> 02:13:14.840
[Guest]: make a true crime show where a girl gets kidnapped and there's a man who's trying to, you know,

02:13:14.840 --> 02:13:18.560
[Guest]: whatever, who's at the hem of it, another man who's trying to save that's the easiest

02:13:18.560 --> 02:13:19.560
[Guest]: thing to do.

02:13:19.560 --> 02:13:23.880
[Guest]: You get any director, get any writer, get any kind of actor, and you know, people will

02:13:23.880 --> 02:13:26.440
[Guest]: watch it because that's what they've always been watching.

02:13:26.440 --> 02:13:33.520
[Guest]: So I know I still I feel like I have hope I always have hope that just unfortunately

02:13:33.520 --> 02:13:39.080
[Guest]: the kind of person I have, but at this point, I don't see where I don't I don't know where

02:13:39.080 --> 02:13:43.480
[Guest]: Bollywood is leading or where Indian cinema at large is leading, especially with the rise

02:13:43.480 --> 02:13:47.920
[Guest]: of these hyper masculine South films.

02:13:47.920 --> 02:13:52.400
[Amit Varma]: So a couple of things I want to double click on and ask further questions about but first

02:13:52.400 --> 02:13:57.560
[Amit Varma]: boss Nikhil, I have to say, every time you say no disrespect intended, when language

02:13:57.560 --> 02:14:04.960
[Amit Varma]: like that is used, basically what you're saying is full disrespect intended, it's like, yeah,

02:14:04.960 --> 02:14:06.560
[Amit Varma]: I don't mean to burst your bubble.

02:14:06.560 --> 02:14:10.280
[Guest]: Whenever you say I don't mean to burst your bubble, you're bursting the bubble.

02:14:10.280 --> 02:14:12.120
[Amit Varma]: I am with you.

02:14:12.120 --> 02:14:13.120
[Amit Varma]: So never mind that.

02:14:13.120 --> 02:14:18.120
[Amit Varma]: No, I all of this is extremely insightful in terms of, you know, little things like

02:14:18.120 --> 02:14:24.120
[Amit Varma]: how we normalize all of this, either term like item number, term like female led film

02:14:24.120 --> 02:14:28.760
[Amit Varma]: at one on one hand, it's a description accurate to her.

02:14:28.760 --> 02:14:33.600
[Amit Varma]: But on another hand, the fact that the description is necessary, is telling you something, you

02:14:33.600 --> 02:14:37.640
[Amit Varma]: know, just calling someone a hero in a film, sort of telling you something and just the

02:14:37.640 --> 02:14:43.160
[Amit Varma]: fact that, you know, Kiara Advani can act in a film led by Akshay Kumar, but Akshay

02:14:43.160 --> 02:14:47.360
[Amit Varma]: Kumar will never act in a film led by any woman, obviously.

02:14:47.360 --> 02:14:51.120
[Amit Varma]: So you know, earlier at lunch, we were both raving about TikTok.

02:14:51.120 --> 02:14:55.120
[Amit Varma]: And I'll, you know, I'll sort of talk about that to get to my next question.

02:14:55.120 --> 02:15:01.000
[Amit Varma]: And I had even for a month, I had taught one course called TikTok and Indian society I

02:15:01.000 --> 02:15:02.920
[Amit Varma]: had, in fact, taught it on WhatsApp.

02:15:02.920 --> 02:15:04.440
[Amit Varma]: So it was like WhatsApp University.

02:15:04.440 --> 02:15:08.600
[Amit Varma]: And the reason I taught it on WhatsApp was to support my chapters, I had like hundreds

02:15:08.600 --> 02:15:11.040
[Amit Varma]: of TikTok videos I wanted to send.

02:15:11.040 --> 02:15:16.120
[Amit Varma]: So if you think of the vertical format, WhatsApp was actually the best place to send it sequentially

02:15:16.120 --> 02:15:19.600
[Amit Varma]: with my comments and all that, but that was a time TikTok was banned.

02:15:19.600 --> 02:15:21.200
[Amit Varma]: So I just did it once.

02:15:21.200 --> 02:15:28.440
[Amit Varma]: Now, what I loved about TikTok is that TikTok broke through all the structures that existed.

02:15:28.440 --> 02:15:32.120
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, that happened at the same time as you know, Jio was making broadband almost

02:15:32.120 --> 02:15:33.120
[Amit Varma]: ubiquitous.

02:15:33.120 --> 02:15:38.880
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, a person in a village who might otherwise have felt that no one was making

02:15:38.880 --> 02:15:43.360
[Amit Varma]: entertainment for them, that no one was speaking to them, could turn on their mobile phone

02:15:43.360 --> 02:15:48.000
[Amit Varma]: and no matter what they were, maybe alternate sexuality or whatever, they might have felt

02:15:48.000 --> 02:15:49.560
[Amit Varma]: that they are all alone.

02:15:49.560 --> 02:15:55.200
[Amit Varma]: And you can suddenly see people like yourself, creating art and entertainment for you.

02:15:55.200 --> 02:15:59.760
[Amit Varma]: And then there is that magic moment where you can turn the camera around, and you can

02:15:59.760 --> 02:16:01.560
[Amit Varma]: make something yourself.

02:16:01.560 --> 02:16:07.800
[Amit Varma]: And initially, obviously, you would find TikTokers initially doing, you know, those standard

02:16:07.800 --> 02:16:10.640
[Amit Varma]: memes with a lip sync to something or whatever.

02:16:10.640 --> 02:16:16.120
[Amit Varma]: But then going beyond that, I just saw such an outpouring of great original art coming

02:16:16.120 --> 02:16:17.120
[Amit Varma]: out of that.

02:16:17.120 --> 02:16:18.280
[Amit Varma]: And it blew my mind.

02:16:18.280 --> 02:16:21.240
[Amit Varma]: And it was bottom up, which I just loved.

02:16:21.240 --> 02:16:24.440
[Amit Varma]: And that way, unfortunately, TikTok was banned.

02:16:24.440 --> 02:16:31.740
[Amit Varma]: And my sense has been over the last few years, whenever I look around me across domains,

02:16:31.740 --> 02:16:37.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, whether it is in the media, or just across domains, that the mainstream is crumbling,

02:16:37.200 --> 02:16:41.680
[Amit Varma]: right, that the mainstream is crumbling, everything is getting decentralized.

02:16:41.680 --> 02:16:46.600
[Amit Varma]: And while there is a lag in the transition, mainstream players have no clue what's happening

02:16:46.600 --> 02:16:47.600
[Amit Varma]: out there.

02:16:47.600 --> 02:16:48.600
[Amit Varma]: Right?

02:16:48.600 --> 02:16:54.240
[Amit Varma]: Would you say that that's also the case with Bollywood in the sense that the way the industry

02:16:54.240 --> 02:16:57.880
[Amit Varma]: works and things is really a bit of an artifact.

02:16:57.880 --> 02:17:01.240
[Amit Varma]: They have a notion of what works, right?

02:17:01.240 --> 02:17:06.020
[Amit Varma]: And then what you beautifully called a vicious circle kicks into play, where they'll produce

02:17:06.020 --> 02:17:09.640
[Amit Varma]: more and more of that, and some of that will work, and then they'll double down on that.

02:17:09.640 --> 02:17:11.600
[Amit Varma]: And they'll say, huh, this works.

02:17:11.600 --> 02:17:15.880
[Amit Varma]: But they cannot think outside that particular box, that TikTokers were thinking outside

02:17:15.880 --> 02:17:16.880
[Amit Varma]: all boxes.

02:17:16.880 --> 02:17:24.680
[Amit Varma]: And so do you feel that that's a problem with mainstream industry in the sense that in another

02:17:24.680 --> 02:17:30.160
[Amit Varma]: place you spoke about how you did not want to be a filmmaker sitting in a glass cabin

02:17:30.160 --> 02:17:33.560
[Amit Varma]: and Andheri saying this is what the youth wants, this is what the country wants.

02:17:33.560 --> 02:17:37.680
[Amit Varma]: And we'll talk about that phase of your life also.

02:17:37.680 --> 02:17:44.020
[Amit Varma]: But do you think that we are stuck in that space, where we are probably ready for a kind

02:17:44.020 --> 02:17:48.520
[Amit Varma]: of content and a kind of art, which people aren't producing because of this lag because

02:17:48.520 --> 02:17:50.600
[Amit Varma]: entertainment is still so top down?

02:17:50.600 --> 02:17:57.280
[Guest]: Lots to say on this, honestly, where do I begin?

02:17:57.280 --> 02:18:07.320
[Guest]: So I feel like fundamentally now we as an audience don't understand the film industry.

02:18:07.320 --> 02:18:13.680
[Guest]: It's called an industry to begin with, the industry, Bollywood in one hand, even Hollywood,

02:18:13.680 --> 02:18:16.040
[Guest]: most film industries.

02:18:16.040 --> 02:18:23.720
[Guest]: Let's just leave some of the European kind of cinema out of it for now, but it's a business

02:18:23.720 --> 02:18:29.760
[Guest]: and it's like it's worse than gambling because there's no science to it, right?

02:18:29.760 --> 02:18:37.600
[Guest]: When you think about it, every other industry in the world has a structure of what works.

02:18:37.600 --> 02:18:43.040
[Guest]: If I am a computer engineer, if I would have gone into the same line, I would be given

02:18:43.040 --> 02:18:44.040
[Guest]: a certain kind of code.

02:18:44.040 --> 02:18:48.360
[Guest]: I would have a certain problem statement, solve this problem statement, do this coding

02:18:48.360 --> 02:18:50.320
[Guest]: and then maybe we'll reach the solution.

02:18:50.320 --> 02:18:53.320
[Guest]: There are ideas, innovations you have and obviously still you don't know whether it

02:18:53.320 --> 02:18:57.040
[Guest]: will work or not, but there is a structure you can follow to reach there and a lot of

02:18:57.040 --> 02:18:58.040
[Guest]: people have reached there.

02:18:58.040 --> 02:19:01.680
[Guest]: There's a lot of technological innovation that happens because of structure.

02:19:01.680 --> 02:19:07.160
[Guest]: There is nothing that can guarantee a hit film, nothing in the world because if that

02:19:07.160 --> 02:19:11.080
[Guest]: was true, then every film would be a hit, nothing.

02:19:11.080 --> 02:19:16.560
[Guest]: So there are sometimes films like, you know, suddenly there are films that come out like

02:19:16.560 --> 02:19:19.640
[Guest]: an Ayushman film, as I said, can come out and make 150 crores because it was just a

02:19:19.640 --> 02:19:23.780
[Guest]: fresh topic, Vicky Doonar came out of nowhere, then from till Badhaay Do, everything kind

02:19:23.780 --> 02:19:25.240
[Guest]: of worked like that.

02:19:25.240 --> 02:19:31.200
[Guest]: You will have a suddenly you will have an RRR that will come out and blow Hollywood

02:19:31.200 --> 02:19:32.200
[Guest]: away.

02:19:32.200 --> 02:19:36.760
[Guest]: It is 100% going to be nominated to the Oscars because every American filmmaker has gone

02:19:36.760 --> 02:19:40.280
[Guest]: nuts watching it like what is happening over here, right?

02:19:40.280 --> 02:19:44.940
[Guest]: But I mean and not everybody can be Raja Mouli, not everybody can be Ayushman, but not anybody

02:19:44.940 --> 02:19:51.280
[Guest]: can be like Salim Javed at that time at the height of their, you know, success.

02:19:51.280 --> 02:19:53.480
[Guest]: So there is no formula.

02:19:53.480 --> 02:20:01.040
[Guest]: And yet, when you crack something that works, the kind of return on investment you can have,

02:20:01.040 --> 02:20:02.840
[Guest]: it's pretty crazy.

02:20:02.840 --> 02:20:04.200
[Guest]: And you can have it instantly, right?

02:20:04.200 --> 02:20:07.680
[Guest]: When you have a business, you have to build a business for 10 years, and then you get

02:20:07.680 --> 02:20:11.800
[Guest]: a valuation then you whatever, you know, you put a lot of hard work for a very long time,

02:20:11.800 --> 02:20:13.160
[Guest]: and something happens.

02:20:13.160 --> 02:20:16.360
[Guest]: You have one and a half years that you put a film in if you kind of put it together in

02:20:16.360 --> 02:20:17.440
[Guest]: a smart way.

02:20:17.440 --> 02:20:25.120
[Guest]: If it works, you know, you have 300-400 crores that you make, you know, in like, over a period

02:20:25.120 --> 02:20:27.140
[Guest]: of two months or three months.

02:20:27.140 --> 02:20:30.960
[Guest]: So the return on investment is so great that people are happy to do this gamble, but it

02:20:30.960 --> 02:20:31.960
[Guest]: is gambling.

02:20:31.960 --> 02:20:36.400
[Guest]: Like you're up as a as a poker player, you said luck plays a chance so often right and

02:20:36.400 --> 02:20:40.640
[Guest]: you know, you can have skill, but the same thing in Bollywood, you can have some skill,

02:20:40.640 --> 02:20:45.880
[Guest]: but a lot of it is just pure luck, right and and and that's Bollywood, but fundamentally

02:20:45.880 --> 02:20:53.720
[Guest]: people think and misunderstand that you know, it is it is it is a place that is out to make

02:20:53.720 --> 02:20:56.480
[Guest]: things that the audience would love or enjoy.

02:20:56.480 --> 02:21:00.240
[Guest]: That is the secondary object is never the primary objective.

02:21:00.240 --> 02:21:06.120
[Guest]: On the other hand, there are fools, the fools like me, there are fools like many other writers,

02:21:06.120 --> 02:21:12.120
[Guest]: directors, filmmakers who watch some of these movies that could be made for any reason possible,

02:21:12.120 --> 02:21:16.120
[Guest]: you know, and in some way somewhere these films made them feel less alone.

02:21:16.120 --> 02:21:17.120
[Guest]: I have grown.

02:21:17.120 --> 02:21:18.120
[Guest]: I came to India.

02:21:18.120 --> 02:21:23.640
[Guest]: This is a true story because of DDLJ, I grew up, you know, I had got I did my GMAT, so

02:21:23.640 --> 02:21:28.200
[Guest]: I did my SATs and I got a great score and all my friends in my circle of friends in

02:21:28.200 --> 02:21:29.200
[Guest]: Bahrain went to America.

02:21:29.200 --> 02:21:32.520
[Guest]: I was the one who said no, I want to go to India for two reasons.

02:21:32.520 --> 02:21:36.320
[Guest]: One I wanted to go to I wanted to go to Bombay and be a and and make it in Bombay.

02:21:36.320 --> 02:21:43.120
[Guest]: I was very clear and all of it started with DDLJ and I was like what is this?

02:21:43.120 --> 02:21:48.000
[Guest]: I am like I have my favorite thing ever and and the funniest part of this is that I it's

02:21:48.000 --> 02:21:54.440
[Guest]: not the thing that worked for me DDLJ is not Shah Rukh Khan, not Kajol, but Amrish Buri

02:21:54.440 --> 02:22:01.520
[Guest]: repeatedly saying my country's soil and you know my soil's fragrance and and and I was

02:22:01.520 --> 02:22:06.920
[Guest]: like inspired by him to say that yes, my country, my soil, my soil's fragrance, Punjab, I want

02:22:06.920 --> 02:22:11.000
[Guest]: to go there, I want to do something there, but like the film also in itself, Aditya Chopra,

02:22:11.000 --> 02:22:16.200
[Guest]: I ended up working at Yash Raj, got to work with Aditya Chopra and it's just insane like

02:22:16.200 --> 02:22:19.840
[Guest]: you know, but as a young boy, I saw those films and I was like this crazy and when Hrithik

02:22:19.840 --> 02:22:24.520
[Guest]: Roshan came, I was just like I was obsessed with Hrithik, obsessed.

02:22:24.520 --> 02:22:28.600
[Guest]: I was I have I bought like some 30,000 posters of Hrithik Roshan.

02:22:28.600 --> 02:22:33.760
[Guest]: I had created a website, embarrassing but I had created a Geocities website, a fan website

02:22:33.760 --> 02:22:39.080
[Guest]: of Hrithik Roshan when I was like 13, you know, so there was something in films, you

02:22:39.080 --> 02:22:44.480
[Guest]: know, that spoke to young people who did not and especially I feel like young boys who

02:22:44.480 --> 02:22:48.520
[Guest]: just did not know where to fit in, you know, I would see a Bollywood film and you would

02:22:48.520 --> 02:22:53.440
[Guest]: speak to any writer, any filmmaker in Lokhandwala Andheri and they will have a story about like

02:22:53.440 --> 02:22:57.400
[Guest]: the film that corrupted them, the film that made them realize that this is what they want

02:22:57.400 --> 02:23:01.840
[Guest]: to do and it really comes down to an insight that I felt a little less alone.

02:23:01.840 --> 02:23:07.120
[Guest]: As an NRI kid growing up outside of India, films were my connect with my country.

02:23:07.120 --> 02:23:10.600
[Guest]: It was my connect with my language while of course, you know, Middle East beyond a point

02:23:10.600 --> 02:23:15.760
[Guest]: of time has tons and tons of Indians anyway, so it's not like I was in a very foreign place.

02:23:15.760 --> 02:23:18.640
[Guest]: Still, you know, there was something that I would see Punjabi culture in particular

02:23:18.640 --> 02:23:23.160
[Guest]: is like super resonant in like, you know, YRF and Dharma films and whatnot.

02:23:23.160 --> 02:23:27.520
[Guest]: So I'd watch those films and I was like, you know, as somebody who still struggles to be

02:23:27.520 --> 02:23:32.200
[Guest]: Punjabi and is very embarrassed by it because it's the language of my, you know, parents

02:23:32.200 --> 02:23:37.880
[Guest]: and my grandparents, you know, I would hear Punjabi music and I would see films, you know,

02:23:37.880 --> 02:23:41.960
[Guest]: DDLJ and there's all these Malhotras and Khannas and Kapoors and whatnot like, you know, this

02:23:41.960 --> 02:23:44.160
[Guest]: is these are my people, right?

02:23:44.160 --> 02:23:48.680
[Guest]: But when you enter Bombay and you come to Bollywood, so to speak, you realize that these

02:23:48.680 --> 02:23:56.560
[Guest]: are all of this is these are power centers, there are art is elitist, you know, and it's

02:23:56.560 --> 02:24:02.000
[Guest]: always been when people look down and say, okay, you've not seen Gone with the Wind,

02:24:02.000 --> 02:24:05.680
[Guest]: you're not seeing classics, you're not seeing European cinema, you're not seeing like, you

02:24:05.680 --> 02:24:10.400
[Guest]: know, Ingrid Bergman, you've not seen any of these like big filmmakers, big names, you

02:24:10.400 --> 02:24:16.920
[Guest]: know, and people look down on you and say that, you know, because it is it was a language

02:24:16.920 --> 02:24:21.800
[Guest]: of first a language of intellectuals, then a language of rich people, then a language

02:24:21.800 --> 02:24:22.880
[Guest]: of business.

02:24:22.880 --> 02:24:27.520
[Guest]: It was never something that anybody can, it was not a democratic system.

02:24:27.520 --> 02:24:32.100
[Guest]: Why is there this whole anger about demotivism, but you fundamentally misunderstood what this

02:24:32.100 --> 02:24:33.360
[Guest]: industry is.

02:24:33.360 --> 02:24:41.960
[Guest]: If you're angry about nepotism, it's I can't even now said no offense, but you know, you've

02:24:41.960 --> 02:24:47.040
[Guest]: called me out on it, but people get angry about nepotism, I'm just like, do you not

02:24:47.040 --> 02:24:51.440
[Guest]: recognize you think that this is an industry that was made on merit, it wasn't, it was

02:24:51.440 --> 02:24:54.960
[Guest]: made on it was business deals.

02:24:54.960 --> 02:24:55.960
[Guest]: Everybody's the same family.

02:24:55.960 --> 02:25:02.240
[Guest]: 80% of Bollywood is one family, yes, Aditya Chopra and Karan Johar are cousins, you know,

02:25:02.240 --> 02:25:07.320
[Guest]: and like in most people don't know that they're literal cousins, you know, and and so and

02:25:07.320 --> 02:25:11.960
[Guest]: there were four or five families, you know, in the 50s 60s that started it, and they've

02:25:11.960 --> 02:25:15.920
[Guest]: been like, they've grown their empires and businesses, few new people have definitely

02:25:15.920 --> 02:25:19.200
[Guest]: come in and whatnot, tried to create Anurag Kashyap as an example to try to create an

02:25:19.200 --> 02:25:21.880
[Guest]: alternate culture and alternate industry along with it.

02:25:21.880 --> 02:25:25.440
[Guest]: But still it is it is about people who have money, and they will do with the money whatever

02:25:25.440 --> 02:25:26.760
[Guest]: the hell they want.

02:25:26.760 --> 02:25:33.400
[Guest]: And why would they give them, you know, money to outsider quote unquote, because if I give

02:25:33.400 --> 02:25:39.320
[Guest]: it to my son, or my daughter, at least if I fail, you know, I'm putting it I'm feeling

02:25:39.320 --> 02:25:43.600
[Guest]: because I pointed on my children, but if I put it on an outsider, and that feels I'm

02:25:43.600 --> 02:25:46.280
[Guest]: just like I'm an idiot or what, because it's a gamble.

02:25:46.280 --> 02:25:51.280
[Guest]: There is no structure, there's no formula, you can have the best actors, you know, from

02:25:51.280 --> 02:25:55.520
[Guest]: outside of Bollywood, but ultimately, you know, it's a risk.

02:25:55.520 --> 02:26:00.320
[Guest]: And why would someone take a 30 crore 20 crore 10 crore 5 crore risk on somebody else, when

02:26:00.320 --> 02:26:02.960
[Guest]: you can take that 5 crore risk on your family, right and it's the same.

02:26:02.960 --> 02:26:05.200
[Guest]: So everybody is in cohort with each other.

02:26:05.200 --> 02:26:07.080
[Guest]: It's an incestuous industry.

02:26:07.080 --> 02:26:10.320
[Guest]: Everybody is like, you know, you work with each other, that's those have been the power

02:26:10.320 --> 02:26:17.280
[Guest]: centers for the longest time, the internet broke it, YouTube broke it, we come to TikTok.

02:26:17.280 --> 02:26:21.580
[Guest]: But that's what happened in the and I was fortunate as being someone who was started

02:26:21.580 --> 02:26:27.460
[Guest]: off as a, you know, culture writer in Hindustan Times, you know, and was writing about quote

02:26:27.460 --> 02:26:32.000
[Guest]: unquote, the seed, you know, I was I was seeing stand up comedy happen.

02:26:32.000 --> 02:26:36.800
[Guest]: I've also done open mics at the beginning, I've seen the independent music culture, I

02:26:36.800 --> 02:26:38.040
[Guest]: was reporting on it.

02:26:38.040 --> 02:26:41.880
[Guest]: I was seeing channel V and MTV transforming into something interesting.

02:26:41.880 --> 02:26:45.080
[Guest]: You know, what were they doing for culture at that point of time, this alternate season

02:26:45.080 --> 02:26:50.880
[Guest]: Anurag Kashyap and that became my entry in Dev D I saw in 2008-9 ki baat thi, paagal ho

02:26:50.880 --> 02:26:51.880
[Guest]: gaya tha.

02:26:51.880 --> 02:26:52.880
[Guest]: I was like, what is this?

02:26:52.880 --> 02:26:55.960
[Guest]: What I've seen that film in theatres like four times, I was like, how is this like,

02:26:55.960 --> 02:26:56.960
[Guest]: what is happening?

02:26:56.960 --> 02:27:01.040
[Guest]: Udaan I saw, Vikram Aditya Motwani, Oye Lucky Lucky Boys, I think it's one of the greatest

02:27:01.040 --> 02:27:05.760
[Guest]: films ever made of all time, Dibakar Banshee, I went and met them, you know, because I was

02:27:05.760 --> 02:27:09.120
[Guest]: I had the, you know, I was in a place I was in Hindustan Times and, you know, after a

02:27:09.120 --> 02:27:11.800
[Guest]: point of time, I realised paise toh mil nahi rahe hai, so I made a list of people I wanted

02:27:11.800 --> 02:27:12.800
[Guest]: to meet.

02:27:12.800 --> 02:27:14.480
[Guest]: I was like, I'm just going to go and interview these people.

02:27:14.480 --> 02:27:17.680
[Guest]: So I met all of the people I used to love and, you know, like, I love this guy, I want

02:27:17.680 --> 02:27:18.680
[Guest]: to meet him.

02:27:18.680 --> 02:27:23.320
[Guest]: I would love this, you know, woman and, you know, as a director or whatever.

02:27:23.320 --> 02:27:27.680
[Guest]: And I just have these, you know, lists and just go after these people and they're not

02:27:27.680 --> 02:27:30.680
[Guest]: just India lists internationally.

02:27:30.680 --> 02:27:35.160
[Guest]: I interviewed Richard Linklater, I interviewed Aaron Sorkin, all the people that I considered

02:27:35.160 --> 02:27:38.880
[Guest]: my heroes, I just go after them and interview them, right.

02:27:38.880 --> 02:27:43.960
[Guest]: And I would be inspired by how these people are not your, they are not from these power

02:27:43.960 --> 02:27:46.880
[Guest]: centres and it's not even easy for them.

02:27:46.880 --> 02:27:51.720
[Guest]: They have struggled epically, they have struggled publicly, but they have done it.

02:27:51.720 --> 02:27:53.600
[Guest]: They have broken the system.

02:27:53.600 --> 02:27:56.320
[Guest]: And that was always something that I kind of always had the back of my hand.

02:27:56.320 --> 02:28:00.120
[Guest]: So even when I got into MTV, I was, I joined the digital team at that time.

02:28:00.120 --> 02:28:02.120
[Guest]: I was the editor of the MTV website.

02:28:02.120 --> 02:28:06.320
[Guest]: As editor of the MTV website, there was one website, nobody gave a shit about it.

02:28:06.320 --> 02:28:09.920
[Guest]: I was suddenly this 24 year old who's like, you're free say, you gave a little bit of

02:28:09.920 --> 02:28:10.920
[Guest]: a budget.

02:28:10.920 --> 02:28:12.680
[Guest]: And I just, I wrote all kinds of articles on it.

02:28:12.680 --> 02:28:14.920
[Guest]: And suddenly those articles started going viral, started.

02:28:14.920 --> 02:28:19.840
[Guest]: And then there was a team that I was given and a team that I was part of suddenly.

02:28:19.840 --> 02:28:23.640
[Guest]: And Koch studio, the first time was coming and then they gave it to me and said, you

02:28:23.640 --> 02:28:27.280
[Guest]: know, you are the whatever digital in charge of making it happen.

02:28:27.280 --> 02:28:28.640
[Guest]: And I was just trying all kinds of things.

02:28:28.640 --> 02:28:32.920
[Guest]: We did like a, at that time, like a video interview pod and we didn't even have the

02:28:32.920 --> 02:28:37.200
[Guest]: terms podcast, but we did like a video with all the Shankar, all the people who were performing

02:28:37.200 --> 02:28:38.200
[Guest]: at Koch studio.

02:28:38.200 --> 02:28:39.200
[Guest]: We did like this video gathering.

02:28:39.200 --> 02:28:41.240
[Guest]: We did a tweet, tweet meetup.

02:28:41.240 --> 02:28:45.600
[Guest]: So all the Koch studio fans and got them to go to the sets and watch it live.

02:28:45.600 --> 02:28:46.680
[Guest]: And these are all experiment.

02:28:46.680 --> 02:28:47.680
[Guest]: Nobody was doing this.

02:28:47.680 --> 02:28:48.680
[Guest]: It was just fun.

02:28:48.680 --> 02:28:51.880
[Guest]: I was there when the internet was, you know, making things happen.

02:28:51.880 --> 02:28:55.600
[Guest]: And that's where I made the series on, on, on air after that.

02:28:55.600 --> 02:28:59.280
[Guest]: And I made six films at MTV actually, and that's where I got to get into Bollywood.

02:28:59.280 --> 02:29:04.320
[Guest]: I made six films with Anurag Kashyap, Anurag Basu, Sujit Sarkar, Nikhil Adwani, Rohan Sippy,

02:29:04.320 --> 02:29:05.320
[Guest]: Abhinay Deo.

02:29:05.320 --> 02:29:06.680
[Guest]: And I was producing all of them.

02:29:06.680 --> 02:29:09.080
[Guest]: I mean, there's a whole, again, other story around that.

02:29:09.080 --> 02:29:15.280
[Guest]: But when I got into, it was at that time in 2014, 2015, where TVF, that video, Rohdi's

02:29:15.280 --> 02:29:16.400
[Guest]: video went viral.

02:29:16.400 --> 02:29:18.200
[Guest]: And I was at MTV at that time.

02:29:18.200 --> 02:29:22.200
[Guest]: And this video and everybody in MTV was talking about how this internet video is like, what

02:29:22.200 --> 02:29:23.200
[Guest]: is this?

02:29:23.200 --> 02:29:27.240
[Guest]: And that was the first, you know, in that sense to break through, you know, and, and

02:29:27.240 --> 02:29:30.840
[Guest]: one of the first viral, viral videos, because they made fun of Rohdi's, right?

02:29:30.840 --> 02:29:34.640
[Guest]: The show that I was making the disaster of a show that I made was called Reality Stars,

02:29:34.640 --> 02:29:39.560
[Guest]: which was a fiction show about reality shows.

02:29:39.560 --> 02:29:45.560
[Guest]: We had a, is my whole idea of making a parody or like a satirical show, a comedy about these

02:29:45.560 --> 02:29:48.280
[Guest]: bunch of people who want to be part of a show called MTV rejects.

02:29:48.280 --> 02:29:59.680
[Guest]: So, so, but I saw that there was, you know, a scene, a literal counterculture happening

02:29:59.680 --> 02:30:02.840
[Guest]: alongside where the power centers did not matter anymore.

02:30:02.840 --> 02:30:09.840
[Guest]: If you were earlier, and again, I go a little bit into like can, but earlier to become famous,

02:30:09.840 --> 02:30:14.200
[Guest]: you know, fame, the idea of fame has always been associated with, you know, being in front

02:30:14.200 --> 02:30:17.400
[Guest]: of the camera, being in front of the screen at one point to become famous.

02:30:17.400 --> 02:30:20.760
[Guest]: And you see this in old Bollywood films, and you see this in films of your, where you see

02:30:20.760 --> 02:30:28.560
[Guest]: like somebody coming to VT station, and Bombay is the city of dreams, right?

02:30:28.560 --> 02:30:32.480
[Guest]: And that's where city of dreams, and you know, you will, you come to Bombay, you stand in

02:30:32.480 --> 02:30:36.400
[Guest]: a line somewhere, and like, you know, you do an audition, and maybe you become an actor

02:30:36.400 --> 02:30:39.480
[Guest]: and Amitabh Bachchan's story is this, someone else's story is that, everyone has come to

02:30:39.480 --> 02:30:43.120
[Guest]: the station, went there, stood in this line, and one day he became a superstar.

02:30:43.120 --> 02:30:46.160
[Guest]: Then they go to bandstand and talk about the fact that I am now the king of the world,

02:30:46.160 --> 02:30:47.160
[Guest]: right?

02:30:47.160 --> 02:30:48.880
[Guest]: That's the story.

02:30:48.880 --> 02:30:52.560
[Guest]: But you had to come to Bombay, you had to struggle in those lines, and many, many, many

02:30:52.560 --> 02:30:54.160
[Guest]: did not make it, right?

02:30:54.160 --> 02:30:55.960
[Guest]: And then reality TV happened.

02:30:55.960 --> 02:31:01.200
[Guest]: But reality TV, whether it was Indian Idol, Sarekama, and then of course, you know, roadies

02:31:01.200 --> 02:31:05.040
[Guest]: and all of these other shows, they said that you don't have to come to Bombay, we will

02:31:05.040 --> 02:31:06.040
[Guest]: come to you.

02:31:06.040 --> 02:31:10.400
[Guest]: So we will come to your city, you still have to stand in line, but there'll be judges,

02:31:10.400 --> 02:31:13.640
[Guest]: and immediately they'll look at you and say, this person has the potential to be a star.

02:31:13.640 --> 02:31:16.600
[Guest]: And then you can be in front of the television and suddenly you'll be a star one day.

02:31:16.600 --> 02:31:21.400
[Guest]: So suddenly, like it became closer home, I had that opportunity of becoming a star.

02:31:21.400 --> 02:31:27.520
[Guest]: And when the internet happened, even that, you didn't have to stand in line, you didn't

02:31:27.520 --> 02:31:34.080
[Guest]: have to even go to a city somewhere, you could be sitting in any part of the country, the

02:31:34.080 --> 02:31:35.360
[Guest]: world.

02:31:35.360 --> 02:31:41.360
[Guest]: If you had an internet connection, which after, you know, Jio and after, you know, 4G happened

02:31:41.360 --> 02:31:43.560
[Guest]: in our country, everybody kind of got one.

02:31:43.560 --> 02:31:49.960
[Guest]: If you have a phone, this is a new generation, which is, there is no generation before the

02:31:49.960 --> 02:31:53.200
[Guest]: present Gen Z generation that have anything in common.

02:31:53.200 --> 02:31:55.120
[Guest]: No two Indians are the same.

02:31:55.120 --> 02:31:58.000
[Guest]: Everybody has a different circumstance, different story, there's nothing unites us, nothing,

02:31:58.000 --> 02:32:02.120
[Guest]: not one thing, colour, caste, creed, religion, everything is different, right?

02:32:02.120 --> 02:32:08.520
[Guest]: But for a new generation, the Gen Z of young people, everybody, no matter what social hierarchy

02:32:08.520 --> 02:32:12.040
[Guest]: you were in also had like a mobile phone, because of 4G and because of like just that

02:32:12.040 --> 02:32:15.560
[Guest]: became your life, right, like you, everybody had to have a mobile phone, if you wanted

02:32:15.560 --> 02:32:21.000
[Guest]: to do anything, any kind of work, any kind of like, so even the poorest of the poor would

02:32:21.000 --> 02:32:24.800
[Guest]: have like some sort of a cell phone with which they would operate, right?

02:32:24.800 --> 02:32:29.880
[Guest]: And that phone in your hand became democracy in your hand, it became freedom in your hand,

02:32:29.880 --> 02:32:33.800
[Guest]: it became, you know, freedom of speech, freedom of expression in your hand, you know, YouTube

02:32:33.800 --> 02:32:39.180
[Guest]: happened, YouTube still required a little bit of, YouTube is where you saw the first,

02:32:39.180 --> 02:32:44.280
[Guest]: you know, batch of folks who broke through and said, I don't have to worry about whether

02:32:44.280 --> 02:32:49.160
[Guest]: it was TVF, you know, whether it was AIB, we did Vifilm, we of course had a little bit

02:32:49.160 --> 02:32:53.600
[Guest]: of a lot of money, I mean, a lot of money and privilege in that sense, and access in

02:32:53.600 --> 02:32:56.920
[Guest]: that sense, but we made our first web shows at that point of time, there was all the bunch

02:32:56.920 --> 02:32:59.100
[Guest]: of comedians who came from different places.

02:32:59.100 --> 02:33:03.200
[Guest]: And then you also had individual YouTubers, you had your Bhawanbhams of the world, you

02:33:03.200 --> 02:33:09.520
[Guest]: have your Prajakta Kohli's of the world, these people who are, who not really from any of

02:33:09.520 --> 02:33:14.040
[Guest]: the power centers historically, they have not come from the richest of backgrounds,

02:33:14.040 --> 02:33:19.320
[Guest]: they're not from like a quote unquote elite, you know, upbringing, they have broken through

02:33:19.320 --> 02:33:23.280
[Guest]: just because their talent and they had consistently and they had passion and they wanted to do

02:33:23.280 --> 02:33:24.280
[Guest]: it.

02:33:24.280 --> 02:33:28.920
[Guest]: They would not wait for, they wouldn't knock on a door, wait for someone to open it, they'd

02:33:28.920 --> 02:33:33.440
[Guest]: create, you know, doors, they would create the opportunities that stormed through it

02:33:33.440 --> 02:33:37.800
[Guest]: because the YouTube equalized everybody.

02:33:37.800 --> 02:33:42.500
[Guest]: At the same time, YouTube still required you to have like at least a certain sense of editing,

02:33:42.500 --> 02:33:46.320
[Guest]: you would still need to have editing, you'd still need to have, you know, either a camera

02:33:46.320 --> 02:33:50.240
[Guest]: or a phone or, you know, a phone with like a good camera.

02:33:50.240 --> 02:33:55.360
[Guest]: So there was still a little bit of privilege required, still a little bit of like, class,

02:33:55.360 --> 02:33:59.240
[Guest]: certain kind of class for you to belong to, to be able to make something for YouTube,

02:33:59.240 --> 02:34:03.120
[Guest]: which was long form, which was, which required a certain kind of skill that not, and not

02:34:03.120 --> 02:34:05.800
[Guest]: everyone with privilege had, right?

02:34:05.800 --> 02:34:12.160
[Guest]: And then TikTok came and TikTok even broke through that.

02:34:12.160 --> 02:34:19.680
[Guest]: You did not need anything apart from like any kind of a phone with a basic camera, nothing

02:34:19.680 --> 02:34:23.920
[Guest]: else, nothing, nothing, nothing else, one 5G connection, one phone with a camera and

02:34:23.920 --> 02:34:26.400
[Guest]: you can be, you can do whatever the hell you want.

02:34:26.400 --> 02:34:29.080
[Guest]: You can, you can record yourself doing anything.

02:34:29.080 --> 02:34:30.740
[Guest]: You can instantly become famous.

02:34:30.740 --> 02:34:38.240
[Guest]: You can instantly go viral, you know, it, it, it was the most democratic of any mediums

02:34:38.240 --> 02:34:41.320
[Guest]: of any art form we've ever had in India.

02:34:41.320 --> 02:34:44.800
[Guest]: No one before that, and you know, people would look down on it and say cringy and you know

02:34:44.800 --> 02:34:47.960
[Guest]: what, but that's a very classist way of looking at it.

02:34:47.960 --> 02:34:51.660
[Guest]: You know, look at these people, you people would look at it to laugh at it.

02:34:51.660 --> 02:34:58.640
[Guest]: On the other hand, you look at it to see the, the talent, the, the ambition, the aspiration,

02:34:58.640 --> 02:35:04.800
[Guest]: the passion, the excitement, enthusiasm that no matter which background and circumstance

02:35:04.800 --> 02:35:09.240
[Guest]: you have from India and, and it had people from marginalized communities speaking up.

02:35:09.240 --> 02:35:15.200
[Guest]: You were seeing videos of like, you know, trans kids from like smaller towns in India,

02:35:15.200 --> 02:35:17.440
[Guest]: you know, expressing themselves.

02:35:17.440 --> 02:35:23.440
[Guest]: You had most of TikTok and some of the biggest early stars of TikTok were Muslim young kids,

02:35:23.440 --> 02:35:29.600
[Guest]: you know, and, and you can judge them for, you know, the content they were making.

02:35:29.600 --> 02:35:34.800
[Guest]: But before that, no one, they were not allowed to express because where would they do it?

02:35:34.800 --> 02:35:37.200
[Guest]: You would require a certain amount of power and money.

02:35:37.200 --> 02:35:42.320
[Guest]: And that's the only way expression was always, always, always, they were gatekeepers to expression

02:35:42.320 --> 02:35:44.120
[Guest]: in our country and in the world.

02:35:44.120 --> 02:35:47.840
[Guest]: And that's why I'm saying art has always been you, people, film snobs, people who call them

02:35:47.840 --> 02:35:55.640
[Guest]: the film snobbish because you have a certain privilege and access to art in the first place.

02:35:55.640 --> 02:35:59.280
[Guest]: And if you look down on people who don't have that access or who did not have that access,

02:35:59.280 --> 02:36:04.240
[Guest]: that's nothing but classism, you know, so TikTok broke through that classism.

02:36:04.240 --> 02:36:09.160
[Guest]: And of course, invited a certain kind of judgment, which also came from classism, but it was

02:36:09.160 --> 02:36:12.080
[Guest]: the first and only democratic medium.

02:36:12.080 --> 02:36:15.440
[Guest]: And when TikTok happened, and you know, when YouTube happened, and when you know, people

02:36:15.440 --> 02:36:19.600
[Guest]: started coming on the internet and expressing themselves as authentically as possible.

02:36:19.600 --> 02:36:21.120
[Guest]: You see the correlation because I was there.

02:36:21.120 --> 02:36:25.440
[Guest]: I can tell you the correlation at that time was that and I've been I've been on those

02:36:25.440 --> 02:36:26.440
[Guest]: panels.

02:36:26.440 --> 02:36:29.660
[Guest]: I've had those conversations 2014-15 with filmmakers saying that, you know, looking

02:36:29.660 --> 02:36:33.000
[Guest]: at what is working on the internet and saying that, you know, maybe we should start talking

02:36:33.000 --> 02:36:37.760
[Guest]: about the things that they're talking about, you know, and suddenly you had those stories

02:36:37.760 --> 02:36:41.000
[Guest]: that were suddenly socially conscious, they didn't just come out of the blue.

02:36:41.000 --> 02:36:45.480
[Guest]: Every filmmaker and producer who punted on those things, they punted on it because they

02:36:45.480 --> 02:36:50.120
[Guest]: realized that the internet is making those, you know, conversations happen and they were

02:36:50.120 --> 02:36:53.360
[Guest]: happening very actively and it was engaging conversations.

02:36:53.360 --> 02:36:55.160
[Guest]: People were watching YouTube videos on body positivity.

02:36:55.160 --> 02:36:59.560
[Guest]: So let we can do Dhamaka Ayesha, when you're watching films on, you know, a web show on

02:36:59.560 --> 02:37:03.760
[Guest]: man's world that I had done, which was which had which as I said, has like some 90 million

02:37:03.760 --> 02:37:07.960
[Guest]: views right now, across all its episodes, it is on gender inequality.

02:37:07.960 --> 02:37:12.200
[Guest]: And it's a and people watch that and you see the comments on that people are saying for

02:37:12.200 --> 02:37:14.920
[Guest]: the first time we are having this conversation.

02:37:14.920 --> 02:37:18.360
[Guest]: So when you do that, a Ki and Ka becomes possible and I'm not saying there's a direct.

02:37:18.360 --> 02:37:22.680
[Guest]: It's not like R. Balki saw that and said, let me make a Ki and Ka, but it would not

02:37:22.680 --> 02:37:23.680
[Guest]: have happened.

02:37:23.680 --> 02:37:27.520
[Guest]: Arjun Kapoor would not have, you know, five years ago, someone who's launched himself

02:37:27.520 --> 02:37:31.280
[Guest]: with Ishaq Zadeh would not have done a Ki and Ka where, you know, he's the house home

02:37:31.280 --> 02:37:36.400
[Guest]: house husband, so to speak and homemaker and the woman is going and earning, but those

02:37:36.400 --> 02:37:39.120
[Guest]: conversations are happening because of the internet and because of YouTube and because

02:37:39.120 --> 02:37:40.600
[Guest]: of Tik Tok.

02:37:40.600 --> 02:37:44.240
[Guest]: If Tik Tok weren't banned, I feel like we would have seen a different and you saw you

02:37:44.240 --> 02:37:50.080
[Guest]: saw a different kind of a young superstar that was rising, you know, who like the idea

02:37:50.080 --> 02:37:55.960
[Guest]: of Vijay and Amitabh Bachchan and and the angry young man, you had a different kind

02:37:55.960 --> 02:38:01.880
[Guest]: of actual young boy with an identity who would you would not associate with a certain class

02:38:01.880 --> 02:38:06.960
[Guest]: or a certain community or a certain idea of what should be a success successful name.

02:38:06.960 --> 02:38:09.760
[Guest]: Maybe those names were not people think names that you would know how to pronounce because

02:38:09.760 --> 02:38:14.420
[Guest]: they would come from any different part of the country, you know, but the ban unfortunately

02:38:14.420 --> 02:38:19.000
[Guest]: like stopped it in its tracks and today again you have all these kind of platforms and it's

02:38:19.000 --> 02:38:25.120
[Guest]: still still people are still people who go viral, they're still stars that kind of have

02:38:25.120 --> 02:38:29.680
[Guest]: overnight successes, you know, so to speak, but it's not you still it still comes from

02:38:29.680 --> 02:38:31.440
[Guest]: a certain class background.

02:38:31.440 --> 02:38:37.480
[Guest]: You kind of see that very obviously, you know, you you people who get internet culture people

02:38:37.480 --> 02:38:45.500
[Guest]: who have the wherewithal the the access again the privilege the the education the in jokes,

02:38:45.500 --> 02:38:49.920
[Guest]: you know to understand that this is what is going to work on the internet and doing it

02:38:49.920 --> 02:38:54.480
[Guest]: you still have people, you know, and Amit Bhadana kind of, you know, in Haryanvi will

02:38:54.480 --> 02:38:59.280
[Guest]: do something you have like this really interesting platform by the folks who were actually, you

02:38:59.280 --> 02:39:03.320
[Guest]: know, started, I forget the name of the organization, but we're in dreamers as well who started

02:39:03.320 --> 02:39:04.320
[Amit Varma]: something.

02:39:04.320 --> 02:39:05.880
[Amit Varma]: They started witty feed and now they're on stage.

02:39:05.880 --> 02:39:07.360
[Amit Varma]: I had Vinay Singhal on my show.

02:39:07.360 --> 02:39:10.960
[Guest]: Exactly Vinay Singhal, you know, again, they're doing such interesting work now, you know,

02:39:10.960 --> 02:39:12.760
[Guest]: so what is the future of this?

02:39:12.760 --> 02:39:18.560
[Guest]: I don't know, you know, the power structures are still very much based out of Bombay, Delhi,

02:39:18.560 --> 02:39:20.880
[Guest]: you know, the money flows through there.

02:39:20.880 --> 02:39:24.960
[Guest]: So but there is, you know, money that is also coming in and I'm sure that at some point

02:39:24.960 --> 02:39:25.960
[Guest]: they will notice.

02:39:25.960 --> 02:39:30.480
[Guest]: I saw that when I think either Praveen or Vinay, we're having a conversation online.

02:39:30.480 --> 02:39:35.560
[Guest]: I saw that they had come to Bombay too and they went to the sets of Nikhil Advani's show

02:39:35.560 --> 02:39:37.000
[Guest]: Mumbai Diaries.

02:39:37.000 --> 02:39:41.200
[Guest]: So clearly like filmmakers also taking note and saying like who are these interesting,

02:39:41.200 --> 02:39:46.240
[Guest]: you know, young people who are doing something in regional using the internet and ultimately

02:39:46.240 --> 02:39:51.440
[Guest]: they have access to communities and audiences that we may not have.

02:39:51.440 --> 02:39:57.840
[Guest]: So in the need to find those audiences, which they can obviously monetize, maybe our films

02:39:57.840 --> 02:39:58.920
[Guest]: will change.

02:39:58.920 --> 02:40:03.080
[Guest]: But my big worry is that they're only going to change because South films are the biggest

02:40:03.080 --> 02:40:04.080
[Guest]: hits right now.

02:40:04.080 --> 02:40:09.720
[Guest]: So our films will also start again replicating the success formula of South films and South

02:40:09.720 --> 02:40:17.320
[Guest]: films and big blockbusters, unfortunately have never, you know, gotten, have never had

02:40:17.320 --> 02:40:20.840
[Guest]: an evolved understanding of gender.

02:40:20.840 --> 02:40:24.160
[Guest]: That's my worry that again, that'll make a big comeback again in Bollywood because that's

02:40:24.160 --> 02:40:25.160
[Guest]: what's working.

02:40:25.160 --> 02:40:26.160
[Guest]: That's the formula.

02:40:26.160 --> 02:40:27.160
[Guest]: Everyone's right, right.

02:40:27.160 --> 02:40:28.160
[Guest]: And then we're going to go backward.

02:40:28.160 --> 02:40:34.360
[Amit Varma]: So in the very fascinating episode I did with Vinay, he pointed out one interesting thing.

02:40:34.360 --> 02:40:38.960
[Amit Varma]: He said that stage is doing so well that there's now a reverse migration.

02:40:38.960 --> 02:40:43.680
[Amit Varma]: Ki Haryana se ya Rajasthan se jo bachche aate the Bombay mein film banane ke liye, ab wapal

02:40:43.680 --> 02:40:46.000
[Amit Varma]: ja rahe hai because they can make it in their language.

02:40:46.000 --> 02:40:49.960
[Amit Varma]: And not just a language, their dialect, like I'd encourage all listeners who haven't already

02:40:49.960 --> 02:40:56.040
[Amit Varma]: heard it to listen to my episode with Vinay because the profound point there was about

02:40:56.040 --> 02:41:02.480
[Amit Varma]: how it was of a kind of localization, like I was always worried about homogenization

02:41:02.480 --> 02:41:04.880
[Amit Varma]: happening in our society.

02:41:04.880 --> 02:41:09.520
[Amit Varma]: One point that Vinay made really well was ki shaher mein bhasha hoti hai, shaher ke

02:41:09.520 --> 02:41:10.840
[Amit Varma]: bahar boli hoti hai.

02:41:10.840 --> 02:41:15.400
[Amit Varma]: You know, a city will have a language and outside a city you'll have dialects.

02:41:15.400 --> 02:41:20.360
[Amit Varma]: And the typical pressure used to be that a small kid will, like Vinay, born in a Haryanvi

02:41:20.360 --> 02:41:24.800
[Amit Varma]: village, he'll speak a particular dialect, but he'll go to the city and he'll feel inferior

02:41:24.800 --> 02:41:28.800
[Amit Varma]: because you know, everybody else seems more sophisticated outside and looking in border

02:41:28.800 --> 02:41:31.080
[Amit Varma]: wale like that beautiful term.

02:41:31.080 --> 02:41:35.840
[Amit Varma]: And the incentive will be to speak to Hindi and so all the dialects die out and that these

02:41:35.840 --> 02:41:39.040
[Amit Varma]: main languages Hindi, Bengali and all of those remain.

02:41:39.040 --> 02:41:44.840
[Amit Varma]: But what is happening here is kind of the opposite, which is incredibly inspiring that,

02:41:44.840 --> 02:41:48.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, so many people tell him that they feel so empowered.

02:41:48.800 --> 02:41:51.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, people will go and tell him ki are all my life has spoken Haryanvi, but I was

02:41:51.920 --> 02:41:53.040
[Amit Varma]: embarrassed about it.

02:41:53.040 --> 02:41:56.660
[Amit Varma]: But now I'm feeling ki theek hai, no, I can take pride in my culture.

02:41:56.660 --> 02:41:59.720
[Amit Varma]: And it's an incredibly inspiring story.

02:41:59.720 --> 02:42:06.120
[Amit Varma]: And I completely agree so much with what you said about snobs, like no disrespect to snobs

02:42:06.120 --> 02:42:07.120
[Unknown]: intended.

02:42:07.120 --> 02:42:12.240
[Amit Varma]: But you know, one thing, one thing I tell my writing students also is that read whatever

02:42:12.240 --> 02:42:13.240
[Amit Varma]: you enjoy reading.

02:42:13.240 --> 02:42:17.600
[Amit Varma]: You know, koi hierarchy nahi hai, ki is bookne yeh prize jeeta hai, yeh toh somehow you got

02:42:17.600 --> 02:42:18.600
[Amit Varma]: to struggle through it.

02:42:18.600 --> 02:42:22.480
[Amit Varma]: No, everything that captures your attention is doing something right.

02:42:22.480 --> 02:42:27.000
[Amit Varma]: You will learn from it, you will internalize that stuff by osmosis, you'll pick up those

02:42:27.000 --> 02:42:28.000
[Amit Varma]: tricks and all that.

02:42:28.000 --> 02:42:34.240
[Amit Varma]: I want to ask you a question about structure in the context of actual filmmaking, right?

02:42:34.240 --> 02:42:39.480
[Amit Varma]: Now, to take a step back in the creator economy, one of the really heartening things that I've

02:42:39.480 --> 02:42:44.440
[Amit Varma]: seen happening over the last decade or so, is what Kevin Kelly wrote about in his famous

02:42:44.440 --> 02:42:49.000
[Amit Varma]: essay, 1000 true fans has kind of happened, like Kevin Kelly wrote this cult essay around

02:42:49.000 --> 02:42:52.280
[Amit Varma]: 2009 2010, called 1000 true fans.

02:42:52.280 --> 02:42:56.760
[Amit Varma]: And his point was that creators will not have to scale anymore.

02:42:56.760 --> 02:43:01.040
[Amit Varma]: In the past, your model always has been ki aapko scale karna hai, right?

02:43:01.040 --> 02:43:06.200
[Amit Varma]: So your top 1% of people make a lot of money, everybody else is struggling and you know,

02:43:06.200 --> 02:43:09.160
[Amit Varma]: having cutting chai in the tapris or varsova.

02:43:09.160 --> 02:43:12.960
[Amit Varma]: But his point was that now you don't have to scale a creator.

02:43:12.960 --> 02:43:18.720
[Amit Varma]: If you can find 1000 fans who pay you $100 a year, that's $100,000, right?

02:43:18.720 --> 02:43:21.200
[Amit Varma]: And when he wrote that, it wasn't happening.

02:43:21.200 --> 02:43:24.020
[Amit Varma]: But he was very prescient, because it is happening today.

02:43:24.020 --> 02:43:27.880
[Amit Varma]: It is definitely happening today, like on Substack, for example, that $100 a year is

02:43:27.880 --> 02:43:31.960
[Amit Varma]: your standard, this thing and all kinds of people who haven't been heard of before are

02:43:31.960 --> 02:43:34.060
[Amit Varma]: literally making millions doing that.

02:43:34.060 --> 02:43:36.680
[Amit Varma]: So it has completely become possible.

02:43:36.680 --> 02:43:42.760
[Amit Varma]: And in the audiovisual medium, the tools of production have become superbly democratized.

02:43:42.760 --> 02:43:48.840
[Amit Varma]: Really, anybody I think today, if they have the will, can actually make a film, right?

02:43:48.840 --> 02:43:54.160
[Amit Varma]: Like a one great example is a Japanese film, One Cut of the Dead, amazing film, which was

02:43:54.160 --> 02:43:58.640
[Amit Varma]: made for the equivalent of 20 lakhs and made the equivalent of 200 crores, something like

02:43:58.640 --> 02:43:59.640
[Amit Varma]: that.

02:43:59.640 --> 02:44:05.140
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, no film has really filled me with the joy of cinema, as that did.

02:44:05.140 --> 02:44:10.120
[Amit Varma]: So the thing is, you know, if you have the will, you can make a film for 20 lakhs now.

02:44:10.120 --> 02:44:12.360
[Amit Varma]: But the bottleneck is the distribution.

02:44:12.360 --> 02:44:17.080
[Amit Varma]: And part of the problem there is, the model through which we consume cinema is this very

02:44:17.080 --> 02:44:23.900
[Amit Varma]: weird model, where a lot of people congregate in a big hall and watch a film together, right?

02:44:23.900 --> 02:44:26.940
[Amit Varma]: And if you think about it in isolation, we've normalized that model.

02:44:26.940 --> 02:44:31.180
[Amit Varma]: But if you think about it in isolation, or if an alien had to come to this planet and

02:44:31.180 --> 02:44:36.440
[Amit Varma]: think about how do we entertain people, this would seem like a very stupid model, because

02:44:36.440 --> 02:44:39.120
[Amit Varma]: this requires you to scale, right?

02:44:39.120 --> 02:44:42.840
[Amit Varma]: Now, what we have seen creators doing in the audiovisual medium is you don't have to scale,

02:44:42.840 --> 02:44:47.020
[Amit Varma]: you had TikTok, which you still have elsewhere, you have YouTube, YouTube creators don't need

02:44:47.020 --> 02:44:54.280
[Amit Varma]: to scale anymore, you know, but in terms of actual cinematic storytelling, this still

02:44:54.280 --> 02:44:58.420
[Amit Varma]: seems like a fundamental bottleneck, ki aise kyu hai?

02:44:58.420 --> 02:45:02.560
[Amit Varma]: Maybe there's there are intermediate models, like you have small halls, which people can

02:45:02.560 --> 02:45:07.320
[Amit Varma]: just book online, pachas log kuch dekhna chahate hain, bees log kuch dekhna chahate hain, you

02:45:07.320 --> 02:45:09.320
[Amit Varma]: have a room somewhere.

02:45:09.320 --> 02:45:14.040
[Amit Varma]: What is also another trend that seems to be happening is that the kind of films which

02:45:14.040 --> 02:45:19.140
[Amit Varma]: succeed in big theatres are now the spectacle films which require the big theatres.

02:45:19.140 --> 02:45:25.320
[Amit Varma]: So your Marvel Cinematic Universe and RRR and all that, and the intimate cinema, you

02:45:25.320 --> 02:45:31.480
[Amit Varma]: expect that to move to OTT and all of that, toh Ingmar Bergman OTT pe aap dekho, aur you

02:45:31.480 --> 02:45:34.160
[Amit Varma]: know, Steven Spielberg aap hall pe jaake dekho.

02:45:34.160 --> 02:45:38.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, so what is your thought of this structurally?

02:45:38.040 --> 02:45:43.080
[Amit Varma]: Because again, it seems that, you know, I feel like 15 years later, everything will

02:45:43.080 --> 02:45:44.160
[Amit Varma]: be different.

02:45:44.160 --> 02:45:47.120
[Amit Varma]: But we can't imagine how because it's unknown unknowns.

02:45:47.120 --> 02:45:51.760
[Amit Varma]: But right now what we have is an artefact of the past that we are somehow kind of, you

02:45:51.760 --> 02:45:53.820
[Amit Varma]: know, still struggling with.

02:45:53.820 --> 02:45:58.800
[Amit Varma]: So my question is structurally, how do you think we can get past this?

02:45:58.800 --> 02:46:02.560
[Amit Varma]: The fact that the means of production are in everybody's hand, aap aur main agar ek

02:46:02.560 --> 02:46:08.280
[Amit Varma]: idea karte hain, bana sakte hain in very little money, you know, but it will not find a thousand

02:46:08.280 --> 02:46:10.240
[Amit Varma]: true fans even if they exist.

02:46:10.240 --> 02:46:12.240
[Amit Varma]: The bottleneck is there.

02:46:12.240 --> 02:46:18.280
[Guest]: See, you are talking about structure purely because you're talking about film in the long

02:46:18.280 --> 02:46:20.640
[Guest]: form medium, right?

02:46:20.640 --> 02:46:26.760
[Guest]: But that is not the only way of making film now.

02:46:26.760 --> 02:46:31.480
[Guest]: What people are doing with one and a half minutes right now is also filmmaking, you

02:46:31.480 --> 02:46:38.720
[Guest]: know, and you can consume for one hour, you know, 30 of those, 40 of those videos or you

02:46:38.720 --> 02:46:44.080
[Guest]: can spend that one hour in watching one episode of a web show or you can spend, you know,

02:46:44.080 --> 02:46:50.080
[Guest]: James Gunn said this brilliant thing where he said that, you know, I mean, some of it

02:46:50.080 --> 02:46:53.520
[Guest]: I'm going to add to it, but because I'm going to Indianize it, but like when you watch a

02:46:53.520 --> 02:47:00.080
[Guest]: film in India, let's say, let's say an example, you have to spend half a day of your time

02:47:00.080 --> 02:47:01.320
[Guest]: to go and watch that film.

02:47:01.320 --> 02:47:04.160
[Guest]: There's half a day of your life that you have to take away.

02:47:04.160 --> 02:47:08.720
[Guest]: It's a community experience because India mein films again, to go into the history,

02:47:08.720 --> 02:47:15.280
[Guest]: logic, et cetera, the highest crossing film in India at a 500, 700 crores, which is RRR

02:47:15.280 --> 02:47:19.400
[Guest]: or Bahubali has been watched by 4% of Indians in theaters.

02:47:19.400 --> 02:47:24.600
[Guest]: That's how many people it takes to watch the highest crossing 4% of film people going to

02:47:24.600 --> 02:47:25.600
[Guest]: theaters.

02:47:25.600 --> 02:47:30.840
[Guest]: Some of them are going for the second time, people, families in India go for films at

02:47:30.840 --> 02:47:35.680
[Guest]: a, on a Diwali or an Eid or one of those, because it's an expensive medium.

02:47:35.680 --> 02:47:38.240
[Guest]: So it is community viewing because of that.

02:47:38.240 --> 02:47:40.240
[Guest]: It isn't family outing.

02:47:40.240 --> 02:47:42.480
[Guest]: You go to the park every day, which is free.

02:47:42.480 --> 02:47:46.160
[Guest]: And then when you have a little bit of money for the middle class or, you know, upwardly

02:47:46.160 --> 02:47:50.840
[Guest]: mobile, you know, then you go and kind of, uh, go and watch a film, take your whole family

02:47:50.840 --> 02:47:55.600
[Guest]: and say, which is why the stars also happen because you go and watch the film of that

02:47:55.600 --> 02:48:00.160
[Guest]: one person that you kind of know historically, you will not go and watch the film of a younger

02:48:00.160 --> 02:48:01.160
[Guest]: person.

02:48:01.160 --> 02:48:04.840
[Guest]: And when nationalistic or patriotic films happened, they kind of, uh, you know, said

02:48:04.840 --> 02:48:09.520
[Guest]: you don't need to know who's in it as, because it is about your country or the issue that

02:48:09.520 --> 02:48:10.520
[Guest]: you care about.

02:48:10.520 --> 02:48:13.240
[Guest]: You're going as a community to watch that and say, okay, I want to know what happened

02:48:13.240 --> 02:48:14.240
[Guest]: to my community.

02:48:14.240 --> 02:48:16.840
[Guest]: So that is an example.

02:48:16.840 --> 02:48:23.400
