[Guest]: masculinity is in me, conditioned in me, that I am unable to cry otherwise.

03:01:27.120 --> 03:01:35.360
[Guest]: When my grandfather passed away, and I was as close to him, I, and in fact, the reason

03:01:35.360 --> 03:01:39.720
[Guest]: that I came to NID Kurukshetra was because it's next to Karnal.

03:01:39.720 --> 03:01:42.280
[Guest]: And my grandfather and my maasi lived in Karnal.

03:01:42.280 --> 03:01:46.040
[Guest]: And I wanted to spend, I'd never, I loved my grandfather, but never spent any time with

03:01:46.040 --> 03:01:47.040
[Guest]: him.

03:01:47.040 --> 03:01:48.040
[Guest]: So I wanted to live close to him.

03:01:48.040 --> 03:01:49.040
[Guest]: And then weekends I would spend with him.

03:01:49.040 --> 03:01:51.760
[Guest]: So I was like, very fortunate to have gotten some time with him.

03:01:51.760 --> 03:01:58.360
[Guest]: When he died, for two days, I couldn't cry, just could not cry.

03:01:58.360 --> 03:01:59.360
[Guest]: Why?

03:01:59.360 --> 03:02:04.600
[Guest]: Because I was, my maasi was crying nonstop, just consoling her.

03:02:04.600 --> 03:02:07.960
[Guest]: I was just like, suddenly I fell into the duty of my man.

03:02:07.960 --> 03:02:10.880
[Guest]: Okay, my manly duty is that I have to take care of all the guests.

03:02:10.880 --> 03:02:12.500
[Guest]: My maasi is in no condition.

03:02:12.500 --> 03:02:14.320
[Guest]: So I will take care of all the arrangements.

03:02:14.320 --> 03:02:17.400
[Guest]: I'll tell you, tell me what she's, it's not that she wasn't doing, she was doing a lot

03:02:17.400 --> 03:02:20.040
[Guest]: of stuff herself, but she was broken.

03:02:20.040 --> 03:02:23.120
[Guest]: And her, my uncle hadn't reached yet.

03:02:23.120 --> 03:02:25.280
[Guest]: My mother from Barain hadn't reached yet.

03:02:25.280 --> 03:02:27.280
[Guest]: Nobody had been able to reach at that time.

03:02:27.280 --> 03:02:35.520
[Guest]: So a whole day, day and a half, I was just taking care of all the duties of the, of a

03:02:35.520 --> 03:02:42.120
[Guest]: household where someone's passed away without, when my friends came to be like, we're sorry

03:02:42.120 --> 03:02:44.960
[Guest]: from Kurukshetra, you know, how are you feeling, et cetera.

03:02:44.960 --> 03:02:48.640
[Guest]: And I'm like, sad, didn't have tears.

03:02:48.640 --> 03:02:54.760
[Guest]: It's only when one and a half days later, when my mother and I got a quiet moment and

03:02:54.760 --> 03:02:59.960
[Guest]: my mother just asked me, how are you feeling that I burst into tears.

03:02:59.960 --> 03:03:07.960
[Guest]: I was, and then I was inconsolable because just that moment of her reaching out and actually

03:03:07.960 --> 03:03:10.200
[Guest]: caring about my own emotion and being like, how are you feeling?

03:03:10.200 --> 03:03:12.480
[Guest]: I was just like, that's it.

03:03:12.480 --> 03:03:13.680
[Guest]: I just had tears.

03:03:13.680 --> 03:03:15.480
[Guest]: But I can't cry otherwise.

03:03:15.480 --> 03:03:17.160
[Guest]: It's very difficult for me to cry.

03:03:17.160 --> 03:03:26.320
[Guest]: I yeah, and, and, and films have, and that is also why I am, I, I love film so much because

03:03:26.320 --> 03:03:32.840
[Guest]: as a man, I'm able to feel things and feel emotions or give space to those emotions that

03:03:32.840 --> 03:03:36.880
[Guest]: I'm otherwise hiding away or I'm otherwise suppressing.

03:03:36.880 --> 03:03:44.120
[Guest]: So, so films have been the most important friend that I've had growing up.

03:03:44.120 --> 03:03:52.360
[Guest]: It has, it has, it has been, yeah, films and shows and, you know, art, cinema, whatever

03:03:52.360 --> 03:03:55.080
[Guest]: you want to call it, have been like a lifesaver for me.

03:03:55.080 --> 03:03:59.960
[Guest]: It made me in a world where I was struggling to fit in, it helped me like find a space

03:03:59.960 --> 03:04:04.160
[Guest]: for a man who was trying to cry, but not able to.

03:04:04.160 --> 03:04:06.960
[Amit Varma]: Then Shah Rukh Khan films happened.

03:04:06.960 --> 03:04:12.920
[Amit Varma]: Okay, wrong reason to cry, I guess, you know, his acting is so bad, that would make me cry.

03:04:12.920 --> 03:04:15.280
[Guest]: Shah Rukh Khan is the love language of India.

03:04:15.280 --> 03:04:19.760
[Amit Varma]: And you've, you've, you've spoken to Shahana, absolutely.

03:04:19.760 --> 03:04:23.160
[Guest]: And a book is just such a great book.

03:04:23.160 --> 03:04:24.160
[Amit Varma]: It's a great book.

03:04:24.160 --> 03:04:26.800
[Amit Varma]: And that's also my most popular episode so far.

03:04:26.800 --> 03:04:31.400
[Amit Varma]: And that's a great metaphor, you know, a cinema hall, a cinema, you know, men crying in the

03:04:31.400 --> 03:04:32.400
[Amit Varma]: dark together.

03:04:32.400 --> 03:04:33.440
[Amit Varma]: That's such a great metaphor.

03:04:33.440 --> 03:04:38.600
[Amit Varma]: On that note, let's go for a break.

03:04:38.600 --> 03:04:41.240
[Amit Varma]: Long before I was a podcaster, I was a writer.

03:04:41.240 --> 03:04:46.360
[Amit Varma]: In fact, chances are that many of you first heard of me because of my blog India Uncut,

03:04:46.360 --> 03:04:51.200
[Amit Varma]: which was active between 2003 and 2009, and became somewhat popular at the time.

03:04:51.200 --> 03:04:53.480
[Amit Varma]: I love the freedom the form gave me.

03:04:53.480 --> 03:04:56.240
[Amit Varma]: And I feel I was shaped by it in many ways.

03:04:56.240 --> 03:05:01.160
[Amit Varma]: I exercise my writing muscle every day, and was forced to think about many different things

03:05:01.160 --> 03:05:03.480
[Amit Varma]: because I wrote about many different things.

03:05:03.480 --> 03:05:06.720
[Amit Varma]: Well, that phase in my life ended for various reasons.

03:05:06.720 --> 03:05:08.440
[Amit Varma]: And now it is time to revive it.

03:05:08.440 --> 03:05:11.200
[Amit Varma]: Only now, I'm doing it through a newsletter.

03:05:11.200 --> 03:05:17.240
[Amit Varma]: I have started the India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com, where I will write

03:05:17.240 --> 03:05:19.840
[Amit Varma]: regularly about whatever catches my fancy.

03:05:19.840 --> 03:05:24.440
[Amit Varma]: I'll write about some of the themes I cover in this podcast, and about much else.

03:05:24.440 --> 03:05:29.080
[Amit Varma]: So please do head on over to indiancut.substack.com and subscribe.

03:05:29.080 --> 03:05:30.080
[Amit Varma]: It is free.

03:05:30.080 --> 03:05:34.560
[Amit Varma]: And once you sign up, each new installment that I write will land up in your email inbox.

03:05:34.560 --> 03:05:36.360
[Amit Varma]: You don't need to go anywhere.

03:05:36.360 --> 03:05:38.400
[Amit Varma]: So subscribe now for free.

03:05:38.400 --> 03:05:42.720
[Amit Varma]: The India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com.

03:05:42.720 --> 03:05:46.160
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

03:05:46.160 --> 03:05:47.440
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

03:05:47.440 --> 03:05:51.240
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Nikhil Taneja about his fascinating life and work and so on.

03:05:51.240 --> 03:05:57.240
[Amit Varma]: And let's now come back to sort of the chronological narrative.

03:05:57.240 --> 03:06:03.120
[Amit Varma]: You pointed out key engineering was basically your gap years, where you were figuring out

03:06:03.120 --> 03:06:04.640
[Amit Varma]: what to do with your life.

03:06:04.640 --> 03:06:07.120
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about this process.

03:06:07.120 --> 03:06:12.280
[Amit Varma]: Because you know, when I look back on my college years, and when I speak to others as well

03:06:12.280 --> 03:06:17.320
[Amit Varma]: who've come on the show, what I find is key, there are two kinds of pulls and pressures

03:06:17.320 --> 03:06:18.320
[Amit Varma]: happening.

03:06:18.320 --> 03:06:22.240
[Amit Varma]: And one is you want to fit in with your peers, you want to fit in with the cool boys or you

03:06:22.240 --> 03:06:26.720
[Amit Varma]: want to, you know, so you're molding yourself to kind of fit in or to whatever, you know,

03:06:26.720 --> 03:06:29.920
[Amit Varma]: similar to the pressure of being a man in a sense.

03:06:29.920 --> 03:06:34.720
[Amit Varma]: And the other is you're trying to figure yourself out, find yourself and very often you're constructing

03:06:34.720 --> 03:06:40.200
[Amit Varma]: for yourself a self image of what you want to be seen as rather than trying to actually

03:06:40.200 --> 03:06:42.920
[Amit Varma]: understand who you really are.

03:06:42.920 --> 03:06:47.320
[Amit Varma]: Now I'm guessing that since you landed up there as the NRI cool boy, I guess that pressure

03:06:47.320 --> 03:06:51.080
[Amit Varma]: would not have been so intense, the first pressure of fitting in and so on.

03:06:51.080 --> 03:06:58.760
[Amit Varma]: But through your life, how has that process been of getting to understand yourself a little

03:06:58.760 --> 03:06:59.760
[Amit Varma]: better?

03:06:59.760 --> 03:07:04.440
[Amit Varma]: You've already spoken about how the therapy you did later on in dealing with anxiety kind

03:07:04.440 --> 03:07:07.520
[Amit Varma]: of helped with an aspect of that.

03:07:07.520 --> 03:07:13.400
[Amit Varma]: But in general, take me through this process of understanding who you are and what you

03:07:13.400 --> 03:07:16.640
[Amit Varma]: are and coming to terms with it.

03:07:16.640 --> 03:07:23.480
[Guest]: I don't think that I had the self-awareness of any kind of self-awareness about myself

03:07:23.480 --> 03:07:34.240
[Guest]: when I was younger, when I was in college, you know, as I said, I think the three and

03:07:34.240 --> 03:07:39.880
[Guest]: a half years for me were again, once I found out that it was all about like, now what can

03:07:39.880 --> 03:07:40.880
[Guest]: I do with my time?

03:07:40.880 --> 03:07:45.560
[Guest]: And as I said, I started writing, I started furiously, you know, there's this incident

03:07:45.560 --> 03:07:50.600
[Guest]: that happened much later, which was actually quite like sweet when I met a college friend

03:07:50.600 --> 03:07:51.600
[Guest]: many years later.

03:07:51.600 --> 03:07:54.600
[Guest]: And, you know, I was in Hindustan three, four years after college, I was still in Hindustan

03:07:54.600 --> 03:08:00.000
[Guest]: and I was earning a lot of, not earning too much again, you know, 14 and a half thousand

03:08:00.000 --> 03:08:05.120
[Guest]: for two and a half years in Bombay, you know, it's just tough.

03:08:05.120 --> 03:08:07.760
[Guest]: I met like a friend who had gone to US after that.

03:08:07.760 --> 03:08:12.320
[Guest]: And he came back from the US and just came for a visit or something.

03:08:12.320 --> 03:08:16.880
[Guest]: And I just met him and I was just, he's like, how's life, I was like, I'm not really happy

03:08:16.880 --> 03:08:17.880
[Guest]: right now.

03:08:17.880 --> 03:08:21.880
[Guest]: Because he's like, because I'm not earning the money, you know, I don't know if I'll

03:08:21.880 --> 03:08:23.880
[Guest]: be successful or not.

03:08:23.880 --> 03:08:27.920
[Guest]: And he's not someone I kind of was very close with, you know, he's just someone like I was

03:08:27.920 --> 03:08:30.440
[Guest]: friends with, but not very close friends with.

03:08:30.440 --> 03:08:32.360
[Guest]: So he just said, he's like, are you mad?

03:08:32.360 --> 03:08:34.320
[Guest]: You're going, you know, it's like, why, what happened?

03:08:34.320 --> 03:08:39.560
[Guest]: He's like, he's like, I haven't, you were the only person in our college where all of

03:08:39.560 --> 03:08:46.120
[Guest]: us were, you know, we used to drink and study, so we sat in our room, you were churning out

03:08:46.120 --> 03:08:51.360
[Guest]: issues of your magazine, you know, you were the only one who was, who was late till three

03:08:51.360 --> 03:08:57.280
[Guest]: o'clock in the, in the night, trying to make something out of your life, while the rest

03:08:57.280 --> 03:09:01.040
[Guest]: of us were, you know, just doing nonsense.

03:09:01.040 --> 03:09:04.200
[Guest]: And there is, even if you're not successful right now, there's no chance you won't be

03:09:04.200 --> 03:09:05.200
[Guest]: in the future.

03:09:05.200 --> 03:09:10.040
[Guest]: So I feel like, as I said, I still have some, you know, until like someone else tells me,

03:09:10.040 --> 03:09:15.440
[Guest]: I never look at myself as like, you know, I'm doing enough for whatever reasons.

03:09:15.440 --> 03:09:19.520
[Guest]: And it just hit me that, yeah, that's, that's been my college, you know, I actually, so

03:09:19.520 --> 03:09:26.680
[Guest]: I don't drink, I don't smoke, I don't do drugs, I don't have, I've never had any of these,

03:09:26.680 --> 03:09:27.680
[Amit Varma]: you know.

03:09:27.680 --> 03:09:38.200
[Guest]: I take four numbers of girls, which is clearly the vice, you know, for a lot of people there.

03:09:38.200 --> 03:09:44.800
[Guest]: But, but yeah, like, you know, I just, beyond a point, I didn't have enough things, you

03:09:44.800 --> 03:09:48.760
[Guest]: know, times or reasons to hang out with, you know, you hang out with your friends until

03:09:48.760 --> 03:09:52.440
[Guest]: they start drinking, because after they're drinking, then it's just a drunken conversation

03:09:52.440 --> 03:09:55.380
[Guest]: where you are the sober person, you're like, what am I doing here?

03:09:55.380 --> 03:09:57.120
[Guest]: So you don't have those conversations.

03:09:57.120 --> 03:09:58.120
[Guest]: I did.

03:09:58.120 --> 03:10:01.160
[Guest]: Although, on the other hand, I think while I didn't learn much about myself, I learned

03:10:01.160 --> 03:10:05.960
[Guest]: a lot about India, you know, because, again, fortunately, unfortunately, there's no LAN

03:10:05.960 --> 03:10:09.520
[Guest]: in our, this is 2004 to 2008.

03:10:09.520 --> 03:10:10.520
[Guest]: That's where I studied.

03:10:10.520 --> 03:10:13.440
[Guest]: 2000, there was no LAN in our college.

03:10:13.440 --> 03:10:16.560
[Guest]: And there was only like one computer center where you had internet.

03:10:16.560 --> 03:10:21.920
[Guest]: So in your hostel, and because Haryana and North India, and there's always power cuts.

03:10:21.920 --> 03:10:27.120
[Guest]: So every night for one and a half hours, the electricity would just go off.

03:10:27.120 --> 03:10:28.500
[Guest]: And then what do you do?

03:10:28.500 --> 03:10:30.600
[Guest]: Your phone at that time, again, was expensive.

03:10:30.600 --> 03:10:34.760
[Guest]: So you can't call people until I think my third year things became inexpensive and you

03:10:34.760 --> 03:10:37.600
[Guest]: had free calling and free messaging, or whatever.

03:10:37.600 --> 03:10:39.720
[Guest]: And that's the year I made a girlfriend.

03:10:39.720 --> 03:10:41.880
[Guest]: So clearly, thank you Airtel.

03:10:41.880 --> 03:10:47.680
[Guest]: But before that, you didn't even know enough, I mean, while you had that one number after

03:10:47.680 --> 03:10:51.720
[Guest]: that incident, I was like, I'm never calling a woman in my life now.

03:10:51.720 --> 03:10:54.880
[Guest]: But so what did you do?

03:10:54.880 --> 03:10:59.560
[Guest]: And I kind of started after like getting really bored and, you know, talking to my roommates

03:10:59.560 --> 03:11:02.800
[Guest]: and my roommates, I didn't really get along within the first couple of I mean, decent

03:11:02.800 --> 03:11:05.680
[Guest]: people just didn't have much in common.

03:11:05.680 --> 03:11:10.520
[Guest]: I started recognizing that, you know, well, I'm in this campus where there are these people

03:11:10.520 --> 03:11:14.000
[Guest]: from all over the country, from every state of India.

03:11:14.000 --> 03:11:18.160
[Guest]: I have every day there's a power cut, I have nothing to do, nobody can do anything in first

03:11:18.160 --> 03:11:19.160
[Guest]: year.

03:11:19.160 --> 03:11:25.880
[Guest]: So maybe I'll just go and like, find the stories of others, right?

03:11:25.880 --> 03:11:29.440
[Guest]: And it wasn't like a conscious, like, I'm going to find the stories of others.

03:11:29.440 --> 03:11:31.880
[Guest]: It was more like, let me just go and chat with other people, right?

03:11:31.880 --> 03:11:35.120
[Guest]: So I just go up to somebody's room and like, I've never met and just knock on their door

03:11:35.120 --> 03:11:43.560
[Guest]: and be like, you know, we stayed the same, you know, yeah, same hostel or the same floor

03:11:43.560 --> 03:11:45.160
[Guest]: or whatever it is.

03:11:45.160 --> 03:11:47.200
[Guest]: And we've never spoken.

03:11:47.200 --> 03:11:51.760
[Guest]: So yeah, I'm Nikhil and this is where I'm from, I'd love to know a little bit about

03:11:51.760 --> 03:11:52.760
[Guest]: you.

03:11:52.760 --> 03:11:55.040
[Guest]: And then suddenly, like some of those conversations would go nowhere, people were just also not

03:11:55.040 --> 03:11:56.040
[Guest]: very open.

03:11:56.040 --> 03:11:59.400
[Guest]: And then some of them would just turn into like really deep conversations.

03:11:59.400 --> 03:12:03.520
[Guest]: And and sometimes I would have it only once in like, I've spoken to some people during

03:12:03.520 --> 03:12:08.440
[Guest]: power cuts once and never spoken to them again, beyond hi, hello for the rest of my college

03:12:08.440 --> 03:12:09.440
[Guest]: life.

03:12:09.440 --> 03:12:13.680
[Guest]: But that one conversation was deep enough for me to kind of, you know, like if I if

03:12:13.680 --> 03:12:17.680
[Guest]: we ever see each other in public, we hug the hell out of each other and just be like, Oh,

03:12:17.680 --> 03:12:20.120
[Guest]: my God, like, so great to see you after all these years.

03:12:20.120 --> 03:12:26.600
[Guest]: So because of that, I kind of got a sense and understanding of, you know, the stories

03:12:26.600 --> 03:12:27.600
[Guest]: of others.

03:12:27.600 --> 03:12:31.040
[Guest]: And I think that helped me recognize a little bit of our own story as well.

03:12:31.040 --> 03:12:35.080
[Guest]: I didn't know what stories were, I didn't know that, you know, like, again, self awareness

03:12:35.080 --> 03:12:39.920
[Guest]: neither you didn't have the internet, I, you didn't, as even though I was writing for a

03:12:39.920 --> 03:12:45.040
[Guest]: newspaper, you know, or a magazine at that time, even at that time, I did not have like

03:12:45.040 --> 03:12:47.640
[Guest]: Chetan Bhagat did not exist at that time.

03:12:47.640 --> 03:12:53.360
[Guest]: Even at that time, there was no example, a public example of, you know, people who could

03:12:53.360 --> 03:12:54.920
[Guest]: have stories like mine.

03:12:54.920 --> 03:12:57.960
[Guest]: And most of the stories I would hear of people who kind of did the other thing, right?

03:12:57.960 --> 03:13:02.440
[Guest]: So you kind of also connected with that somebody who's a lovely singer, I would find out, you

03:13:02.440 --> 03:13:03.760
[Guest]: know, who's come from this.

03:13:03.760 --> 03:13:07.320
[Guest]: But the reason that I'm like, why don't you go into one of these reality shows and like,

03:13:07.320 --> 03:13:11.840
[Guest]: you know, try singing, just be like, I'm the only child of my family.

03:13:11.840 --> 03:13:15.240
[Guest]: And or I'm the, you know, elder son of my family.

03:13:15.240 --> 03:13:18.920
[Guest]: And my aim is to make it to Microsoft.

03:13:18.920 --> 03:13:23.880
[Guest]: Because that's the way I mean, I need to my parents have put so much money, you know,

03:13:23.880 --> 03:13:26.600
[Guest]: I need to be the return on investment for them.

03:13:26.600 --> 03:13:29.240
[Guest]: And for whatever it was that boy is in Microsoft now.

03:13:29.240 --> 03:13:33.200
[Guest]: And you know, he's made it but he's a beautiful singing voice, which I don't know if anybody

03:13:33.200 --> 03:13:37.560
[Guest]: will ever get to listen to beyond like, the close circle of friends that he may have,

03:13:37.560 --> 03:13:40.120
[Guest]: which is also okay, you know, I mean, sure.

03:13:40.120 --> 03:13:43.560
[Guest]: But I'm just saying like, so many stories that I would hear from so many people from

03:13:43.560 --> 03:13:47.920
[Guest]: all these different parts of India, there's a boy from like, Jammu and Kashmir.

03:13:47.920 --> 03:13:53.600
[Guest]: That I was, it just helped me recognize that, there are so many stories, you know, and every

03:13:53.600 --> 03:13:59.880
[Guest]: story kind of has a, you know, starts with, you know, I mean, nobody really knows where

03:13:59.880 --> 03:14:00.880
[Guest]: it's leading.

03:14:00.880 --> 03:14:06.600
[Guest]: Nobody is aware that, you know, which act of our stories are we are in.

03:14:06.600 --> 03:14:12.920
[Guest]: But there is something there, you know, that, that somewhere makes you recognize that you

03:14:12.920 --> 03:14:19.240
[Guest]: are also a story, you know, where I feel like all of us look at each, I mean, so NID Gurushekhar

03:14:19.240 --> 03:14:24.640
[Guest]: also how we call each other, you know, after a point of time, either we make boys by surname,

03:14:24.640 --> 03:14:31.920
[Guest]: but in our culture, you know, you start calling from wherever you are, so the boy from Bareta,

03:14:31.920 --> 03:14:33.480
[Guest]: you know, is called Bareta.

03:14:33.480 --> 03:14:39.280
[Guest]: The boy from Jammu is called Jammu, you know, Jammu, come here, Bareta, come here.

03:14:39.280 --> 03:14:40.280
[Amit Varma]: So what was yours?

03:14:40.280 --> 03:14:41.280
[Guest]: Barain?

03:14:41.280 --> 03:14:45.800
[Guest]: Yeah, no, Barain for a, you know, a long time, it was Barain Nidhokarnal, but after, as I

03:14:45.800 --> 03:14:49.320
[Guest]: said, like for me, for whatever reason, I was always seen as like this.

03:14:49.320 --> 03:14:54.800
[Guest]: So people would typically call me Taneja or close people would call me like whatever Motu

03:14:54.800 --> 03:14:55.800
[Guest]: etc.

03:14:55.800 --> 03:15:00.880
[Guest]: But I started looking at realizing that every one of them with whatever names or whatever

03:15:00.880 --> 03:15:07.760
[Guest]: labels they were given, there was a story about them that nobody would know that, you

03:15:07.760 --> 03:15:11.120
[Guest]: know, if you just didn't ask them, everyone had a stereotype.

03:15:11.120 --> 03:15:15.880
[Guest]: There's a backbencher, there's a frontbencher, there's a gissu kid, there's a frustu kid,

03:15:15.880 --> 03:15:18.600
[Guest]: all these terms that we used to give each other, you know.

03:15:18.600 --> 03:15:25.400
[Guest]: But beyond that, they all had like this really deep stories that even they wouldn't ever

03:15:25.400 --> 03:15:26.400
[Guest]: think about.

03:15:26.400 --> 03:15:27.400
[Guest]: But that's all I could think about.

03:15:27.400 --> 03:15:30.920
[Guest]: I can't get out of my mind that there is a boy who has such a beautiful singing voice,

03:15:30.920 --> 03:15:36.520
[Guest]: but who's, you know, because he's the eldest son of the family has to only, you know, study

03:15:36.520 --> 03:15:41.280
[Guest]: and do engineering because he has to get into a certain place and he has to make his family

03:15:41.280 --> 03:15:42.280
[Guest]: circumstance better.

03:15:42.280 --> 03:15:46.040
[Guest]: Now that's because I have the privilege to not think at that time, I'd found myself having

03:15:46.040 --> 03:15:51.120
[Guest]: the privilege to not think about and yet I was not living my own story.

03:15:51.120 --> 03:15:55.600
[Guest]: I was also doing engineering, even though I liked writing and I was writing in newspapers

03:15:55.600 --> 03:15:58.120
[Guest]: and magazines and I created my own magazine.

03:15:58.120 --> 03:16:02.200
[Guest]: I've done everything, but I was not doing and you know, funnily what happened and such

03:16:02.200 --> 03:16:05.640
[Guest]: a funny random thing sometimes that happens to you that like puts you on a different path.

03:16:05.640 --> 03:16:11.840
[Guest]: One of my first roommates in my second year, actually first year only afterwards, the second

03:16:11.840 --> 03:16:16.760
[Guest]: roommate I ever had, who I became very good friends with in year one.

03:16:16.760 --> 03:16:17.760
[Guest]: I had met him.

