03:26:51.560 --> 03:26:57.240
[Guest]: So I kind of created a structure basis that but I, that's really also where I kind of

03:26:57.240 --> 03:27:09.560
[Guest]: realized that the joy of, of sharing, or teaching or, you know, helping out in whatever way

03:27:09.560 --> 03:27:14.120
[Guest]: possible and using a privilege in a, in a manner where it's where someone else is benefiting

03:27:14.120 --> 03:27:16.320
[Guest]: off of what you got so easily.

03:27:16.320 --> 03:27:21.160
[Guest]: And even though, as I've said, it wasn't like my whole life has been a piece of cake with

03:27:21.160 --> 03:27:25.800
[Guest]: my parents and whatnot in Bahrain and I said, a lot of bullying had also happened.

03:27:25.800 --> 03:27:31.320
[Guest]: And at the same time, after that, it just stuck to me that, you know, this is something

03:27:31.320 --> 03:27:32.360
[Guest]: that I want to continue doing.

03:27:32.360 --> 03:27:39.840
[Guest]: So when I joined HT, I used to have interns, like nobody, no one knew what they were doing

03:27:39.840 --> 03:27:40.840
[Guest]: in BMM.

03:27:40.840 --> 03:27:47.720
[Guest]: So I just asked one of my friends, who was also a professor at Jain, who had become a

03:27:47.720 --> 03:27:53.320
[Guest]: professor at Jain, I also want to teach because I want to teach like journalism to, you know,

03:27:53.320 --> 03:27:56.360
[Guest]: these young people because they clearly like don't know the structure of writing or whatever

03:27:56.360 --> 03:27:57.360
[Guest]: they come in.

03:27:57.360 --> 03:27:59.920
[Guest]: You know, I don't want people to, I can help them.

03:27:59.920 --> 03:28:06.840
[Guest]: So I came with this, this, this messiah severe complex that I had helped people in NID Kurukshetra

03:28:06.840 --> 03:28:10.280
[Guest]: and now it become like, now I'm going to change the lives of the kids.

03:28:10.280 --> 03:28:13.800
[Guest]: And because there, anybody like, when you got a job, you will get emotional calls from

03:28:13.800 --> 03:28:14.800
[Guest]: people.

03:28:14.800 --> 03:28:15.800
[Guest]: Sir, I got a job.

03:28:15.800 --> 03:28:19.920
[Guest]: Because we used to call seniors, sir, you know, all like, thank you for like that course

03:28:19.920 --> 03:28:25.240
[Guest]: and that changed my life, I was hearing this and I was, my heart was getting full and I

03:28:25.240 --> 03:28:26.760
[Guest]: was like, man, I made a difference.

03:28:26.760 --> 03:28:33.040
[Guest]: And then I went to college in Jain college in Mumbai, and no one gives a shit about the

03:28:33.040 --> 03:28:34.560
[Guest]: professors over there.

03:28:34.560 --> 03:28:35.560
[Guest]: No one cares.

03:28:35.560 --> 03:28:39.400
[Guest]: You can have like this notions and narcissistic notions of like giving back.

03:28:39.400 --> 03:28:40.400
[Guest]: They don't want to receive.

03:28:40.400 --> 03:28:41.400
[Guest]: They're like, screw you.

03:28:41.400 --> 03:28:45.400
[Guest]: You are anyway three years older than us and you want to change our lives, please, bro,

03:28:45.400 --> 03:28:46.400
[Guest]: think about yourself.

03:28:46.400 --> 03:28:49.120
[Guest]: I used to have students come to me after my first batch, it was such a big disaster.

03:28:49.120 --> 03:28:53.200
[Guest]: My first batch students would like message me on Facebook messages saying, like, this

03:28:53.200 --> 03:28:58.240
[Guest]: is maybe how you should go about teaching students are advising me how to be a better

03:28:58.240 --> 03:28:59.240
[Guest]: teacher.

03:28:59.240 --> 03:29:02.560
[Guest]: I was like, this is and I was so like disappointed with the way the first batch went, because

03:29:02.560 --> 03:29:07.800
[Guest]: I'd come with these really wrong notions that I want to give back that in the second batch,

03:29:07.800 --> 03:29:11.360
[Guest]: I wanted to teach one more batch, even the teacher was, you know, like the coordinator

03:29:11.360 --> 03:29:17.520
[Guest]: recognized I failed a little bit in the first batch, although I taught a lot of, you know,

03:29:17.520 --> 03:29:21.880
[Guest]: which nobody cared about also, because like in a BMM batch of 30-40 students, only three

03:29:21.880 --> 03:29:22.880
[Guest]: want to be journalists.

03:29:22.880 --> 03:29:24.680
[Guest]: The rest of them anyway want to do other things.

03:29:24.680 --> 03:29:28.720
[Guest]: So why am I doing news reporting to people, how do they write, what is the structure.

03:29:28.720 --> 03:29:33.560
[Guest]: So second time, I just wanted to kind of, I was like, I'm a little bit more humility

03:29:33.560 --> 03:29:40.720
[Guest]: and go into it with the intent of not just teaching, but also learning, not just talking,

03:29:40.720 --> 03:29:42.520
[Guest]: but also listening.

03:29:42.520 --> 03:29:53.440
[Guest]: And that I did not recognize at that time, but it became a it was a radical thing I ended

03:29:53.440 --> 03:29:57.080
[Guest]: up doing without recognizing or realizing it.

03:29:57.080 --> 03:30:02.720
[Guest]: Because what started happening is because I was so curious and eager to listen to them

03:30:02.720 --> 03:30:09.400
[Guest]: and kind of non-judgmentally learn from them, I came off my high horse and being like, I'm,

03:30:09.400 --> 03:30:12.920
[Guest]: you know, I'm not a teacher here, I mean, while I'm a teacher, but I'm really here to

03:30:12.920 --> 03:30:13.920
[Guest]: listen to you.

03:30:13.920 --> 03:30:18.240
[Guest]: I want to hear your thoughts, your opinions on, I mean, from journalism topics or what's

03:30:18.240 --> 03:30:23.040
[Guest]: happening in the world, but like, let's chat, let's talk, here's a topic I want everyone

03:30:23.040 --> 03:30:24.040
[Guest]: to have their voice.

03:30:24.040 --> 03:30:27.000
[Guest]: And I'd reach out to people and say, you know, this is your voice, tell me, tell me, tell

03:30:27.000 --> 03:30:28.000
[Guest]: me.

03:30:28.000 --> 03:30:31.240
[Guest]: And then slowly students outside of class hours would start coming to me and saying,

03:30:31.240 --> 03:30:35.160
[Guest]: you know, thank you for just like asking me to speak up or it was tough for me, but like

03:30:35.160 --> 03:30:38.960
[Guest]: you made it really comfortable and then would tell me other problems of their life.

03:30:38.960 --> 03:30:41.520
[Guest]: You know, I have this issue with my parents, what do I do?

03:30:41.520 --> 03:30:45.960
[Guest]: And I'm just like, I don't know, like, you know, so I would still give them whatever

03:30:45.960 --> 03:30:51.520
[Guest]: little bit of advice that I could, you know, in whatever more experience I had in life.

03:30:51.520 --> 03:30:56.320
[Guest]: But I also had a recognizing that every one of these kids would come in and talk about

03:30:56.320 --> 03:30:58.040
[Guest]: these things that they cared about.

03:30:58.040 --> 03:31:01.400
[Guest]: And somehow they were not talking to each other.

03:31:01.400 --> 03:31:06.080
[Guest]: I'm like, you said a problem, you said a problem, Sonu's problem is the same, but you're not

03:31:06.080 --> 03:31:07.240
[Guest]: talking to each other.

03:31:07.240 --> 03:31:14.080
[Guest]: This person sits, you know, I mean, Bombay, just again, there's an ecosystem of like hierarchies

03:31:14.080 --> 03:31:15.080
[Guest]: we've spoken about, right?

03:31:15.080 --> 03:31:18.680
[Guest]: There's a hierarchy of how people sit in a Bombay classroom.

03:31:18.680 --> 03:31:26.160
[Guest]: So there is a, there is a Bandra club of people who sit in, in one bunch, you know, who were,

03:31:26.160 --> 03:31:30.400
[Guest]: who would always sit in a, and again, you know, this is, this is, this is just what

03:31:30.400 --> 03:31:32.680
[Guest]: I saw in my classroom.

03:31:32.680 --> 03:31:38.480
[Guest]: Also the kids from Bandra was just not interested in like, you know, journalism or news reporting,

03:31:38.480 --> 03:31:42.600
[Guest]: you know, they were always like, in fact, I've had one of the Bandra students come to

03:31:42.600 --> 03:31:45.200
[Guest]: me and again, I'm not stereotyping, this is just how it was in my class.

03:31:45.200 --> 03:31:46.200
[Guest]: No disrespect.

03:31:46.200 --> 03:31:47.200
[Guest]: No disrespect.

03:31:47.200 --> 03:31:49.400
[Guest]: But Bandra kids have come to me and said, would you like to smoke weed?

03:31:49.400 --> 03:31:54.560
[Guest]: I'm like, I'm your professor, please can you not ask me that question, bro, do you want

03:31:54.560 --> 03:31:55.560
[Guest]: to smoke?

03:31:55.560 --> 03:31:56.560
[Guest]: I'm like, what are you saying?

03:31:56.560 --> 03:31:59.440
[Guest]: First of all, you shouldn't be smoking up a second, you should not be telling me to

03:31:59.440 --> 03:32:00.440
[Guest]: smoke up.

03:32:00.440 --> 03:32:03.560
[Guest]: If you want to do it, do it outside the class, please don't come in the middle of the class

03:32:03.560 --> 03:32:05.680
[Guest]: at the time of college school.

03:32:05.680 --> 03:32:10.280
[Guest]: They were, they were, they were kids from, for example, Navi Mumbai, who would all sit

03:32:10.280 --> 03:32:14.000
[Guest]: on the further benches, you know, Navi Mumbai and beyond.

03:32:14.000 --> 03:32:16.720
[Guest]: And one of the reasons I started realizing, why do they, why?

03:32:16.720 --> 03:32:19.800
[Guest]: Because they would always be late because the trains used to miss, etc. etc.

03:32:19.800 --> 03:32:22.920
[Guest]: And they would form their own little community, which was a community of people who would

03:32:22.920 --> 03:32:26.640
[Guest]: miss trains and then be late together, that if both of them miss, let's become friends

03:32:26.640 --> 03:32:29.880
[Guest]: because we are from the same, they could be, one could be a Bhandar, one could be a Vashi,

03:32:29.880 --> 03:32:33.520
[Guest]: but one couldn't be from Thane, but they would just be like, we are from the back and beyond

03:32:33.520 --> 03:32:34.520
[Guest]: of Bombay.

03:32:34.520 --> 03:32:35.520
[Guest]: So now this is one community.

03:32:35.520 --> 03:32:39.360
[Guest]: There was a South Bombay community always, you know, and these were the richest kids

03:32:39.360 --> 03:32:43.840
[Guest]: from like really rich families, they would have a language only that I wouldn't understand.

03:32:43.840 --> 03:32:47.360
[Guest]: You know, I was like, what language is this, what vocabulary is this, what's going on?

03:32:47.360 --> 03:32:52.160
[Guest]: They talk in ways that I would just be like, confused, like, what did you just say?

03:32:52.160 --> 03:32:53.160
[Guest]: What does that word mean?

03:32:53.160 --> 03:32:54.160
[Amit Varma]: Please explain.

03:32:54.160 --> 03:32:56.680
[Guest]: Like, for example, like internet language now that has happened, right?

03:32:56.680 --> 03:33:00.200
[Guest]: They were like the originate OGs of that language.

03:33:00.200 --> 03:33:06.720
[Guest]: These languages have started from these subcultures of like, you know, kids who, you know, baby,

03:33:06.720 --> 03:33:07.720
[Guest]: I don't know, man.

03:33:07.720 --> 03:33:11.040
[Guest]: When you see whatever you're seeing in like all of these Bollywood, young Bollywood actresses

03:33:11.040 --> 03:33:14.080
[Guest]: talk in the language, that was a language that they would communicate in.

03:33:14.080 --> 03:33:20.120
[Guest]: And then you would have the kids from, there were always the kids from Delhi, who would

03:33:20.120 --> 03:33:21.840
[Guest]: hate everyone from Bombay.

03:33:21.840 --> 03:33:24.640
[Guest]: And then you would have the kids of rest of India, who would hate everyone from Delhi

03:33:24.640 --> 03:33:27.280
[Guest]: and Bombay, and they all had their own batches.

03:33:27.280 --> 03:33:28.280
[Guest]: And I would see it.

03:33:28.280 --> 03:33:29.280
[Guest]: I would see it.

03:33:29.280 --> 03:33:33.680
[Guest]: You know, that there is which are the front benchers who are just kind of like, you know,

03:33:33.680 --> 03:33:38.200
[Guest]: the first people to try and like fit in and be like, mujhe zindagi mein jana, aagey badna

03:33:38.200 --> 03:33:41.520
[Guest]: hai, toh mujhe pata nahi, main aagey badunga nahi badunga, but aagey baith toh sakta hoon.

03:33:41.520 --> 03:33:44.880
[Guest]: You know, so that is their intent, whether they're topping or not topping is beyond the

03:33:44.880 --> 03:33:45.880
[Guest]: point.

03:33:45.880 --> 03:33:46.880
[Guest]: At least they're first somewhere.

03:33:46.880 --> 03:33:50.360
[Guest]: Then you had your backbenchers, who are there only for attendance, you know, or like, attendance

03:33:50.360 --> 03:33:51.880
[Guest]: de do, mein soh jaata hoon.

03:33:51.880 --> 03:33:56.960
[Guest]: That was my favorite people because they were at least they were so, you know, casual about

03:33:56.960 --> 03:33:57.960
[Guest]: what they wanted.

03:33:57.960 --> 03:34:00.800
[Guest]: Their ambition was, I want to just please give me attendance and don't disturb me.

03:34:00.800 --> 03:34:04.120
[Guest]: And then the middle benchers would always be people with existential crisis, like, you

03:34:04.120 --> 03:34:07.920
[Guest]: know, like people who just did not know where to fit, like, I don't know which group I'm

03:34:07.920 --> 03:34:08.920
[Guest]: in.

03:34:08.920 --> 03:34:09.920
[Guest]: So I'm going to sit on the middle bench.

03:34:09.920 --> 03:34:12.040
[Guest]: And you know, they're always there will be like four individuals sitting on the middle

03:34:12.040 --> 03:34:15.520
[Guest]: bench, who are always like, just don't know which group.

03:34:15.520 --> 03:34:18.080
[Guest]: So I'd see all these groups, I'll see all these communities, I'll see all these labels

03:34:18.080 --> 03:34:22.920
[Guest]: and I'm like, kya chal raha hai yahan par na, and individual come to me and you'll talk

03:34:22.920 --> 03:34:25.080
[Guest]: about like, this is what I'm going through, this is what I'm going through, but you're

03:34:25.080 --> 03:34:26.400
[Guest]: not talking to each other.

03:34:26.400 --> 03:34:32.120
[Guest]: So one day, randomly, absolutely, I remember it was it was it was raining on that it was

03:34:32.120 --> 03:34:33.120
[Guest]: a Sunday.

03:34:33.120 --> 03:34:37.120
[Guest]: And I used to teach on Saturday, Sundays because I was a weekend, weekdays par padha nahi sakta

03:34:37.120 --> 03:34:38.120
[Guest]: tha.

03:34:38.120 --> 03:34:40.440
[Guest]: Sunday ko aaye the sab log, kaafi bali shod thi us din par.

03:34:40.440 --> 03:34:44.640
[Guest]: So I saw that nobody's like, what 75% of the class was there.

03:34:44.640 --> 03:34:47.300
[Guest]: But I realized that not anybody's in the mood to study.

03:34:47.300 --> 03:34:50.480
[Guest]: So I was trying to talk and then they were all talking to each other.

03:34:50.480 --> 03:34:53.760
[Guest]: And then you know what, I was like, you know what, today, let's not pretend, you know,

03:34:53.760 --> 03:34:55.680
[Guest]: to study or whatever.

03:34:55.680 --> 03:35:00.240
[Guest]: I actually just wanted to, and it came out of curiosity also I said, I just want to kind

03:35:00.240 --> 03:35:03.000
[Guest]: of know because and let's just have an honest chat.

03:35:03.000 --> 03:35:06.600
[Guest]: I want to know that I speak to so many of you individually.

03:35:06.600 --> 03:35:09.560
[Guest]: And then you are able to tell me all the things that you're going through.

03:35:09.560 --> 03:35:13.080
[Guest]: But for whatever reason, I found out that you guys really judge each other, right?

03:35:13.080 --> 03:35:19.520
[Guest]: Like you don't, you all sit in your own subgroups and your own sub, you know, sections and just

03:35:19.520 --> 03:35:23.560
[Guest]: mingle with each other as if that's the only world that you can ever be in.

03:35:23.560 --> 03:35:27.600
[Guest]: I mean, you have that, like what I was doing in NID Gurukshetra, I was also like, you have

03:35:27.600 --> 03:35:33.120
[Guest]: the, you have the possibility and the opportunity to interact with people from all kinds of

03:35:33.120 --> 03:35:35.600
[Guest]: parts of like Bombay and the rest of India.

03:35:35.600 --> 03:35:36.880
[Guest]: Why are you not getting to know each other?

03:35:36.880 --> 03:35:40.000
[Guest]: Why are you not, why are you creating these cliques and like talking to each other?

03:35:40.000 --> 03:35:42.360
[Guest]: You know, people give you labels.

03:35:42.360 --> 03:35:46.240
[Guest]: You don't have to believe them, you know, and again, I, at this time, again, I don't

03:35:46.240 --> 03:35:47.440
[Guest]: have that understanding of gender.

03:35:47.440 --> 03:35:48.440
[Guest]: I don't have that understanding.

03:35:48.440 --> 03:35:53.760
[Guest]: I just have a little bit of experience from NID Gurukshetra, but I just found it very

03:35:53.760 --> 03:35:58.000
[Guest]: irritating that, you know, that and, and, and sad that, you know, that there are all

03:35:58.000 --> 03:36:05.720
[Guest]: of these human made ideas of who should be talking to whom people in the same class circles

03:36:05.720 --> 03:36:09.920
[Guest]: should stay with each other, same like interest should stay with each other.

03:36:09.920 --> 03:36:14.280
[Guest]: In fact, all my learning and all the, I mean, my favorite, my closest friend, my wife is

03:36:14.280 --> 03:36:15.400
[Guest]: from Assam.

03:36:15.400 --> 03:36:20.200
[Guest]: I would never have, till I was in Bahrain, I did not know, I'll be as honest in saying

03:36:20.200 --> 03:36:22.720
[Guest]: I did not even know where Assam was on the map of India.

03:36:22.720 --> 03:36:25.920
[Guest]: And now I'm married to a girl from Assam because of NID Gurukshetra.

03:36:25.920 --> 03:36:32.280
[Guest]: My closest friend is from, you know, a small village in, near Chennai in Tamil Nadu.

03:36:32.280 --> 03:36:37.520
[Guest]: And he's now in the US and working in Amazon and, and I mean, just all kinds of friends

03:36:37.520 --> 03:36:41.200
[Guest]: that I've had from that time have come from all kinds of different places of, you know,

03:36:41.200 --> 03:36:42.200
[Guest]: the country.

03:36:42.200 --> 03:36:45.520
[Guest]: It's like, it's made me richer as a person.

03:36:45.520 --> 03:36:49.440
[Guest]: And but I just feel like, you know, you guys are not using this opportunity.

03:36:49.440 --> 03:36:54.360
[Guest]: So I just said, like, you know, for today, let's just for one minute, I want you to just

03:36:54.360 --> 03:36:56.100
[Guest]: stop talking to each other.

03:36:56.100 --> 03:36:58.520
[Guest]: And for some reason, they stopped, which is just like, wait, what is happening?

03:36:58.520 --> 03:36:59.520
[Guest]: Why did you stop talking?

03:36:59.520 --> 03:37:04.040
[Guest]: I just said, and I wanted to think for a second, who are you beyond these labels that you have

03:37:04.040 --> 03:37:08.000
[Guest]: given yourself and what the society has given you?

03:37:08.000 --> 03:37:10.040
[Guest]: And then come and like, talk about it.

03:37:10.040 --> 03:37:11.440
[Guest]: What is your story beyond these labels?

03:37:11.440 --> 03:37:16.360
[Guest]: I said very casually, I had never thought that this is a big thing.

03:37:16.360 --> 03:37:19.800
[Guest]: And then, and then after this one minute, they all looked up, I was like, was there

03:37:19.800 --> 03:37:20.800
[Guest]: quiet for one minute?

03:37:20.800 --> 03:37:21.800
[Guest]: Clearly, they were introspective.

03:37:21.800 --> 03:37:23.280
[Guest]: So I said, who wants to talk?

03:37:23.280 --> 03:37:28.360
[Guest]: So one person first came up and like said something very like, well, I want to be a,

03:37:28.360 --> 03:37:33.920
[Guest]: you know, even things like I just chill over here, but I want to, I'm very, I want to,

03:37:33.920 --> 03:37:34.920
[Guest]: I used to be a cricketer.

03:37:34.920 --> 03:37:37.880
[Guest]: But then I had some injury, couldn't play, but I want to now get into sports broadcasting,

03:37:37.880 --> 03:37:38.880
[Guest]: you know, that's my ambition.

03:37:38.880 --> 03:37:42.920
[Guest]: I was like, well, sure, that's not what I went by Louisville stories, but thank you

03:37:42.920 --> 03:37:45.280
[Guest]: for coming and speaking up.

03:37:45.280 --> 03:37:47.520
[Guest]: For whatever it's worth, that boy is a sports broadcaster today.

03:37:47.520 --> 03:37:50.960
[Guest]: So you know, full marks for him.

03:37:50.960 --> 03:37:58.920
[Guest]: The second boy who came, he changed my life, man, like, he came and he's this lovely, lovely

03:37:58.920 --> 03:38:01.040
[Guest]: boy.

03:38:01.040 --> 03:38:03.080
[Guest]: And he happened to be gay.

03:38:03.080 --> 03:38:06.000
[Guest]: So he came and spoke to everyone and said he was very openly gay.

03:38:06.000 --> 03:38:11.960
[Guest]: He was like someone who would, you know, be very open and comfortable with his identity

03:38:11.960 --> 03:38:13.020
[Guest]: in college.

03:38:13.020 --> 03:38:18.320
[Guest]: So he came and said to everyone, he's like, well, you know me as someone who's like open

03:38:18.320 --> 03:38:22.640
[Guest]: about his sexuality and you're all like, I'm very comfortable.

03:38:22.640 --> 03:38:28.480
[Guest]: But what you don't know about me and the story that I have beyond this label is that every

03:38:28.480 --> 03:38:34.440
[Guest]: evening after college, on the way to home, I stop at a petrol pump.

03:38:34.440 --> 03:38:35.440
[Guest]: He has a bike.

03:38:35.440 --> 03:38:37.400
[Guest]: I used to go on the bike and stop at a petrol pump.

03:38:37.400 --> 03:38:44.120
[Guest]: And then I take out different clothes that I change into so that when I go home, I have

03:38:44.120 --> 03:38:46.760
[Guest]: to hide who I am in front of my parents.

03:38:46.760 --> 03:38:48.720
[Guest]: Because my one truth is that I'm gay.

03:38:48.720 --> 03:38:52.660
[Guest]: The second truth is my parents and I belong to a very religious family.

03:38:52.660 --> 03:38:58.240
[Guest]: And in my family, it is not okay for homosexuality is not okay.

03:38:58.240 --> 03:39:00.840
[Guest]: And in my religion, homosexuality is not okay.

03:39:00.840 --> 03:39:08.720
[Guest]: So while here I get to be who I am in front of the people I love the most, I have to hide

03:39:08.720 --> 03:39:10.960
[Guest]: a part of me.

03:39:10.960 --> 03:39:14.860
[Guest]: And and then he just burst into tears when he said this.

03:39:14.860 --> 03:39:22.040
[Guest]: And then suddenly that moment, that day, that boy changed the trajectory of my life.

03:39:22.040 --> 03:39:25.480
[Guest]: I think I wouldn't be overstating that.

03:39:25.480 --> 03:39:28.840
[Guest]: Because immediately after that, a wave of empathy happened in the classroom and somebody

03:39:28.840 --> 03:39:29.840
[Guest]: becomes vulnerable.

03:39:29.840 --> 03:39:30.840
[Guest]: And this is the thing about stories.

03:39:30.840 --> 03:39:33.240
[Guest]: And stories lead to other stories.

03:39:33.240 --> 03:39:34.360
[Guest]: Vulnerability is actually strength.

03:39:34.360 --> 03:39:40.960
[Guest]: If you are if you are sharing something, it allows people to to also let their guards

03:39:40.960 --> 03:39:48.720
[Guest]: down and share back, you know, human connection, human bonding, human friendships all happen

03:39:48.720 --> 03:39:53.580
[Guest]: because of this beautiful thing called empathy that comes after you share your stories.

03:39:53.580 --> 03:39:59.160
[Guest]: And this boy shared his story and everyone was like, you know, maybe I should do it too.

03:39:59.160 --> 03:40:04.080
[Guest]: So then there is a girl who came up and she's like, she's already crying.

03:40:04.080 --> 03:40:07.440
[Guest]: She's like, everyone thinks of me as a topper.

03:40:07.440 --> 03:40:10.440
[Guest]: And I've topped I've topped everywhere, you know, all know me.

03:40:10.440 --> 03:40:15.120
[Guest]: But I've topped in the college, I've topped in this district, I've been a school topper.

03:40:15.120 --> 03:40:16.120
[Guest]: But you don't know why I top.

03:40:16.120 --> 03:40:17.120
[Guest]: Her story is heartbreaking.

03:40:17.120 --> 03:40:26.320
[Guest]: She's like, when I was born, I very soon found out that my parents wanted a boy and but they

03:40:26.320 --> 03:40:27.720
[Guest]: got a girl.

03:40:27.720 --> 03:40:33.080
[Guest]: So for some reason, my parents and especially my father has never really given me love.

03:40:33.080 --> 03:40:37.960
[Guest]: She's like, I grew up not knowing what love is, but then kind of started recognizing that

03:40:37.960 --> 03:40:42.600
[Guest]: with other students in school, they would get a lot of love from the parents when they

03:40:42.600 --> 03:40:43.600
[Guest]: would do well in their exams.

03:40:43.600 --> 03:40:48.280
[Guest]: So I was like, what if I start doing well in my exams and I'll get love from my parents.

03:40:48.280 --> 03:40:51.920
[Guest]: She's like, from that time onwards, I'm in primary school, I've been topping everywhere.

03:40:51.920 --> 03:40:54.960
[Guest]: I've topped school, I've topped district, I've topped college.

03:40:54.960 --> 03:40:59.040
[Guest]: And every time I take my report card or my marks back to my father in the hope that he

03:40:59.040 --> 03:41:02.100
[Guest]: says I love you to me, but he still hasn't.

03:41:02.100 --> 03:41:03.580
[Guest]: And she's just in tears.

03:41:03.580 --> 03:41:07.200
[Guest]: And as all of us are listening, and we're like, man, what is going on?

03:41:07.200 --> 03:41:11.640
[Guest]: And just really beautiful, powerful stories started coming out.

03:41:11.640 --> 03:41:18.520
[Guest]: Very emotionally speaking about what the world thinks of them as and who they really are.

03:41:18.520 --> 03:41:25.140
[Guest]: And I realize at this point, man, there is there is something here that you know, something

03:41:25.140 --> 03:41:30.040
[Guest]: happened that that day and that evening that kind of totally it started as like a 12 o'clock

03:41:30.040 --> 03:41:31.040
[Guest]: session.

03:41:31.040 --> 03:41:35.600
[Guest]: And then it went on to like six o'clock, like six hours, we were just talking.

03:41:35.600 --> 03:41:38.200
[Guest]: Everybody and everybody heard everybody else.

03:41:38.200 --> 03:41:44.520
[Guest]: Everybody gave everybody the respect of like, time and emotion and empathy and hugs.

03:41:44.520 --> 03:41:46.960
[Guest]: There were so many hugs that day.

03:41:46.960 --> 03:41:48.600
[Guest]: And I was like, man, what has happened?

03:41:48.600 --> 03:41:52.400
[Guest]: And then you know, like your WhatsApp, I mean, I think the WhatsApp group after that gets

03:41:52.400 --> 03:41:57.240
[Guest]: lit and there's so many like, emojis and like hearts and whatnot and hugs.

03:41:57.240 --> 03:42:01.460
[Guest]: And I was like, there's something here, you know.

03:42:01.460 --> 03:42:04.880
[Guest]: And all the people who missed it then suddenly were like, man, you know, something happened

03:42:04.880 --> 03:42:08.680
[Guest]: yesterday, like everybody's talking about.

03:42:08.680 --> 03:42:11.640
[Guest]: And I realized that maybe there's something that I need to do with every batch, you know,

03:42:11.640 --> 03:42:12.840
[Guest]: this happened by mistake.

03:42:12.840 --> 03:42:18.360
[Guest]: But it just made me so it made me realize the power of stories, power of empathy.

03:42:18.360 --> 03:42:21.720
[Guest]: And I started I then called it started calling it the kindness project.

03:42:21.720 --> 03:42:25.480
[Guest]: And I said, like, this is a project, the next batch I gave from the very beginning, but

03:42:25.480 --> 03:42:28.760
[Guest]: here it happened by, you know, accident.

03:42:28.760 --> 03:42:31.880
[Guest]: I said that at the end of the semester, I'm going to give you a project.

03:42:31.880 --> 03:42:35.920
[Guest]: And it's called the kindness project, where I will ask you to do this exercise.

03:42:35.920 --> 03:42:39.160
[Guest]: You have the whole semester to think about it, you can start thinking from now.

03:42:39.160 --> 03:42:42.120
[Guest]: But I want you to tell me the story you have beyond the label that you have.

03:42:42.120 --> 03:42:46.920
[Guest]: And I will, I'd start my class by asking how many of you want to be journalists and like

03:42:46.920 --> 03:42:49.240
[Guest]: actually four of them would be like, I was like, great.

03:42:49.240 --> 03:42:53.160
[Guest]: Now, all of the rest of you also have a story, why are you here?

03:42:53.160 --> 03:42:56.400
[Guest]: And I want to know that story, but I will talk about it in the last class.

03:42:56.400 --> 03:43:00.600
[Guest]: And I said, I'd say that it's a marked project, but I give everybody full marks.

03:43:00.600 --> 03:43:05.200
[Guest]: And then every year, year on year on year, I mean, the kind of stories that came out,

03:43:05.200 --> 03:43:09.760
[Guest]: it is, it became, I mean, at that time, I did not know the terms for it, but became

03:43:09.760 --> 03:43:10.960
[Guest]: a safe space.

03:43:10.960 --> 03:43:16.360
[Guest]: It became a space where I'm so proud to say a student of mine decided that he's going

03:43:16.360 --> 03:43:21.320
[Guest]: to come out to the world in that space, because he didn't have an opportunity.

03:43:21.320 --> 03:43:24.200
[Guest]: And he just came, I remember, he's just the sweetest boy.

03:43:24.200 --> 03:43:28.520
[Guest]: And he came and he's like, said a few lines about himself and what he likes and how he's

03:43:28.520 --> 03:43:33.120
[Guest]: as a human being, what he likes, what he doesn't like, and he ended by saying, so I just want

03:43:33.120 --> 03:43:39.800
[Guest]: to say that I'm a boy who has brown hair, black eyes, crooked tooth.

03:43:39.800 --> 03:43:44.680
[Guest]: And I have, you know, and I like boys, and he just said something so beautiful.

03:43:44.680 --> 03:43:47.040
[Guest]: Everybody was like, wait, what did he just come out?

03:43:47.040 --> 03:43:51.280
[Guest]: And it was just hugs, hugs, hugs after the other was so beautiful.

03:43:51.280 --> 03:43:57.040
[Guest]: One of the most powerful, and I because I want to is just some one of my most inspiring

03:43:57.040 --> 03:44:04.040
[Guest]: I think stories, one of the most powerful stories happened with this boy who, who came

03:44:04.040 --> 03:44:08.760
[Guest]: to me and said, Sir, I don't know what to say in this, you know, class because I don't

03:44:08.760 --> 03:44:09.760
[Guest]: have a story.

03:44:09.760 --> 03:44:10.760
[Guest]: Everybody has a story.

03:44:10.760 --> 03:44:11.760
[Guest]: I don't have a story.

03:44:11.760 --> 03:44:12.760
[Guest]: So I don't know what to say.

03:44:12.760 --> 03:44:20.520
[Guest]: So now this boy, I'll tell you what this was, he's like the brightest, one of the brightest

03:44:20.520 --> 03:44:22.160
[Guest]: smartest kids I'd met.

03:44:22.160 --> 03:44:26.080
[Guest]: He was so bright, he would correct me in class, he'd just be like, that's wrong.

03:44:26.080 --> 03:44:27.200
[Guest]: This is the right thing.

03:44:27.200 --> 03:44:30.440
[Guest]: And I was just after one time I realized that you know a lot more than me.

03:44:30.440 --> 03:44:33.880
[Guest]: So he would ask me questions and say, you know, that you said this, but this happened

03:44:33.880 --> 03:44:34.880
[Guest]: in 1852.

03:44:34.880 --> 03:44:35.880
[Guest]: I said, I didn't know.

03:44:35.880 --> 03:44:42.400
[Guest]: I have not, I have not done, you know, not studied history or, or, or even for that matter,

03:44:42.400 --> 03:44:45.120
[Guest]: journalism or engineering, but I work in history.

03:44:45.120 --> 03:44:49.120
[Guest]: That's why I'm teaching you, you know, so, but if you have something, I want you to talk

03:44:49.120 --> 03:44:50.120
[Guest]: about it.

03:44:50.120 --> 03:44:51.880
[Guest]: So why don't you come and tell like what happened?

03:44:51.880 --> 03:44:55.760
[Guest]: So be my co-professor once is like asking me because I don't know, I'm very comfortable

03:44:55.760 --> 03:44:56.960
[Guest]: with saying, I don't know.

03:44:56.960 --> 03:45:01.200
[Guest]: So he started, so I just told him, I said, the only thing I know about you is that you're

03:45:01.200 --> 03:45:03.760
[Guest]: very well read, crazily well read.

03:45:03.760 --> 03:45:08.680
[Guest]: It is insane how I 2021, you know, so many things about like the world.

03:45:08.680 --> 03:45:10.280
[Guest]: Maybe there's a reason behind it.

03:45:10.280 --> 03:45:12.160
[Guest]: Maybe there's a story that I don't know.

03:45:12.160 --> 03:45:13.160
[Guest]: What is the story?

03:45:13.160 --> 03:45:17.200
[Guest]: And then his eyes just widened and he's like, Oh shit, I think I know what my story is.

03:45:17.200 --> 03:45:20.200
[Guest]: I said, great, then come and tell it in that class.

03:45:20.200 --> 03:45:23.920
[Guest]: So and I'd workshop with most of the kids, I would workshop these stories, then I'd be

03:45:23.920 --> 03:45:28.680
[Guest]: like, tell me what it is, and then we'll try to get you to dig deep and say something authentic.

03:45:28.680 --> 03:45:32.120
[Guest]: So he said, I said, he said, can I tell you, I was like, whatever you prefer, he's like,

03:45:32.120 --> 03:45:33.120
[Guest]: can I say it in the class directly?

03:45:33.120 --> 03:45:39.520
[Guest]: I said, sure, came to the class, he's like, so his story was, he's like, I've grown up

03:45:39.520 --> 03:45:44.200
[Guest]: in a very misogynistic setup, very patriarchal setup, he's like, my father is a patriarch

03:45:44.200 --> 03:45:45.200
[Guest]: of the house.

03:45:45.200 --> 03:45:51.920
[Guest]: And he's so patriarchal that when there is that I have a sister and my mother, even when

03:45:51.920 --> 03:45:55.840
[Guest]: he's watching TV, and the remote control is on the table in front of him, he will not

03:45:55.840 --> 03:45:57.200
[Guest]: pick it up himself.

03:45:57.200 --> 03:46:00.520
[Guest]: He will call my mother or my sister to come and pick it up for him.

03:46:00.520 --> 03:46:05.840
[Guest]: He's like, it used to be so irritating to me to see and so and I used to get so angry

03:46:05.840 --> 03:46:09.160
[Guest]: at the way he treats me and the way he treats my mother and there were different rules for

03:46:09.160 --> 03:46:10.160
[Guest]: all of us.

03:46:10.160 --> 03:46:12.760
[Guest]: My sister would not get to God, I'd get to God, my sister would not get a certain kind

03:46:12.760 --> 03:46:14.360
[Guest]: of money, I'd get a certain kind of money.

03:46:14.360 --> 03:46:17.320
[Guest]: If there's some work to be done, my sister, my mother were the ones who are being asked

03:46:17.320 --> 03:46:20.960
[Guest]: to do the work, whereas I wouldn't be asked to do it at all.

03:46:20.960 --> 03:46:26.320
[Guest]: And he's like, my anger turned into resentment.

03:46:26.320 --> 03:46:32.360
[Guest]: And when sometimes my father would hit me or hit any of us, there was a day where I

03:46:32.360 --> 03:46:34.240
[Guest]: almost hit him back.

03:46:34.240 --> 03:46:37.120
[Guest]: And then I realized that what am I doing?

03:46:37.120 --> 03:46:38.560
[Guest]: How can I do this?

03:46:38.560 --> 03:46:40.120
[Guest]: I'm turning into him.

03:46:40.120 --> 03:46:43.660
[Guest]: He's like that realization happened and I just got very scared.

03:46:43.660 --> 03:46:48.740
[Guest]: And I was like, there has to be a better way of, you know, giving back to my father without

03:46:48.740 --> 03:46:52.520
[Guest]: getting angry like him, because that's his thing, I don't want to be that boy.

03:46:52.520 --> 03:46:57.720
[Guest]: So he's like, every time I would fight with him and say that, you know, you can't do this,

03:46:57.720 --> 03:46:59.840
[Guest]: he would say, but this is the way the world works.

03:46:59.840 --> 03:47:00.840
[Guest]: This is the way the world works.

03:47:00.840 --> 03:47:08.120
[Guest]: This is the position of girls, boys do this, girls do that, women do this, men do that.

03:47:08.120 --> 03:47:11.140
[Guest]: Don't fight, you know, the way the world works.

03:47:11.140 --> 03:47:13.360
[Guest]: So he started, he just, he had Google.

03:47:13.360 --> 03:47:16.520
[Guest]: So he went online and he's just like, is this the way the world works?

03:47:16.520 --> 03:47:21.000
[Guest]: And then he discovered feminism and then he discovered feminist movements, then he discovered

03:47:21.000 --> 03:47:25.960
[Guest]: communities in different parts of the world, which did not have patriarchy, but matriarchy.

03:47:25.960 --> 03:47:28.680
[Guest]: So the next time his father would get angry and say, this is the way the world works,

03:47:28.680 --> 03:47:32.620
[Guest]: he would hit back with a fact and say, you know what, in Northeast India, the kids take

03:47:32.620 --> 03:47:37.040
[Guest]: the names of their mothers, you know, because it's not patriarchy, it's matriarchy, so it

03:47:37.040 --> 03:47:38.040
[Guest]: is not the way the world works.

03:47:38.040 --> 03:47:39.840
[Guest]: It might work in this household, but not everywhere.

03:47:39.840 --> 03:47:43.440
[Guest]: And his father would suddenly be stumped, he'd be like, wait, what?

03:47:43.440 --> 03:47:46.560
[Guest]: The next time he'd say, this is the way the world works, he'd be like, do you know about

03:47:46.560 --> 03:47:47.560
[Guest]: the feminist movement over here?

03:47:47.560 --> 03:47:48.560
[Guest]: And this is what happened here.

03:47:48.560 --> 03:47:50.840
[Guest]: In Africa, there's a tribe, there is.

03:47:50.840 --> 03:47:53.200
[Guest]: And he would always come back with facts.

03:47:53.200 --> 03:47:57.780
[Guest]: And the father would just be like, I don't know what to say to this, because he was not,

03:47:57.780 --> 03:48:02.400
[Guest]: you know, getting angry back at him, but talking in like, facts.

03:48:02.400 --> 03:48:06.760
[Guest]: And he's like, he's like, I started doing this so much that my father, instead of getting

03:48:06.760 --> 03:48:10.520
[Guest]: angry, would just like, go away, because he didn't know how to respond.

03:48:10.520 --> 03:48:14.680
[Guest]: And he's like, now it's reached a place where it's not that my father has suddenly become

03:48:14.680 --> 03:48:17.560
[Guest]: like a feminist, or, you know, is not patriarchal anymore.

03:48:17.560 --> 03:48:20.080
[Guest]: But when he wants the remote, he picks it himself.

03:48:20.080 --> 03:48:22.880
[Guest]: He's like, that's how much of a change it is.

03:48:22.880 --> 03:48:27.440
[Guest]: He doesn't ask my mother and my sister to, you know, get it.

03:48:27.440 --> 03:48:29.240
[Guest]: And I was like, man, he's like, that's my story.

03:48:29.240 --> 03:48:35.280
[Guest]: And I'm like, insane, like, just the fact that this boy has so many facts in him.

03:48:35.280 --> 03:48:37.360
[Guest]: Can you imagine the deep story behind that?

03:48:37.360 --> 03:48:43.120
[Guest]: And through these stories of these young people, I started recognising that I too have a story.

03:48:43.120 --> 03:48:50.480
[Guest]: Now, what I used to think, I used to understand, and that man thing, I never could unlock.

03:48:50.480 --> 03:48:55.840
[Guest]: But I unlocked like, why I care about films, I told you, it's my father and stuff.

03:48:55.840 --> 03:49:01.160
[Guest]: You know, a lot of it really, yeah, I just struggled, I knew there was something there,

03:49:01.160 --> 03:49:03.080
[Guest]: but I just did not know what it was.

03:49:03.080 --> 03:49:04.160
[Guest]: And then it was anxiety.

03:49:04.160 --> 03:49:05.160
[Guest]: And then it was therapy.

03:49:05.160 --> 03:49:12.280
[Guest]: And actually, how I also realised it is anxiety is one of my students, by the way, like, one

03:49:12.280 --> 03:49:14.600
[Guest]: of my students has spoken about anxiety in her session.

03:49:14.600 --> 03:49:17.360
[Guest]: So I called her one day and said, can I meet?

03:49:17.360 --> 03:49:19.560
[Guest]: You know, and you're very close, we're very thick.

03:49:19.560 --> 03:49:22.600
[Guest]: So I met her, you know, for lunch or something.

03:49:22.600 --> 03:49:26.920
[Guest]: And I said that, so you said you got anxiety, just tell me like, what all happens?

03:49:26.920 --> 03:49:27.920
[Guest]: What are the symptoms?

03:49:27.920 --> 03:49:29.280
[Guest]: Because she was taking therapy at that time.

03:49:29.280 --> 03:49:32.920
[Guest]: And then she told me like, this happens, this happens, this happens, this happens, this

03:49:32.920 --> 03:49:33.920
[Guest]: happens.

03:49:33.920 --> 03:49:36.080
[Guest]: And I was like, shit, all of this happens to me.

03:49:36.080 --> 03:49:39.200
[Guest]: So is this is what I have also anxiety.

03:49:39.200 --> 03:49:42.560
[Guest]: And she said, maybe it is, you should get it checked, and maybe you should go to a therapist.

03:49:42.560 --> 03:49:46.080
[Guest]: And that's where I was like, oh, shit, I can't go to a therapist, I'm a man.

03:49:46.080 --> 03:49:51.560
[Guest]: But yeah, I mean, it's in my students, it's in the conversations that I had.

03:49:51.560 --> 03:49:56.680
[Guest]: It's in the stories of others that I found my own, you know, so and then, of course,

03:49:56.680 --> 03:50:00.200
[Guest]: in clinical anxiety.

03:50:00.200 --> 03:50:04.480
[Amit Varma]: It's such a powerful thought and such a powerful frame, just, you know, just thinking about

03:50:04.480 --> 03:50:09.240
[Amit Varma]: what your story is, like what your roommate, in fact, said to you that you should be writing

03:50:09.240 --> 03:50:13.520
[Amit Varma]: on the side, writing on the side, writing on the side, and just taking that step back

03:50:13.520 --> 03:50:20.200
[Amit Varma]: and forcing you to think of it in terms of stories can, you know, at least make you self

03:50:20.200 --> 03:50:21.200
[Amit Varma]: reflect.

03:50:21.200 --> 03:50:26.520
[Amit Varma]: And I was struck by this talk that you gave, where there's this lovely line where you say,

03:50:26.520 --> 03:50:30.640
[Amit Varma]: stories unite us, labels divide us, right, and I'll link it from the show notes, of course.

03:50:30.640 --> 03:50:39.000
[Amit Varma]: But this is, you know, so particularly pertinent today, because, you know, I keep saying, it's

03:50:39.000 --> 03:50:43.600
[Amit Varma]: almost a cliche on my show where I quote Whitman and talk about how we contain multitudes.

03:50:43.600 --> 03:50:48.960
[Amit Varma]: But the thing is that a lot of the way, a lot of the discourse around us is so reductive,

03:50:48.960 --> 03:50:55.680
[Amit Varma]: where we'll reduce people down to labels and to narratives, that so and so is a liberal

03:50:55.680 --> 03:51:00.960
[Amit Varma]: and anti-national, this is so and so, that is so and so, everywhere you're putting narratives

03:51:00.960 --> 03:51:05.320
[Amit Varma]: of victimhood or narratives of oppression, looking at people only through that lens.

03:51:05.320 --> 03:51:10.040
[Amit Varma]: And that is just offensive to reduce people to one particular thing over which they had

03:51:10.040 --> 03:51:14.340
[Amit Varma]: no control, because it's often just an identity of birth.

03:51:14.340 --> 03:51:17.640
[Amit Varma]: Another theme I often talk about on the show is the difference between the abstract and

03:51:17.640 --> 03:51:18.640
[Amit Varma]: the concrete.

03:51:18.640 --> 03:51:23.080
[Amit Varma]: I did an episode with Anshul Malhotra, and she wrote a book on the memories of partition.

03:51:23.080 --> 03:51:28.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and in her episode, she spoke about how while collecting material for the book,

03:51:28.920 --> 03:51:33.000
[Amit Varma]: she was sitting with a family in Pakistan, who had come over after partition, and they

03:51:33.000 --> 03:51:34.360
[Amit Varma]: had suffered a lot.

03:51:34.360 --> 03:51:38.840
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, they were just full of rage when those memories came and they were saying,

03:51:38.840 --> 03:51:42.240
[Amit Varma]: Hindus are like this, Hindus are like that, Hindus are like this, Hindus are like that.

03:51:42.240 --> 03:51:45.160
[Amit Varma]: But then they suddenly noticed that they're talking to a Hindu and they said, lekin tum

03:51:45.160 --> 03:51:47.200
[Amit Varma]: nahi beti, tum achhi ho.

03:51:47.200 --> 03:51:52.400
[Amit Varma]: And that's the difference between an abstract notion in the head and a concrete person with

03:51:52.400 --> 03:51:55.400
[Amit Varma]: a story who's actually sitting in front of you.

03:51:55.400 --> 03:51:59.800
[Amit Varma]: And when I think about what divides us today, it is abstract things like all these labels

03:51:59.800 --> 03:52:01.520
[Amit Varma]: we pin on people.

03:52:01.520 --> 03:52:07.080
